{"title_page": "Dick Motz", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand Test cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name              = Dick Motz\n| image             = Dick_Motz.jpg\n| caption           = Dick Motz hitting a six against the MCC in 1960\u201361\n| fullname          = Richard Charles Motz\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|1940|1|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|04|29|1940|1|12|df=y}} \n| death_place       = Christchurch, New Zealand\n| international     = true\n| internationalspan = 1961\u20131969\n| country           = New Zealand\n| testcap           = 92\n| testdebutagainst  = South Africa\n| testdebutdate     = 8 December\n| testdebutyear     = 1961\n| lasttestdate      = 21 August\n| lasttestagainst   = England\n| lasttestyear      = 1969\n| batting           = Right-handed\n| bowling           = Right-arm fast\n| columns           = 2\n| column1           = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1          = 32\n| runs1             = 612\n| bat avg1          = 11.54\n| 100s/50s1         = 0/3\n| top score1        = 60\n| deliveries1       = 7,034\n| wickets1          = 100\n| bowl avg1         = 31.48\n| fivefor1          = 5\n| tenfor1           = 0\n| best bowling1     = 6/63\n| catches/stumpings1= 9/\u2013\n| column2           = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches2          = 142\n| runs2             = 3,494\n| bat avg2          = 17.12\n| 100s/50s2         = 1/13\n| top score2        = 103[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries2       = 29,773\n| wickets2          = 518\n| bowl avg2         = 22.71\n| fivefor2          = 24\n| tenfor2           = 4\n| best bowling2     = 8/61\n| catches/stumpings2= 41/\u2013\n| date              = 1 April\n| year              = 2017\n| source            = http://www.espncricinfo.com/newzealand/content/player/37733.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Richard Charles Motz''' (12 January 1940 \u2013 29 April 2007) was a New Zealand [[cricket]]er. A right-arm fast bowler and hard-hitting lower order batsman, Motz played 32 [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for the [[New Zealand cricket team]] between 1961 and 1969. He was the first bowler for New Zealand to take 100 wickets in [[Test cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/149420.html |title=Captain calypso |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMotz was born in [[Christchurch]]. He was educated at North New Brighton primary school and [[Linwood High School, Christchurch|Linwood High School]], excelling as an [[all-rounder]] at both.<ref name=\"Wisden CoY\"/> He also played rugby, tennis, badminton and golf. He played as full-back for the [[New Brighton, New Zealand|New Brighton]] rugby team for two years after leaving school.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>{{dead link|date=April 2012}}\n\n==Domestic career==\nHe played domestic cricket for [[Canterbury cricket team|Canterbury]], making his debut in the [[Plunket Shield]] in 1957, while still a schoolboy, taking 4 for 40 at his first outing.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22785.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Northern Districts, Plunket Shield 1957/58, from CricketArchive.</ref> He made his reputation as a hostile fast bowler, and a big-hitting lower order batsman.  \n\nHis best first-class performances were in New Zealand domestic cricket. He took 8 wickets for 61 runs against [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] in 1966\u201367,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/28/28575.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Wellington, Plunket Shield 1966/67, from CricketArchive.</ref> and scored 103 not out against [[Otago cricket team|Otago]] in 1967\u201368,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29225.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Otago, Plunket Shield 1967\u201368, from CricketArchive.</ref> making his only first-class century inside an hour.<ref name=\"independent\"/> On tour to [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 1967\u201368|Australia in 1967\u201368]], he scored 94 against [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]],<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29146.html Scorecard], South Australia v New Zealanders, November 1967, from CricketArchive.</ref> including 76 runs from boundaries (6 sixes and 10 fours).<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\n==International career==\nHe was one of five New Zealand players and seven [[South African cricket team|South Africans]] to make their Test debut in the 1st Test at [[Durban]] in December 1961.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1961-62/NZ_IN_RSA/NZ_RSA_T1_08-12DEC1961.html Scorecard], South Africa v New Zealand, 1st Test, 1961\u201362, from [[Cricinfo]].</ref>  He took 81 wickets on the tour, at a bowling average of 19, including 19 wickets in the five Tests.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nHe took five wickets in an innings five times in Tests, once in England and twice at home against each of India and West Indies. He was also a handy lower-order batsman, scoring three Test half-centuries, all at home against England. \n\nIn 1968, he was the first bowler to be banned from bowling in a Test due to running on the [[wicket]].<ref name=\"independent\"/><ref>[http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/newzealand/content/story/292849.html Former fast bowler Dick Motz dies], [[Cricinfo]], 29 April 2007.</ref> In his last Test, the third Test against [[England cricket team|England]] at [[The Oval]] in August 1969,<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1969/NZ_IN_ENG/NZ_ENG_T3_21-26AUG1969.html Scorecard], England v New Zealand, 3rd Test, 1969, from [[Cricinfo]].</ref> Motz became the first New Zealand [[Bowler (cricket)|bowler]] to take 100 [[Test cricket|Test]] [[wicket]]s when he trapped [[Phil Sharpe (cricketer)|Phil Sharpe]] [[leg before wicket]] (his only wicket of the match).<ref name=\"telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;jsessionid=GLMV0NTQODHKJQFIQMGSFFWAVCBQWIV0?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/news/2007/05/07/db0702.xml Obituary], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 May 2007</ref>\n\n==Trivia==\nHe was ''New Zealand Cricket Almanack'' Player of the Year in 1961, ''South African Cricket Annual'' Cricketer of the Year in 1962, and a [[Wisden Cricketer of the Year]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Wisden CoY\">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154878.html | title=1966 Wisden Cricketers of the Year \u2013 Dick Motz|author= [[R. T. Brittenden]]| publisher=ESPNcricinfo | work=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]] | accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/1/1172/1172.html Profile] from CricketArchive.</ref>\n\n==After cricket==\nMotz's playing career ended at the age of 29, after he was found to have a displaced [[vertebra]] \u2013 indeed, he had been playing with a bad back for over a year.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> After his retirement from cricket, he became a taxi driver. He also ran a sports business, and then ran a pub in [[Timaru]].  In later years, he put on considerable weight, ending over 30 stone.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\nHe was inducted to the [[New Zealand Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1997.\n\nHe was married twice. His first marriage, to cricketer Loretta Todd, ended in divorce in 1987.  They had a son and two daughters.  His son, Wayne, was murdered in 1989.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>  He remarried, to Josephine Cole.\n\nHe died in [[Christchurch]].<ref name=\"independent\">[http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2530749.ece   Obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001082611/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2530749.ece |date=1 October 2007 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 11 May 2007</ref><ref>{{cite news | first= | last=AAP | coauthors= | title=NZ cricketer Dick Motz dead at 67 |date=30 April 2007 | publisher= | url =http://www.smh.com.au/news/Sport/NZ-cricketer-Dick-Motz-dead-at-67/2007/04/30/1177788004373.html | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-04-29 | language = }}</ref> He was found dead at his home by his former captain, [[Graham Dowling]].   He was survived by his two daughters from his first marriage.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=37733}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motz, Dick}}\n[[Category:Canterbury cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby union players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Linwood College]]\n[[Category:D. H. Robins' XI cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand Test cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name              = Dick Motz\n| image             = Dick_Motz.jpg\n| caption           = Dick Motz hitting a six against the MCC in 1960-61\n| fullname          = Richard Charles Motz\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|1940|1|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|04|29|1940|1|12|df=y}} \n| death_place       = Christchurch, New Zealand\n| international     = true\n| internationalspan = 1961\u20131969\n| country           = New Zealand\n| testcap           = 92\n| testdebutagainst  = South Africa\n| testdebutdate     = 8 December\n| testdebutyear     = 1961\n| lasttestdate      = 21 August\n| lasttestagainst   = England\n| lasttestyear      = 1969\n| batting           = Right-handed\n| bowling           = Right-arm fast\n| columns           = 2\n| column1           = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1          = 32\n| runs1             = 612\n| bat avg1          = 11.54\n| 100s/50s1         = 0/3\n| top score1        = 60\n| deliveries1       = 7,034\n| wickets1          = 100\n| bowl avg1         = 31.48\n| fivefor1          = 5\n| tenfor1           = 0\n| best bowling1     = 6/63\n| catches/stumpings1= 9/\u2013\n| column2           = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches2          = 142\n| runs2             = 3,494\n| bat avg2          = 17.12\n| 100s/50s2         = 1/13\n| top score2        = 103[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries2       = 29,773\n| wickets2          = 518\n| bowl avg2         = 22.71\n| fivefor2          = 24\n| tenfor2           = 4\n| best bowling2     = 8/61\n| catches/stumpings2= 41/\u2013\n| date              = 1 April\n| year              = 2017\n| source            = http://www.espncricinfo.com/newzealand/content/player/37733.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Richard Charles Motz''' (12 January 1940 \u2013 29 April 2007) was a New Zealand [[cricket]]er. A right-arm fast bowler and hard-hitting lower order batsman, Motz played 32 [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for the [[New Zealand cricket team]] between 1961 and 1969. He was the first bowler for New Zealand to take 100 wickets in [[Test cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/149420.html |title=Captain calypso |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMotz was born in [[Christchurch]]. He was educated at North New Brighton primary school and [[Linwood High School, Christchurch|Linwood High School]], excelling as an [[all-rounder]] at both.<ref name=\"Wisden CoY\"/> He also played rugby, tennis, badminton and golf. He played as full-back for the [[New Brighton, New Zealand|New Brighton]] rugby team for two years after leaving school.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>{{dead link|date=April 2012}}\n\n==Domestic career==\nHe played domestic cricket for [[Canterbury cricket team|Canterbury]], making his debut in the [[Plunket Shield]] in 1957, while still a schoolboy, taking 4 for 40 at his first outing.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22785.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Northern Districts, Plunket Shield 1957/58, from CricketArchive.</ref> He made his reputation as a hostile fast bowler, and a big-hitting lower order batsman.  \n\nHis best first-class performances were in New Zealand domestic cricket. He took 8 wickets for 61 runs against [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] in 1966-67,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/28/28575.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Wellington, Plunket Shield 1966/67, from CricketArchive.</ref> and scored 103 not out against [[Otago cricket team|Otago]] in 1967-68,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29225.html Scorecard], Canterbury v Otago, Plunket Shield 1967-68, from CricketArchive.</ref> making his only first-class century inside an hour.<ref name=\"independent\"/> On tour to [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 1967\u201368|Australia in 1967-68]], he scored 94 against [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]],<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29146.html Scorecard], South Australia v New Zealanders, November 1967, from CricketArchive.</ref> including 76 runs from boundaries (6 sixes and 10 fours).<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\n==International career==\nHe was one of five New Zealand players and seven [[South African cricket team|South Africans]] to make their Test debut in the 1st Test at [[Durban]] in December 1961.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1961-62/NZ_IN_RSA/NZ_RSA_T1_08-12DEC1961.html Scorecard], South Africa v New Zealand, 1st Test, 1961-62, from [[Cricinfo]].</ref>  He took 81 wickets on the tour, at a bowling average of 19, including 19 wickets in the five Tests.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nHe took five wickets in an innings five times in Tests, once in England and twice at home against each of India and West Indies. He was also a handy lower-order batsman, scoring three Test half-centuries, all at home against England. \n\nIn 1968, he was the first bowler to be banned from bowling in a Test due to running on the [[wicket]].<ref name=\"independent\"/><ref>[http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/newzealand/content/story/292849.html Former fast bowler Dick Motz dies], [[Cricinfo]], 29 April 2007.</ref> In his last Test, the third Test against [[England cricket team|England]] at [[The Oval]] in August 1969,<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1960S/1969/NZ_IN_ENG/NZ_ENG_T3_21-26AUG1969.html Scorecard], England v New Zealand, 3rd Test, 1969, from [[Cricinfo]].</ref> Motz became the first New Zealand [[Bowler (cricket)|bowler]] to take 100 [[Test cricket|Test]] [[wicket]]s when he trapped [[Phil Sharpe (cricketer)|Phil Sharpe]] [[leg before wicket]] (his only wicket of the match).<ref name=\"telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;jsessionid=GLMV0NTQODHKJQFIQMGSFFWAVCBQWIV0?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/news/2007/05/07/db0702.xml Obituary], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 May 2007</ref>\n\n==Trivia==\nHe was ''New Zealand Cricket Almanack'' Player of the Year in 1961, ''South African Cricket Annual'' Cricketer of the Year in 1962, and a [[Wisden Cricketer of the Year]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Wisden CoY\">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/154878.html | title=1966 Wisden Cricketers of the Year - Dick Motz|author= [[R. T. Brittenden]]| publisher=ESPNcricinfo | work=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]] | accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/1/1172/1172.html Profile] from CricketArchive.</ref>\n\n==After cricket==\nMotz's playing career ended at the age of 29, after he was found to have a displaced [[vertebra]] \u2013 indeed, he had been playing with a bad back for over a year.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> After his retirement from cricket, he became a taxi driver. He also ran a sports business, and then ran a pub in [[Timaru]].  In later years, he put on considerable weight, ending over 30 stone.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\nHe was inducted to the [[New Zealand Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1997.\n\nHe was married twice. His first marriage, to cricketer Loretta Todd, ended in divorce in 1987.  They had a son and two daughters.  His son, Wayne, was murdered in 1989.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>  He remarried, to Josephine Cole.\n\nHe died in [[Christchurch]].<ref name=\"independent\">[http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2530749.ece   Obituary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001082611/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2530749.ece |date=1 October 2007 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 11 May 2007</ref><ref>{{cite news | first= | last=AAP | coauthors= | title=NZ cricketer Dick Motz dead at 67 |date=30 April 2007 | publisher= | url =http://www.smh.com.au/news/Sport/NZ-cricketer-Dick-Motz-dead-at-67/2007/04/30/1177788004373.html | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-04-29 | language = }}</ref> He was found dead at his home by his former captain, [[Graham Dowling]].   He was survived by his two daughters from his first marriage.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=37733}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motz, Dick}}\n[[Category:Canterbury cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby union players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Linwood College]]\n[[Category:D. H. Robins' XI cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dick_Motz"}
{"title_page": "The ACE Academy", "text_new": "{{Redirect-distinguish|Tipton Grammar School|Tupton Hall School}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name         = The ACE Academy\n| logo        =\n| logo_size         =\n| coordinates  = {{coord|52.53215|-2.04972|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        =\n| established =\n| closed       =\n| religious_affiliation     = \n| president    =\n| head_label   =\n| head         = \n| r_head       =\n| chair_label  =\n| chair        =\n| founder      =\n| specialist   =\n| address       = Alexandra Road\n| city         = [[Tipton]]\n| county       = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n| country      = England\n| postcode     = DY4 7NR\n| local_authority          =\n| ofsted       = yes\n| dfeno        = 333/4001\n| urn          = 139328\n| staff        =\n| students   = 1371\n| gender       = Co-educational\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 16\n| houses       =\n| publication  =\n| free_label_1 = Former names\n| free_1       = Tipton County Grammar School\n                      Alexandra High School and Sixth Form Centre\n| free_label_2 =\n| free_2       =\n| colours      = Blue, black, silver, yellow and green\n| free_3       =\n| website      = {{URL|1=http://www.acesch.co.uk|2=The ACE Academy}}\n}}\n\n'''The ACE Academy''' ('''Alexandra College of Enterprise'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acesch.co.uk/about-us/welcome|website=The ACE Academy|accessdate=3 February 2016|quote=ACE stands for \u2018Alexandra College of Enterprise\u2019}}</ref>) is a secondary school and [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Tipton]], West Midlands, England.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe ACE Academy mainly serves children aged 11\u201316 years for KS3 and 16\u201318 for Sixth Form. Pupils who mainly live in the [[Great Bridge, West Midlands|Great Bridge]], [[Tibbington]], [[Horseley Heath]] and [[Tipton Green]] areas of the town attend the school.\n\nIt is situated on Alexandra Road (B4517) towards [[Toll End]] (and [[West Bromwich]]) and near the crossroads with Church Lane (B4163) and the fire station. It is about a mile from the [[A41 road|A41]]/[[A461 road|A461]] roundabout at Great Bridge, and about a half-mile north of [[Dudley Port railway station]].\n\n==History==\n===Grammar school===\nThe school was opened in 1927 as Tipton Central School. It served the local area as a grammar school for boys and girls, and its title was soon altered to '''Tipton County Grammar School''', situated on Alexandra Road. It was administered by the South-West Divisional Executive of Staffordshire Education Committee (based in [[Dudley]]), then West Bromwich Education Committee with around 700 boys and girls. The buildings were expanded in 1962 to include a new school hall, kitchen, dining hall, swimming pool, gymnasium and Science classrooms. This building was demolished in the mid-1990s following further extensions to the site.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk/brief-history-of-tipton.php |title=Brief History of Tipton |publisher=Tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk |accessdate=26 November 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120915100741/http://www.tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk/brief-history-of-tipton.php |archivedate=15 September 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Comprehensive===\nTipton Grammar merged with nearby [[Park Lane Secondary School, Tipton|Park Lane Secondary School]] in Queens Road in September 1969 and became a comprehensive school. It took the title of '''Alexandra High School''' at this time. 'O' Level and 'A' Level pupils were educated at the original site in Alexandra Road, while the younger pupils mostly attended the Park Lane buildings (which dated back to 1904).\n\nNew buildings were added to the Alexandra Road site at the beginning of the 1980s, giving younger pupils a chance to have three days a week at the main site, although they still used the Park Lane site twice a week until it closed in July 1990, being demolished the following year. Since September 1990, the school has also lost its popularity with children living in the [[Tipton Green]] area of the town, with a significant percentage of children in this area selecting [[Dormston School]] or [[High Arcal School]] in [[Sedgley]] as their destination for secondary school following the reduction in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Dudley|Dudley borough's]] secondary transfer age from 12 to 11, bringing it into line with Sandwell and the rest of the region.\n\nA new sixth form centre was built in 1995 and the early 1980s extensions were demolished in 2011 to make way for new classrooms.\n\n===Academy===\nThe school converted to academy status on 1 March 2013, and was reopened by [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] as The ACE Academy. However, after it opened, it was rated \"Inadequate\" by ofsted. Thus, it was closed down and renamed Q3 Academy Tipton as part of the Q3 Multi Academies trust. (Q3MAT)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2013/03/28/countess-of-wessex-sophie-launches-77m-west-bromwich-college/28089320/ |title=Countess of Wessex Sophie launches \u00a377m West Bromwich college \" Express & Star |work=Express & Star |date=28 March 2013 |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> .<ref>{{cite web |author=Web Optic |url=http://www.acesch.co.uk/page/about-us/17 |title=About Us \u2013 Alexandra School of Enterprise |publisher=Acesch.co.uk |accessdate=18 August 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019053654/http://www.acesch.co.uk/page/about-us/17 |archivedate=19 October 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Academic performance==\nIn 2006, 25% of [[GCSE]] students attained 5 grades at 'C' or above. This placed the school at 13th out of 18 schools in [[Sandwell]]. By 2009, it had progressed further with 38% of pupils achieving similar results, placing it as joint eighth of the 17 schools in the borough.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/09/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/333_gcse_lea.stm]</ref> This is well under the England average, similar to most schools in Sandwell: only two schools get GCSE results above average.\n\nAt [[A level]], results are low, similar again to most schools in Sandwell that offer A levels.\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n===Alexandra High School and Sixth Form Centre===\n* [[David Burrows (footballer)|David Burrows]], former [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] player\n* [[Shafiq Rasul]], [[Asif Iqbal (Guantanamo captive 87)|Asif Iqbal]] and [[Ruhal Ahmed]], incarcerated in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] after being accused of fighting for the [[Taliban]] in Afghanistan; later released without charge\n\n===Tipton Grammar School===\n* [[Philip Bradbourn]] OBE, Conservative MEP since 1999 for the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]]\n* [[Joe Mayo]], former [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] footballer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/Sport/JOE-MAYO-TWICE-TO-THE-ORIENT-2.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721213157/http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/Sport/JOE-MAYO-TWICE-TO-THE-ORIENT-2.htm |url-status = dead|archive-date=21 July 2012 |title=JOE MAYO \u2013 TWICE TO THE ORIENT! &#124; Sport |publisher=Black Country Bugle |date=25 May 1951 |accessdate=18 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.acesch.co.uk/ School's website]\n\n{{Schools in Sandwell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ACE Academy}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1927]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Sandwell]]\n[[Category:Academies in Sandwell]]\n[[Category:Tipton]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect-distinguish|Tipton Grammar School|Tupton Hall School}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name         = The ACE Academy\n| logo        =\n| logo_size         =\n| coordinates  = {{coord|52.53215|-2.04972|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        =\n| established =\n| closed       =\n| religious_affiliation     = \n| president    =\n| head_label   =\n| head         = \n| r_head       =\n| chair_label  =\n| chair        =\n| founder      =\n| specialist   =\n| address       = Alexandra Road\n| city         = [[Tipton]]\n| county       = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n| country      = England\n| postcode     = DY4 7NR\n| local_authority          =\n| ofsted       = yes\n| dfeno        = 333/4001\n| urn          = 139328\n| staff        =\n| students   = 1371\n| gender       = Co-educational\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 16\n| houses       =\n| publication  =\n| free_label_1 = Former names\n| free_1       = Tipton County Grammar School\n                      Alexandra High School and Sixth Form Centre\n| free_label_2 =\n| free_2       =\n| colours      = Blue, black, silver, yellow and green\n| free_3       =\n| website      = {{URL|1=http://www.acesch.co.uk|2=The ACE Academy}}\n}}\n\n'''The ACE Academy''' ('''Alexandra College of Enterprise'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acesch.co.uk/about-us/welcome|website=The ACE Academy|accessdate=3 February 2016|quote=ACE stands for \u2018Alexandra College of Enterprise\u2019}}</ref>) is a secondary school and [[sixth form]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]], located in [[Tipton]], West Midlands, England.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe ACE Academy mainly serves children aged 11\u201316 years for KS3 and 16\u201318 for Sixth Form. Pupils who mainly live in the [[Great Bridge, West Midlands|Great Bridge]], [[Tibbington]], [[Horseley Heath]] and [[Tipton Green]] areas of the town attend the school.\n\nIt is situated on Alexandra Road (B4517) towards [[Toll End]] (and [[West Bromwich]]) and near the crossroads with Church Lane (B4163) and the fire station. It is about a mile from the [[A41 road|A41]]/[[A461 road|A461]] roundabout at Great Bridge, and about a half-mile north of [[Dudley Port railway station]].\n\n==History==\n===Grammar school===\nThe school was opened in 1927 as Tipton Central School. It served the local area as a grammar school for boys and girls, and its title was soon altered to '''Tipton County Grammar School''', situated on Alexandra Road. It was administered by the South-West Divisional Executive of Staffordshire Education Committee (based in [[Dudley]]), then West Bromwich Education Committee with around 700 boys and girls. The buildings were expanded in 1962 to include a new school hall, kitchen, dining hall, swimming pool, gymnasium and Science classrooms. This building was demolished in the mid-1990s following further extensions to the site.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk/brief-history-of-tipton.php |title=Brief History of Tipton |publisher=Tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk |accessdate=26 November 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120915100741/http://www.tiptoncivicsociety.co.uk/brief-history-of-tipton.php |archivedate=15 September 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Comprehensive===\nTipton Grammar merged with nearby [[Park Lane Secondary School, Tipton|Park Lane Secondary School]] in Queens Road in September 1969 and became a comprehensive school. It took the title of '''Alexandra High School''' at this time. 'O' Level and 'A' Level pupils were educated at the original site in Alexandra Road, while the younger pupils mostly attended the Park Lane buildings (which dated back to 1904).\n\nNew buildings were added to the Alexandra Road site at the beginning of the 1980s, giving younger pupils a chance to have three days a week at the main site, although they still used the Park Lane site twice a week until it closed in July 1990, being demolished the following year. Since September 1990, the school has also lost its popularity with children living in the [[Tipton Green]] area of the town, with a significant percentage of children in this area selecting [[Dormston School]] or [[High Arcal School]] in [[Sedgley]] as their destination for secondary school following the reduction in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Dudley|Dudley borough's]] secondary transfer age from 12 to 11, bringing it into line with Sandwell and the rest of the region.\n\nA new sixth form centre was built in 1995 and the early 1980s extensions were demolished in 2011 to make way for new classrooms.\n\n===Academy===\nThe school converted to academy status on 1 March 2013, and was reopened by [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] as The ACE Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2013/03/28/countess-of-wessex-sophie-launches-77m-west-bromwich-college/28089320/ |title=Countess of Wessex Sophie launches \u00a377m West Bromwich college \" Express & Star |work=Express & Star |date=28 March 2013 |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> The school is sponsored by the [[University of Wolverhampton]]s Education Central Multi Academy Trust.<ref>{{cite web |author=Web Optic |url=http://www.acesch.co.uk/page/about-us/17 |title=About Us \u2013 Alexandra School of Enterprise |publisher=Acesch.co.uk |accessdate=18 August 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019053654/http://www.acesch.co.uk/page/about-us/17 |archivedate=19 October 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Academic performance==\nIn 2006, 25% of [[GCSE]] students attained 5 grades at 'C' or above. This placed the school at 13th out of 18 schools in [[Sandwell]]. By 2009, it had progressed further with 38% of pupils achieving similar results, placing it as joint eighth of the 17 schools in the borough.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/09/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/333_gcse_lea.stm]</ref> This is well under the England average, similar to most schools in Sandwell: only two schools get GCSE results above average.\n\nAt [[A level]], results are low, similar again to most schools in Sandwell that offer A levels.\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n===Alexandra High School and Sixth Form Centre===\n* [[David Burrows (footballer)|David Burrows]], former [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] player\n* [[Shafiq Rasul]], [[Asif Iqbal (Guantanamo captive 87)|Asif Iqbal]] and [[Ruhal Ahmed]], incarcerated in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] after being accused of fighting for the [[Taliban]] in Afghanistan; later released without charge\n\n===Tipton Grammar School===\n* [[Philip Bradbourn]] OBE, Conservative MEP since 1999 for the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]]\n* [[Joe Mayo]], former [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] footballer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/Sport/JOE-MAYO-TWICE-TO-THE-ORIENT-2.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721213157/http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/Sport/JOE-MAYO-TWICE-TO-THE-ORIENT-2.htm |url-status = dead|archive-date=21 July 2012 |title=JOE MAYO \u2013 TWICE TO THE ORIENT! &#124; Sport |publisher=Black Country Bugle |date=25 May 1951 |accessdate=18 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.acesch.co.uk/ School's website]\n\n{{Schools in Sandwell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ACE Academy}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1927]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Sandwell]]\n[[Category:Academies in Sandwell]]\n[[Category:Tipton]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:aa80:ee01:1502:205f:e1d3:b198", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAcademy)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_ACE_Academy"}
