     =\n| pfr                 =\n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Chase Young\n|school=Ohio State Buckeyes\n|currentnumber=2\n|major=[[Criminology]]\n|currentposition=[[Defensive end]]\n|class=Junior\n|bowlgames=\n* [[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)]]\n* [[2019 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=5\n|weight_lb=265\n|highschool=[[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n|pastschools=\n* [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4241986\n|highlights=\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* First-team All-Big Ten ([[2019 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2019]])\n* Second-team All-Big Ten ([[2018 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2018]])\n* ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Walter Camp Award]] National Player of the Week\n}}\n'''Chase Young''' (born April 14, 1999) is an [[American football]] [[defensive end]] for the <!--[[]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).-->[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State Buckeyes]]. As a junior in 2019, Young broke Ohio State's single-season sack record with 16.5, winning him several honors such as the [[Chuck Bednarik Award]], [[Ted Hendricks Award]], and [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]], as well as being named a unanimous [[All-America]]n and [[Heisman Trophy]] finalist.\n\n==Early life==\nChase Young was born in [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]] on April 14, 1999.<ref name=\"OSUBio\">{{cite web |title=Chase Young - Football |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |access-date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213232426/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Walter Camp National Defensive PoW \u2026 Again! |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-walter-camp-national-defensive-pow-again/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Young first attended [[St. Vincent Pallotti High School]] in [[Laurel, Maryland]], starting at quarterback and outside linebacker as a freshman in 2013 before switching to defensive end later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=The Chase for Young is on |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704181213/http://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899 |archive-date=July 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Santoliquito |first1=Joseph |title=Eagles fan Chase Young may soon become an Eagles\u2019 nightmare |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/chase-young-philadelphia-eagles-fan-ohio-state-maxwell-awards-nfl-draft-washington-redskins/ |website=Philly Voice |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2014, he and the team won the MIAA C Conference championship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Worgo |first1=Tom |title=Pallotti football relies on running game, defense to defeat AACS for MIAA C Conference title |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/laurel/ph-ll-pallott-annapolisareachristianschool-footballi-story.html |website=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> He transferred to [[DeMatha Catholic High School]] in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]] in 2015, where he had 118 tackles with 19 sacks as a senior the following year, which helped the team go undefeated and win the state championship.<ref name=\"SportingNews\">{{cite web |last1=Bender |first1=Bill |title=The making of Chase Young: How an athletic freak at Ohio State became the best player in the NFL Draft |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |website=Sporting News |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303052838/https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young also played basketball for both schools, where he was a DeMatha teammate and friend of future [[NBA]] player [[Markelle Fultz]], who was [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|selected first overall]] in the [[2017 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young chasing top draft pick of HS basketball teammate Markelle Fultz |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ohio-state-de-chase-young-chasing-top-draft-pick-of-high-school-basketball-teammate-markelle-fultz-024346344.html |website=Yahoo Sports |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228192302/https://sports.yahoo.com/ohio-state-de-chase-young-chasing-top-draft-pick-of-high-school-basketball-teammate-markelle-fultz-024346344.html |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was also a member of the school's choir, playing the piano, saxophone, and violin.<ref name=\"Dayton\">{{cite web |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Tom |title=Archdeacon: Ohio State\u2019s Young a menace in mauling of Badgers |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |website=Dayton Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, he was considered one of the best high school football players in the nation, where he was included on the [[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team]], as well as being named as the all-metropolitan defensive football player of the year by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Football Defense: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202012103/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Fall All-Met |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626021033/https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also invited to the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]], playing for the East team.<ref>{{cite web |title=DeMatha defensive end Chase Young solidifies standing with Army All-American selection |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221142657/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection/ |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young received scholarship offers from over 40 colleges before committing to [[Ohio State University]] in July 2016, choosing them over other schools such as [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park|Maryland]] due to their approach that he felt was more \"family-oriented\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connors |first1=Ryan |title=5-star DE Chase Young commits to Ohio State: Maryland football misses out on top local prospect |url=https://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |website=testudotimes.com |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030181151/http://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lombardi |first1=Matt |title=Chase Young Explains Why He Chose Ohio State Over Alabama |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/chase-young-explains-why-he-chose-ohio-state-over-alabama |website=The Spun |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nPlaying for the [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State Buckeyes]], Young recorded four sacks as a freshman in 2017.<ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Ludwiczak |first1=Brett |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young is ready to build off a breakout sophomore season |url=https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |website=Land Grant Holy Land |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=January 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191344/https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> During his sophomore season in 2018, Young sprained both ankles but still managed to record 10.5 sacks on the season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haas-Hill |first1=Colin |title=K.J. Hill, Chase Young and J.K. Dobbins Could Break or Tie Ohio State Individual Records in 2019 |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191351/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He came on strong after fellow defensive end [[Nick Bosa]] was injured in the latter part of the season, recording three sacks in the [[2018 Big Ten Football Championship Game]] against [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]].<ref name=\"Sophomore\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowland |first1=Kyle |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young wants to be the best |url=https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |website=[[Toledo Blade]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510205559/https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring his junior season in 2019, Young tied Ohio State school records for single-game sacks (four) and tackles for loss (five) in a win against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Planos |first1=Josh |title=Ohio State's Chase Young Is Playing Like A Heisman Contender |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116060500/https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heisman Watch: Chase Young Crashes Quarterback Party |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |website=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031175718/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the game, Ohio State head coach [[Ryan Day (American football)|Ryan Day]] called him the most dominant player in all of college football.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hummer |first1=Chris |title=Chase Young is on a historic, Heisman-worthy pace |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-Heisman-Trophy-Ohio-State-football-2020-NFL-Draft-137613670/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Young was suspended for two games by the [[NCAA]] for getting an unauthorized loan from a family friend to allegedly help his girlfriend attend the [[2019 Rose Bowl]], which he later repaid in full.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bumbaca |first1=Chris |title=Ohio State Buckeyes' Chase Young expected to serve four-game suspension, per reports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=NCAA rules Ohio State's Chase Young to miss 1 more game |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113185829/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young recorded three sacks against Penn State in his first game after returning.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/> He ended the season with 16.5 sacks, 46 tackles, six forced fumbles, three passes batted, as well as a blocked kick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rapp |first1=Timothy |title=Chase Young Rumors: Teams Behind Lions in 2020 NFL Draft Haven't Contacted Star |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2885639-chase-young-rumors-teams-behind-lions-in-2020-nfl-draft-havent-contacted-star |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Noga |first1=Joe |title=Chase Young, Ohio State DE: 2020 NFL Draft profile |url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331014816/https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His 16.5 sacks broke the single-season school record previously held by [[Vernon Gholston]], who had 14 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Joey |title=Chase Young a Heisman finalist despite playing defense, being suspended |url=https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |website=Buckeyextra.com |publisher=The Columbus Dispatch |accessdate=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224230059/https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYoung won several awards and honors for his performance that season, including the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]],<ref name=\"Bronko\">{{cite web |last1=Straka |first1=Dean |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young wins Bronko Nagurski Trophy |url=https://247sports.com/Article/ohio-state-defensive-end-chase-young-wins-2019-bronko-nagurski-trophy-140221610/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Chuck Bednarik Award]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Wins 2019 Chuck Bednarik Award |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195746/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ted Hendricks Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clay |first1=Jarrod |title=Chase Young wins 2019 Ted Hendricks Award |url=https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |website=ABC 6 |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195619/https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenstein |first1=Teddy |title=Chase Young is the 2019 Chicago Tribune Silver Football winner \u2014 and the 1st Ohio State defensive player to win the award in its 95-year history |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |website=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230142145/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]],<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> and [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]].<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> In addition, he was twice named the [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp]] defensive player of the week for his performances against Wisconsin and Penn State,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hass-Hill |first1=Colin |title=Chase Young Named Walter Camp National Defensive Player Of The Week For Second Time This Season |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |website=Elevan Warriors |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127222424/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was [[List of unanimous All-Americans in college football|unanimously named]] to the 2019 All-Big Ten and [[2019 College Football All-America Team|All-America Teams]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204022652/https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also named a finalist for the [[Maxwell Award]] and [[Heisman Trophy]], becoming only the ninth defensive player since 1982 to be nominated for the latter, where he finished fourth in voting behind quarterbacks [[Joe Burrow]], [[Jalen Hurts]], and [[Justin Fields]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duffley |first1=John |title=Joe Burrow Wins Maxwell Award as CFB\u2019s Player of the Year |url=https://fanbuzz.com/college-football/maxwell-award-watch-list/ |website=FanBuzz.com |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Ian |title=OSU defensive end Chase Young declares for 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |website=News 5 Cleveland |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104141151/https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN News Services |title=Bayou bliss: LSU QB Joe Burrow takes home Heisman |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230123538/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second all-time there behind only [[Mike Vrabel]]'s 36.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anders |first1=Andy |title=Football: Chase Young declares for NFL Draft |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |website=The Latern |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406225649/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=1|Games\n! colspan=4|Tackles\n! colspan=2|Sacks\n! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP\n! Solo !! Ast !! Total !! TFL !! Total !! Yards\n!FF\n!FR\n|-\n![[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2017]]\n|9\n|11\n|7\n|18\n|5\n|3.5\n|20\n|1\n|0\n|-\n![[2018 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2018]]\n|13\n|25\n|9\n|34\n|14.5\n|10.5\n|60\n|1\n|0\n|-\n![[2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2019]]\n|12\n|32\n|14\n|46\n|21\n|16.5\n|117\n|7\n|0\n|-\n! Totals<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=College Football Reference |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n!34\n!68||30||98||40.5||30.5||197\n!9\n!0\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nYoung decided to forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]],<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young announces he's entering NFL draft |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103191232/https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young declares for 2020 draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195556/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he is considered by many to be its best overall prospect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Birkett |first1=Dave |title=Chase Young is NFL draft's No. 1 prospect; don't let late-season slump worry you |url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |website=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225215049/https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Copeland |first1=Kareem |title=Chase Young is a \u2018generational talent\u2019 and clear choice for Redskins, draft expert says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/02/22/chase-young-is-generational-talent-clear-choice-redskins-draft-expert-says/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226103632/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/02/22/chase-young-is-generational-talent-clear-choice-redskins-draft-expert-says/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any workouts or drills, stating that he did not want to waste time being a \"combine athlete\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=DelVecchio |first1=Steve |title=Chase Young has great explanation for skipping combine workouts |url=https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |website=Yardbarker |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303053338/https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Joe Burrow, Chase Young to participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108846/article/joe-burrow-chase-young-to-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung's father, Greg, played college basketball at [[Bowie State University]] before working as a police deputy in [[Arlington County, Virginia]], while his mother, Carla, works for the [[US Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Dayton\"/><ref name=\"Law\">{{cite web |last1=Means |first1=Stephen |title=Ohio State\u2019s star DE Chase Young following his family\u2019s formula to success: From athletics to law enforcement |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |website=Cleveland.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205731/https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |archive-date=October 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young has a sister, Weslie, who played college basketball at [[North Carolina Wesleyan]].<ref name=\"Tattoo\">{{cite web |last1=Culpepper |first1=Chuck |title=A veteran and grandfather\u2019s kinetic tribute \u2014 on the arm of college football\u2019s best player |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229110140/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At Ohio State, Young decided to major in [[criminology]] after being inspired by his father and two of his uncles, who all work in [[law enforcement]].<ref name=\"Law\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young, DeMatha Catholic, Weak-Side Defensive End |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Chase-Young-83154/high-school-144085/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> Young is sometimes called the \"Predator\" for his on-field dominance, as well as his [[dreadlock]]s resembling [[Predator (fictional species)|Predators]] from the ''[[Predator (franchise)|Predator]]'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Why freaky OSU DE Chase Young is the best player in college football: \u2018There\u2019s only 10 guys like him in the world\u2019 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101104924/https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Jackson Carman Eluded Ohio State; will Block Chase Young |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |website=SI.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225151946/https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Ohio State's Chase Young May Be Better Than Bosa Brothers |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/ohio-states-chase-young-may-be-better-than-bosa-brothers |website=SI.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Young has a tattoo of Carl H. Robinson, his late grandfather and [[US Air Force]] veteran, on his right arm.<ref name=\"Tattoo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter|youngchase907}}\n* [https://www.nfl.com/prospects/chase-young?id=3219594f-5514-6550-d662-263c81d981b1 NFL.com prospect profile]\n* [http://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Chase Young|list=\n{{Ted Hendricks Award}}\n{{Bronko Nagurski Trophy}}\n{{Chuck Bednarik Award}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chase}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:DeMatha Catholic High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Washington metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football defensive end}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the American football player|the Xiaolin Showdown character|Chase Young (Xiaolin Showdown)}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Chase Young\n| image               =\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| number              = --\n| current_team        =\n| position            = [[Defensive end]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n| birth_place         = [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 5\n| weight_lb           = 265\n| high_school         = [[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n| college             = [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          =\n| draftpick           =\n| undraftedyear       =\n| pastteams           =\n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          =\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          =\n| statweek            =\n| statlabel1          = [[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\n| statlabel2          = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| nflnew              =\n| pfr                 =\n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Chase Young\n|school=Ohio State Buckeyes\n|currentnumber=2\n|major=[[Criminology]]\n|currentposition=[[Defensive end]]\n|class=Junior\n|bowlgames=\n* [[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)]]\n* [[2019 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=5\n|weight_lb=265\n|highschool=[[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n|pastschools=\n* [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4241986\n|highlights=\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* First-team All-Big Ten ([[2019 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2019]])\n* Second-team All-Big Ten ([[2018 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2018]])\n* ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Walter Camp Award]] National Player of the Week\n}}\n'''Chase Young''' (born April 14, 1999) is an [[American football]] [[defensive end]] for the <!--[[]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).-->[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State Buckeyes]]. As a junior in 2019, Young broke Ohio State's single-season sack record with 16.5, winning him several honors such as the [[Chuck Bednarik Award]], [[Ted Hendricks Award]], and [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]], as well as being named a unanimous [[All-America]]n and [[Heisman Trophy]] finalist.\n\n==Early life==\nChase Young was born on April 14, 1999, in [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]] to Greg and Carla Young.<ref name=\"OSUBio\">{{cite web |title=Chase Young - Football |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |access-date=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213232426/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ |archive-date=December 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Walter Camp National Defensive PoW \u2026 Again! |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-walter-camp-national-defensive-pow-again/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Young first attended [[St. Vincent Pallotti High School]] in [[Laurel, Maryland]], starting at quarterback and outside linebacker as a freshman in 2013 before switching to defensive end later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=The Chase for Young is on |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704181213/http://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899 |archive-date=July 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Santoliquito |first1=Joseph |title=Eagles fan Chase Young may soon become an Eagles\u2019 nightmare |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/chase-young-philadelphia-eagles-fan-ohio-state-maxwell-awards-nfl-draft-washington-redskins/ |website=Philly Voice |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2014, he and the team won the MIAA C Conference championship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Worgo |first1=Tom |title=Pallotti football relies on running game, defense to defeat AACS for MIAA C Conference title |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/laurel/ph-ll-pallott-annapolisareachristianschool-footballi-story.html |website=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> He transferred to [[DeMatha Catholic High School]] in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]] in 2015, where he had 118 tackles with 19 sacks as a senior the following year, which helped the team go undefeated and win the state championship.<ref name=\"SportingNews\">{{cite web |last1=Bender |first1=Bill |title=The making of Chase Young: How an athletic freak at Ohio State became the best player in the NFL Draft |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |website=Sporting News |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303052838/https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young also played basketball for both schools, where he was a DeMatha teammate and friend of future [[NBA]] player [[Markelle Fultz]], who was [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|selected first overall]] in the [[2017 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young chasing top draft pick of HS basketball teammate Markelle Fultz |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ohio-state-de-chase-young-chasing-top-draft-pick-of-high-school-basketball-teammate-markelle-fultz-024346344.html |website=Yahoo Sports |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228192302/https://sports.yahoo.com/ohio-state-de-chase-young-chasing-top-draft-pick-of-high-school-basketball-teammate-markelle-fultz-024346344.html |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was also a member of the school's choir, playing the piano, saxophone, and violin.<ref name=\"Dayton\">{{cite web |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Tom |title=Archdeacon: Ohio State\u2019s Young a menace in mauling of Badgers |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |website=Dayton Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, he was considered one of the best high school football players in the nation, where he was included on the [[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team]], as well as being named as the all-metropolitan defensive football player of the year by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Football Defense: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202012103/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Fall All-Met |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626021033/https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also invited to the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]], playing for the East team.<ref>{{cite web |title=DeMatha defensive end Chase Young solidifies standing with Army All-American selection |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221142657/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection/ |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young received scholarship offers from over 40 colleges before committing to [[Ohio State University]] in July 2016, choosing them over other schools such as [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park|Maryland]] due to their approach that he felt was more \"family-oriented\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connors |first1=Ryan |title=5-star DE Chase Young commits to Ohio State: Maryland football misses out on top local prospect |url=https://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |website=testudotimes.com |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030181151/http://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lombardi |first1=Matt |title=Chase Young Explains Why He Chose Ohio State Over Alabama |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/chase-young-explains-why-he-chose-ohio-state-over-alabama |website=The Spun |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nPlaying for the [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State Buckeyes]], Young recorded four sacks as a freshman in 2017.<ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Ludwiczak |first1=Brett |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young is ready to build off a breakout sophomore season |url=https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |website=Land Grant Holy Land |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=January 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191344/https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> During his sophomore season in 2018, Young sprained both ankles but still managed to record 10.5 sacks on the season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haas-Hill |first1=Colin |title=K.J. Hill, Chase Young and J.K. Dobbins Could Break or Tie Ohio State Individual Records in 2019 |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191351/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He came on strong after fellow defensive end [[Nick Bosa]] was injured in the latter part of the season, recording three sacks in the [[2018 Big Ten Football Championship Game]] against [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]].<ref name=\"Sophomore\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowland |first1=Kyle |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young wants to be the best |url=https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |website=[[Toledo Blade]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510205559/https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring his junior season in 2019, Young tied Ohio State school records for single-game sacks (four) and tackles for loss (five) in a win against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Planos |first1=Josh |title=Ohio State's Chase Young Is Playing Like A Heisman Contender |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116060500/https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heisman Watch: Chase Young Crashes Quarterback Party |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |website=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031175718/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the game, Ohio State head coach [[Ryan Day (American football)|Ryan Day]] called him the most dominant player in all of college football.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hummer |first1=Chris |title=Chase Young is on a historic, Heisman-worthy pace |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-Heisman-Trophy-Ohio-State-football-2020-NFL-Draft-137613670/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Young was suspended for two games by the [[NCAA]] for getting an unauthorized loan from a family friend to allegedly help his girlfriend attend the [[2019 Rose Bowl]], which he later repaid in full.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bumbaca |first1=Chris |title=Ohio State Buckeyes' Chase Young expected to serve four-game suspension, per reports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=NCAA rules Ohio State's Chase Young to miss 1 more game |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113185829/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young recorded three sacks against Penn State in his first game after returning.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/> He ended the season with 16.5 sacks, 46 tackles, six forced fumbles, three passes batted, as well as a blocked kick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rapp |first1=Timothy |title=Chase Young Rumors: Teams Behind Lions in 2020 NFL Draft Haven't Contacted Star |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2885639-chase-young-rumors-teams-behind-lions-in-2020-nfl-draft-havent-contacted-star |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Noga |first1=Joe |title=Chase Young, Ohio State DE: 2020 NFL Draft profile |url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331014816/https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His 16.5 sacks broke the single-season school record previously held by [[Vernon Gholston]], who had 14 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Joey |title=Chase Young a Heisman finalist despite playing defense, being suspended |url=https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |website=Buckeyextra.com |publisher=The Columbus Dispatch |accessdate=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224230059/https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYoung won several awards and honors for his performance that season, including the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]],<ref name=\"Bronko\">{{cite web |last1=Straka |first1=Dean |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young wins Bronko Nagurski Trophy |url=https://247sports.com/Article/ohio-state-defensive-end-chase-young-wins-2019-bronko-nagurski-trophy-140221610/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Chuck Bednarik Award]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Wins 2019 Chuck Bednarik Award |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195746/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ted Hendricks Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clay |first1=Jarrod |title=Chase Young wins 2019 Ted Hendricks Award |url=https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |website=ABC 6 |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195619/https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenstein |first1=Teddy |title=Chase Young is the 2019 Chicago Tribune Silver Football winner \u2014 and the 1st Ohio State defensive player to win the award in its 95-year history |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |website=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230142145/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]],<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> and [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]].<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> In addition, he was twice named the [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp]] defensive player of the week for his performances against Wisconsin and Penn State,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hass-Hill |first1=Colin |title=Chase Young Named Walter Camp National Defensive Player Of The Week For Second Time This Season |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |website=Elevan Warriors |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127222424/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was [[List of unanimous All-Americans in college football|unanimously named]] to the 2019 All-Big Ten and [[2019 College Football All-America Team|All-America Teams]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204022652/https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also named a finalist for the [[Maxwell Award]] and [[Heisman Trophy]], becoming only the ninth defensive player since 1982 to be nominated for the latter, where he finished fourth in voting behind quarterbacks [[Joe Burrow]], [[Jalen Hurts]], and [[Justin Fields]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duffley |first1=John |title=Joe Burrow Wins Maxwell Award as CFB\u2019s Player of the Year |url=https://fanbuzz.com/college-football/maxwell-award-watch-list/ |website=FanBuzz.com |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Ian |title=OSU defensive end Chase Young declares for 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |website=News 5 Cleveland |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104141151/https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN News Services |title=Bayou bliss: LSU QB Joe Burrow takes home Heisman |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230123538/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second all-time there behind only [[Mike Vrabel]]'s 36.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anders |first1=Andy |title=Football: Chase Young declares for NFL Draft |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |website=The Latern |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406225649/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=1|Games\n! colspan=4|Tackles\n! colspan=2|Sacks\n! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP\n! Solo !! Ast !! Total !! TFL !! Total !! Yards\n!FF\n!FR\n|-\n![[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2017]]\n|9\n|11\n|7\n|18\n|5\n|3.5\n|20\n|1\n|0\n|-\n![[2018 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2018]]\n|13\n|25\n|9\n|34\n|14.5\n|10.5\n|60\n|1\n|0\n|-\n![[2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2019]]\n|12\n|32\n|14\n|46\n|21\n|16.5\n|117\n|7\n|0\n|-\n! Totals<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=College Football Reference |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n!34\n!68||30||98||40.5||30.5||197\n!9\n!0\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nYoung decided to forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]],<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young announces he's entering NFL draft |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103191232/https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young declares for 2020 draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195556/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he is considered by many to be its best overall prospect.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Birkett |first1=Dave |title=Chase Young is NFL draft's No. 1 prospect; don't let late-season slump worry you |url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |website=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225215049/https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Copeland |first1=Kareem |title=Chase Young is a \u2018generational talent\u2019 and clear choice for Redskins, draft expert says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/02/22/chase-young-is-generational-talent-clear-choice-redskins-draft-expert-says/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226103632/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/02/22/chase-young-is-generational-talent-clear-choice-redskins-draft-expert-says/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any workouts or drills, stating that he did not want to waste time being a \"combine athlete\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=DelVecchio |first1=Steve |title=Chase Young has great explanation for skipping combine workouts |url=https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |website=Yardbarker |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303053338/https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Joe Burrow, Chase Young to participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108846/article/joe-burrow-chase-young-to-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung's father, Greg, played college basketball at [[Bowie State University]] before working as a police deputy in [[Arlington County, Virginia]], while his mother, Carla, works for the [[US Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Dayton\"/><ref name=\"Law\">{{cite web |last1=Means |first1=Stephen |title=Ohio State\u2019s star DE Chase Young following his family\u2019s formula to success: From athletics to law enforcement |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |website=Cleveland.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205731/https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |archive-date=October 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young has a sister, Weslie, who played college basketball at [[North Carolina Wesleyan]].<ref name=\"Tattoo\">{{cite web |last1=Culpepper |first1=Chuck |title=A veteran and grandfather\u2019s kinetic tribute \u2014 on the arm of college football\u2019s best player |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229110140/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At Ohio State, Young decided to major in [[criminology]] after being inspired by his father and two of his uncles, who all work in [[law enforcement]].<ref name=\"Law\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young, DeMatha Catholic, Weak-Side Defensive End |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Chase-Young-83154/high-school-144085/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> Young is sometimes called the \"Predator\" for his on-field dominance, as well as his [[dreadlock]]s resembling [[Predator (fictional species)|Predators]] from the ''[[Predator (franchise)|Predator]]'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Why freaky OSU DE Chase Young is the best player in college football: \u2018There\u2019s only 10 guys like him in the world\u2019 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101104924/https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Jackson Carman Eluded Ohio State; will Block Chase Young |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |website=SI.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225151946/https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Ohio State's Chase Young May Be Better Than Bosa Brothers |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/ohio-states-chase-young-may-be-better-than-bosa-brothers |website=SI.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Young has a tattoo of Carl H. Robinson, his late grandfather and [[US Air Force]] veteran, on his right arm.<ref name=\"Tattoo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter|youngchase907}}\n* [https://www.nfl.com/prospects/chase-young?id=3219594f-5514-6550-d662-263c81d981b1 NFL.com prospect profile]\n* [http://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Chase Young|list=\n{{Ted Hendricks Award}}\n{{Bronko Nagurski Trophy}}\n{{Chuck Bednarik Award}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chase}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:DeMatha Catholic High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Washington metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "Dissident93", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:now in the personal section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chase_Young"}
{"title_page": "Marriage certificate", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2008}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Marriage certificate-1907.jpg|thumb|Marriage certificate issued in [[Russian language|Russian]] in the [[Congress Poland]], 1907]]\nA '''marriage certificate''' (sometimes: '''marriage lines''') is an official statement that two people are [[marriage|married]]. In most jurisdictions, a marriage certificate is issued by a government official only after the [[civil registration]] of the marriage.\n\nIn some jurisdictions, especially in the United States, a marriage certificate is the official record that two people have undertaken a marriage ceremony. This includes jurisdictions where [[marriage license]]s do not exist. In other jurisdictions, a marriage license serves a dual purpose of granting permission for a marriage to take place and then endorsing the same document to record the fact that the marriage has been performed.\n\nA marriage certificate may be required for a number of reasons. It may be required as evidence of change of a party's name, on issues of [[Legitimacy (family law)|legitimacy]] of a child, during divorce proceedings, or as part of a genealogical history, besides other purposes.\n\n==Countries==\n===Australia===\n{{see also|Marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage in Australia}}\nThough marriage in [[Australia]] is [[Marriage Act 1961 (Australia)|regulated under federal law]], the [[civil registration|registration]] of marriages takes place under the respective [[States and territories of Australia|state or territory]] laws, generally through an agency named \"Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/information-and-services/family-and-community/births-deaths-and-marriages-registries|title=Births, deaths and marriages registries \u2013 australia.gov.au|first=Digital Transformation |last=Agency |website=Australia.gov.au |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> or similar, and marriage certificates are issued by these agencies. Under Federal law, a certificate is issued at the time of marriage by a celebrant, for forwarding to the state or territory registry. A similar (sometimes cut-down) document is often given to the couple on the day of the marriage, it is generally handwritten.  While legally valid as proof of marriage, is not generally acceptable as an official document. However, the state or territory marriage certificate is considered to be an acceptable and secure [[Identity documents of Australia|secondary identity document]] especially for the purposes of change of name, and needs to be obtained separately for a fee generally some time after the marriage. This document can be verified electronically by the [[Attorney-general of Australia]]'s Document Verification Service.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081501/https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> States and territories sometimes market commemorative marriage certificates, which generally have no official document status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdm.nsw.gov.au/Pages/marriages/marriage-certificate.aspx#commemorative|title=Marriage certificate |website=Bdm.nsw.gov.au|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nState and territory issued certificates are on [[A4 paper]] and provide: Date and place of marriage, full names, occupations, addresses, marital status (never validly married, divorced, widow/er), birth date & place, age, father's name, mother's maiden name of each the couple, the celebrant, witness names (generally two), the registrar official of the state or territory authority, and the date of registration. The registrar's signature and seal is printed/embossed on the certificate along with a number, and date of issue of certificate.\n\nMarriage certificates are not generally used in Australia, other than to prove change-of-name, and proof of marital status in a divorce hearing. Some visa categories require a certificate (where a partner is to be associated with a primary applicant),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/300- |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407233805/https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/300- |archive-date=7 April 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> however there are similar categories of partner visas that do not.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/801-|title=Partner visa (subclasses 820 and 801)|website=Border.gov.au|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, Australian federal law has recognised [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Australia|same-sex marriages]].<ref name=\"MarriageAct9Dec2017V1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2017C00382 |title=Marriage Act|date=9 December 2017 |work=Federal Register of Legislation|quote=Refer to Part 1 (Subsection 8) of the Act}}</ref> These marriages are registrable and documented in the conventional way. \n\n===England and Wales===\nOn 1 July 1837 civil registration was introduced in England and Wales, providing a central record of all births, deaths and marriages. A Registrar General was appointed with overall responsibility and the country was divided into registration districts, each controlled by a superintendent registrar. Under this system, all marriage ceremonies have been certified by the issuing of a marriage certificate whose details are also stored centrally. From that date, marriage ceremonies could be performed, and certificates issued either by a clergyman of the [[Church of England]], in a parish church, or by a civil registrar in a civil register office. Marriages performed according to the ceremonies of [[Quakers]] and [[Jew]]s also continued to be recognised as legal marriages, and certificates were issued.\n\nThe marriage certificate itself is given to the couple who have married. Copies are made in two registers: one is retained by the church or register office; the other, when the entire register is full, is sent to the superintendent registrar of the registration district. Every quarter, the minister or civil registrar prepares a further copy of all the marriage entries and sends them to the Registrar General.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Geo6/12-13-14/76/contents|title=Marriage Act 1949|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe certificate lists the date of the marriage, and the full names of both spouses. Their ages are included (it is also permissible to write \"full\", meaning of age, and until 1850 some 75% of certificates said that; if the certificate reads \"minor\" or \"under age\", it means that, until 1929 when the law changed to 16, the bride was between 12 and 20 and the groom 14 and 20 years of age).\n\nThe certificate does not contain a specific record of the intended new surname(s), if one or both spouses wish to change their name. However, if a wife wishes to take her husband's surname, a marriage certificate obtained in England or Wales recording both her maiden name and her husband's name is supposed to be sufficient evidence for getting her name changed on, for example, her bank account<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/advice/woman-getting-married#take-partners-name|title=Advice for a woman getting married|publisher=Deed Poll Office|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> and any UK bank that rejects such a marriage certificate as evidence is in error.\n\nThe certificate also records the previous marital status of both spouses. Those not previously married were \"bachelor\" or \"spinster.\" From 1858 to 1952 a previously divorced groom was listed as \"the divorced husband of\u2026\" with his ex-wife's maiden name listed, and vice versa for a divorced bride. The currently used wording is \"previous marriage dissolved\" with no further details given.\nOn 5 September 2005, the Registrar General in England and Wales officially abolished the traditional terms of \"bachelor\" and \"spinster\" and substituted the more politically-correct \"single\" to coincide with the reform that introduced civil partnerships, explaining, \"The word single will be used to mean a couple who has never been through a marriage or civil partnership.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/4141996.stm|title=R.I.P Bachelors and Spinsters|date=14 September 2005|accessdate=21 May 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nUnlike birth and death registrations, marriage registers are held by individual Anglican churches in England.  Two copies are held and when full or when the church is closed one copy is deposited in [[diocesan record office]]s or [[county record office]]s (often but not always the same office) and the other deposited at the local register office. Such records are thus available for inspection in their original form (or a direct filmed copy) without the requirement to pay a search fee or the purchase of certified copies. The availability can be somewhat random: some churches have not yet filled their original 1837 registers, while others might have deposited a register in recent weeks.\n\n===Russia===\n[[image:2014 \u0421\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Marriage certificate form of Russia issued in 2014]]\nA certificate of marriage is the only legally valid document on the registration of marriage in Russia. Issued in the certification of the fact of state registration of the civil status act, signed by the head of the registry office and is sealed with its seal.<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\">{{Cite web|url=http://base.consultant.ru/cons/cgi/online.cgi?req=doc;base=LAW;n=173279;div=LAW;dst=3,1;rnd=177853.6236325593199581956692|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 15.11.1997 N 143-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 31.12.2014) \"\u041e\u0431 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044f\"|publisher=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430, \u2116224|date=20 November 1997|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nA state registration fee of 350 rubles is charged for state registration of acts of civil status.\n\nFor the marriage, the couple must file a joint statement confirming mutual voluntary consent for the conclusion of the marriage union, as well as the absence of circumstances preventing marriage. Future spouses sign a joint statement and indicate the date of its compilation. Simultaneously with the application it is necessary to provide documents proving the identity of future spouses; documents confirming the termination of the previous marriage, if any; permission to enter into marriage before reaching the marriageable age, if the person (person) entering into marriage is a minor.<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\"/>\n\nThe certificate of marriage contains the following information:<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\"/>\n\n*Surname (before and after the marriage), name, patronymic, date and place of birth, citizenship and nationality (if indicated in the record of the act of marriage) of each of the persons married\n*Date of marriage\n*Date of compilation and the number of the record of the marriage certificate\n*Place of state registration of marriage, namely the name of the registry office chosen by future spouses at will in the territory of the Russian Federation\n*Date of issue of the marriage certificate\n\n===United States===\nIn parts of the United States, the certificate of marriage is recorded on the same document as the marriage license or application for marriage. While each state creates their own form for use with the recording of marriages, most states have a specific portion of the record to be completed by the official performing the ceremony. In some states, this portion also includes places for the parties to indicate a change in name, if any. (The marriage certificate can be used as documentation to justify a legal name change but not as proof that a name change has occurred.) If there is not a place for a name change, the name is changed as requested on government documents with proof of marriage.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nImage:2020\n-wedding-lic.jpg|A wedding certificate issued in 2020 in New york\nImage:2020 Marriage Certificate.jpg|2020 marriage certificate, United States\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Marriage certificates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marriage Certificate}}\n[[Category:Identity documents]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2008}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Marriage certificate-1907.jpg|thumb|Marriage certificate issued in [[Russian language|Russian]] in the [[Congress Poland]], 1907]]\nA '''marriage certificate''' (sometimes: '''marriage lines''') is an official statement that two people are [[marriage|married]]. In most jurisdictions, a marriage certificate is issued by a government official only after the [[civil registration]] of the marriage.\n\nIn some jurisdictions, especially in the United States, a marriage certificate is the official record that two people have undertaken a marriage ceremony. This includes jurisdictions where [[marriage license]]s do not exist. In other jurisdictions, a marriage license serves a dual purpose of granting permission for a marriage to take place and then endorsing the same document to record the fact that the marriage has been performed.\n\nA marriage certificate may be required for a number of reasons. It may be required as evidence of change of a party's name, on issues of [[Legitimacy (family law)|legitimacy]] of a child, during divorce proceedings, or as part of a genealogical history, besides other purposes.\n\n==Countries==\n===Australia===\n{{see also|Marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage in Australia}}\nThough marriage in [[Australia]] is [[Marriage Act 1961 (Australia)|regulated under federal law]], the [[civil registration|registration]] of marriages takes place under the respective [[States and territories of Australia|state or territory]] laws, generally through an agency named \"Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/information-and-services/family-and-community/births-deaths-and-marriages-registries|title=Births, deaths and marriages registries \u2013 australia.gov.au|first=Digital Transformation |last=Agency |website=Australia.gov.au |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> or similar, and marriage certificates are issued by these agencies. Under Federal law, a certificate is issued at the time of marriage by a celebrant, for forwarding to the state or territory registry. A similar (sometimes cut-down) document is often given to the couple on the day of the marriage, it is generally handwritten.  While legally valid as proof of marriage, is not generally acceptable as an official document. However, the state or territory marriage certificate is considered to be an acceptable and secure [[Identity documents of Australia|secondary identity document]] especially for the purposes of change of name, and needs to be obtained separately for a fee generally some time after the marriage. This document can be verified electronically by the [[Attorney-general of Australia]]'s Document Verification Service.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081501/https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> States and territories sometimes market commemorative marriage certificates, which generally have no official document status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdm.nsw.gov.au/Pages/marriages/marriage-certificate.aspx#commemorative|title=Marriage certificate |website=Bdm.nsw.gov.au|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nState and territory issued certificates are on [[A4 paper]] and provide: Date and place of marriage, full names, occupations, addresses, marital status (never validly married, divorced, widow/er), birth date & place, age, father's name, mother's maiden name of each the couple, the celebrant, witness names (generally two), the registrar official of the state or territory authority, and the date of registration. The registrar's signature and seal is printed/embossed on the certificate along with a number, and date of issue of certificate.\n\nMarriage certificates are not generally used in Australia, other than to prove change-of-name, and proof of marital status in a divorce hearing. Some visa categories require a certificate (where a partner is to be associated with a primary applicant),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/300- |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407233805/https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/300- |archive-date=7 April 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> however there are similar categories of partner visas that do not.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.border.gov.au/Trav/Visa-1/801-|title=Partner visa (subclasses 820 and 801)|website=Border.gov.au|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, Australian federal law has recognised [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Australia|same-sex marriages]].<ref name=\"MarriageAct9Dec2017V1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2017C00382 |title=Marriage Act|date=9 December 2017 |work=Federal Register of Legislation|quote=Refer to Part 1 (Subsection 8) of the Act}}</ref> These marriages are registrable and documented in the conventional way. \n\n===England and Wales===\nOn 1 July 1837 civil registration was introduced in England and Wales, providing a central record of all births, deaths and marriages. A Registrar General was appointed with overall responsibility and the country was divided into registration districts, each controlled by a superintendent registrar. Under this system, all marriage ceremonies have been certified by the issuing of a marriage certificate whose details are also stored centrally. From that date, marriage ceremonies could be performed, and certificates issued either by a clergyman of the [[Church of England]], in a parish church, or by a civil registrar in a civil register office. Marriages performed according to the ceremonies of [[Quakers]] and [[Jew]]s also continued to be recognised as legal marriages, and certificates were issued.\n\nThe marriage certificate itself is given to the couple who have married. Copies are made in two registers: one is retained by the church or register office; the other, when the entire register is full, is sent to the superintendent registrar of the registration district. Every quarter, the minister or civil registrar prepares a further copy of all the marriage entries and sends them to the Registrar General.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Geo6/12-13-14/76/contents|title=Marriage Act 1949|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe certificate lists the date of the marriage, and the full names of both spouses. Their ages are included (it is also permissible to write \"full\", meaning of age, and until 1850 some 75% of certificates said that; if the certificate reads \"minor\" or \"under age\", it means that, until 1929 when the law changed to 16, the bride was between 12 and 20 and the groom 14 and 20 years of age).\n\nThe certificate does not contain a specific record of the intended new surname(s), if one or both spouses wish to change their name. However, if a wife wishes to take her husband's surname, a marriage certificate obtained in England or Wales recording both her maiden name and her husband's name is supposed to be sufficient evidence for getting her name changed on, for example, her bank account<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/advice/woman-getting-married#take-partners-name|title=Advice for a woman getting married|publisher=Deed Poll Office|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> and any UK bank that rejects such a marriage certificate as evidence is in error.\n\nThe certificate also records the previous marital status of both spouses. Those not previously married were \"bachelor\" or \"spinster.\" From 1858 to 1952 a previously divorced groom was listed as \"the divorced husband of\u2026\" with his ex-wife's maiden name listed, and vice versa for a divorced bride. The currently used wording is \"previous marriage dissolved\" with no further details given.\nOn 5 September 2005, the Registrar General in England and Wales officially abolished the traditional terms of \"bachelor\" and \"spinster\" and substituted the more politically-correct \"single\" to coincide with the reform that introduced civil partnerships, explaining, \"The word single will be used to mean a couple who has never been through a marriage or civil partnership.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/4141996.stm|title=R.I.P Bachelors and Spinsters|date=14 September 2005|accessdate=21 May 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nUnlike birth and death registrations, marriage registers are held by individual Anglican churches in England.  Two copies are held and when full or when the church is closed one copy is deposited in [[diocesan record office]]s or [[county record office]]s (often but not always the same office) and the other deposited at the local register office. Such records are thus available for inspection in their original form (or a direct filmed copy) without the requirement to pay a search fee or the purchase of certified copies. The availability can be somewhat random: some churches have not yet filled their original 1837 registers, while others might have deposited a register in recent weeks.\n\n===Russia===\n[[image:2014 \u0421\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Marriage certificate form of Russia issued in 2014]]\nA certificate of marriage is the only legally valid document on the registration of marriage in Russia. Issued in the certification of the fact of state registration of the civil status act, signed by the head of the registry office and is sealed with its seal.<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\">{{Cite web|url=http://base.consultant.ru/cons/cgi/online.cgi?req=doc;base=LAW;n=173279;div=LAW;dst=3,1;rnd=177853.6236325593199581956692|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 15.11.1997 N 143-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 31.12.2014) \"\u041e\u0431 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044f\"|publisher=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430, \u2116224|date=20 November 1997|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nA state registration fee of 350 rubles is charged for state registration of acts of civil status.\n\nFor the marriage, the couple must file a joint statement confirming mutual voluntary consent for the conclusion of the marriage union, as well as the absence of circumstances preventing marriage. Future spouses sign a joint statement and indicate the date of its compilation. Simultaneously with the application it is necessary to provide documents proving the identity of future spouses; documents confirming the termination of the previous marriage, if any; permission to enter into marriage before reaching the marriageable age, if the person (person) entering into marriage is a minor.<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\"/>\n\nThe certificate of marriage contains the following information:<ref name=\"ZAGS-law\"/>\n\n*Surname (before and after the marriage), name, patronymic, date and place of birth, citizenship and nationality (if indicated in the record of the act of marriage) of each of the persons married\n*Date of marriage\n*Date of compilation and the number of the record of the marriage certificate\n*Place of state registration of marriage, namely the name of the registry office chosen by future spouses at will in the territory of the Russian Federation\n*Date of issue of the marriage certificate\n\n===United States===\nIn parts of the United States, the certificate of marriage is recorded on the same document as the marriage license or application for marriage. While each state creates their own form for use with the recording of marriages, most states have a specific portion of the record to be completed by the official performing the ceremony. In some states, this portion also includes places for the parties to indicate a change in name, if any. (The marriage certificate can be used as documentation to justify a legal name change but not as proof that a name change has occurred.) If there is not a place for a name change, the name is changed as requested on government documents with proof of marriage.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nImage:1883-wedding-lic.jpg|A wedding certificate issued in 1883 in lake Michigan \nImage:1875 Marriage Certificate.jpg|1875 marriage certificate, United States\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Marriage certificates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marriage Certificate}}\n[[Category:Identity documents]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n", "name_user": "98.116.175.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUnited States)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marriage_certificate"}
{"title_page": "Gondi languages", "text_new": "{{Infobox language family\n| name        = Gondi languages\n| ethnicity   = [[Gondi people|Gonds]]\n| region      = Throughout Central [[India]], mostly [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| familycolor = Dravidian\n| fam2        = South-Central\n| fam3        = Gondi-Kui\n| child1      = [[Gondi language|Gondi]]\n| child2      = [[Muria language|Muria]]\n| child3      = [[Koya language|Koya]]\n| child4      = [[Madiya language|Madiya]]\n| child5      = [[Khirwar language|Khirwar]]?\n| glotto = gond1265\n| glottorefname = Gondi\n}}\n\nThe '''Gondi languages''' are a subgroup of the Dravidian family that includes Gondi and related languages. [[Gondi language|Gondi]] proper is the most widely spoken language, with over 2.7 million speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-1586.html|title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-22}}</ref> Other languages in this subgroup include [[Muria language|Muria]], [[Madiya language|Madiya]], and [[Koya language|Koya]]. It is undetermined whether [[Pardhan language|Pardhan]] is a separate language or a dialect of Gondi, although current fieldwork suggests it is a [[dialect]].<ref>{{Cite document|title=A Sociolingustic Survey Among the Pardhan Community of Central India|last=Thangmulian|first=Valte|last2=Mathai|first2=Elrose K.|date=August 2008|publisher=SIL International|last3=George|first3=Symon|citeseerx = 10.1.1.559.17}}</ref> [[Khirwar language|Khirwar]] is a poorly-attested language spoken by people in the general Gond area, and so is assumed to be related to Gondi.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dravidian languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language family\n| name        = Gondi languages\n| ethnicity   = [[Gondi people|Gonds]]\n| region      = Throughout Central [[India]], mostly [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Chhattisgarh]]\n| familycolor = Dravidian\n| fam2        = South-Central\n| fam3        = Gondi-Kui\n| child1      = [[Gondi language|Gondi]]\n| child2      = [[Muria language|Muria]]\n| child3      = [[Koya language|Koya]]\n| child4      = [[Madiya language|Madiya]]\n| child5      = [[Khirwar language|Khirwar]]?\n| glotto = gond1265\n| glottorefname = Gondi\n}}\n\nThe '''Gondi languages''' are a subgroup of the Dravidian family that includes Gondi and related languages. [[Gondi language|Gondi]] proper is the most widely spoken language, with over 2.7 million speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-1586.html|title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-22}}</ref> Other languages in this subgroup include [[Muria language|Muria]], [[Madiya language|Madiya]], and [[Koya language|Koya]]. It is undetermined whether [[Pardhan language|Pardhan]] is a separate language or a dialect of Gondi, although current fieldwork suggests it is a dialect.<ref>{{Cite document|title=A Sociolingustic Survey Among the Pardhan Community of Central India|last=Thangmulian|first=Valte|last2=Mathai|first2=Elrose K.|date=August 2008|publisher=SIL International|last3=George|first3=Symon|citeseerx = 10.1.1.559.17}}</ref> [[Khirwar language|Khirwar]] is a poorly-attested language spoken by people in the general Gond area, and so is assumed to be related to Gondi.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dravidian languages]]\n", "name_user": "Funde24", "label": "safe", "comment": "added internal link to 'dialect' page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondi_languages"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga Rugby\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =\n|ru_triesA           =0\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =0\n|ru_teamB            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = \n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He also played for Tauranga against Te Puke and despite recently joining the rugby code was named captain\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nHe captained Tauranga in a match against [[Rangitaiki]] which was won 12-5 with Iles involved prominently throughout the match\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In 1932 George Iles was captain of the Athletic Football Club and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]]\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Mayla Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga Rugby\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =\n|ru_triesA           =0\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =0\n|ru_teamB            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = \n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He also played for Tauranga against Te Puke and despite recently joining the rugby code was named captain\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nHe captained Tauranga in a match against [[Rangitaiki]] which was won 12-5 with Iles involved prominently throughout the match\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In 1932 George Iles was captain of the Athletic Football Club and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]]\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "UFC 249", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|UFC mixed martial arts event in 2020}}\n{{Infobox MMA event\n|name= UFC 249: Ferguson vs. Gaethje\n|image= UFC 249 poster.jpg\n|promotion=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n|date={{start date|2020|04|18}}\n|venue= [[TBA]]\n|city= [[TBA]]\n|attendance=\n|gate=\n|previousevent=[[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]]\n|followingevent=[[UFC Fight Night: Smith vs. Teixeira]]\n}}\n\n'''''UFC 249: Ferguson vs. Gaethje''''' was an upcoming [[mixed martial arts]] event produced by the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], scheduled to take place on April 18, 2020.<ref name=\"UFC249\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/mixed-martial-arts/ufc-249-khabib-nurmagomedov-tony-ferguson-1.39502080|title=Khabib vs. Ferguson set for UFC 249 at Barclays|publisher=newsday.com|author=Mark La Monica|date=2019-12-14|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>. It was canceled on April 9.<ref>https://twitter.com/espnmma/status/1248371420226347008</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA [[UFC Lightweight Championship]] bout between the current champion [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]] and former interim champion [[Tony Ferguson]] (also [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Lesnar vs. Team dos Santos]] welterweight winner) was slated to headline this event.<ref name=\"UFC249\" /> The pairing has previously been scheduled and cancelled for various reasons on four separate occasions ([[The Ultimate Fighter: Team McGregor vs. Team Faber#The Ultimate Fighter 22 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter: Team McGregor vs. Team Faber Finale]], [[UFC on Fox: Teixeira vs. Evans]], [[UFC 209]] and [[UFC 223]]) over the last four years.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mmafighting.com/2015/10/30/9645620/edson-barboza-steps-in-for-khabib-nurmagomedov-to-face-tony-ace-tony-ferguson|title= Edson Barboza steps in for Khabib Nurmagomedov to face Tony Ferguson at TUF Finale|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2015-10-30|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-tony-ferguson-out-rashad-evans-vs-glover-teixeira-set-as-new-main-event-040516|title=Tony Ferguson out; Rashad Evans vs. Glover Teixeira set as new main event|publisher=foxsports.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2016-04-05|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/3/3/14805818/ufc-releases-statement-on-khabib-nurmagomedov|title=UFC releases statement on Khabib Nurmagomedov|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2017-03-03|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2018/4/1/17187016/how-did-tony-ferguson-injure-his-knee-ufc-223|title=You won't believe how Tony Ferguson injured his knee and ended up off UFC 223|author=Ryan Harkness|date=2018-04-01|publisher=mmamania.com|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> The bout was canceled for a fifth time due to issues related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] ''(see section below)''.\n\n[[File:\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0438\u0431 \u041d\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432-2. 12.9.2019.jpg|thumb|left|190px|[[Khabib Nurmagomedov]] was expected to make his third title defense at this event, but had to pull out due to [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\n\nA featherweight bout between [[Jeremy Stephens]] and [[Calvin Kattar]] was expected to take place at [[UFC 248]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2020/1/6/21051609/ufc-248-jeremy-stephens-vs-calvin-kattar-march-7-las-vegas|title=UFC 248: Jeremy Stephens vs Calvin Kattar on tap for March 7 in Las Vegas|author=Jesse Holland|date=2020-01-06|publisher=mmamania.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> However, Stephens was removed from the card in mid-January with an injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/jeremy-stephens-injured-out-ufc-248-fight-calvin-kattar|title=Jeremy Stephens injured, out of planned UFC 248 bout vs. Calvin Kattar; rescheduling expected|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|access-date=2020-01-16|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The pairing was rescheduled for this event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/calvin-kattar-vs-jeremy-stephens-ufc-249|title=Calvin Kattar vs. Jeremy Stephens in the works for UFC 249|author=Nolan King|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|access-date=2020-01-23|date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nA heavyweight bout between [[Shamil Abdurakhimov]] and [[Ciryl Gane]] was scheduled for the event. However on March 5, it was announced that Gane was forced to pull out from the event after he was struck by a [[pneumothorax]] during one of his trainings. The bout was eventually scrapped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/3/5/21166938/ciryl-gane-out-ufc-249-fight-shamil-abdurakhimov|title=Ciryl Gane out of UFC 249 fight with Shamil Abdurakhimov|date=2020-03-05|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nA welterweight bout between former [[List of Bellator champions#Welterweight Championship|Bellator Welterweight Champion]] [[Lyman Good]] and [[Belal Muhammad (fighter)|Belal Muhammad]] was scheduled for this event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/02/ufc-249-belal-muhammad-vs-lyman-good-booked|title=Belal Muhammad vs. Lyman Good added to UFC 249 in Brooklyn|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Farah Hannoun and Mike Bohn|date=2020-02-11|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> The pairing was expected to meet at [[UFC 205]] in November 2016, but Good was pulled after being notified by [[USADA]] due to a potential anti-doping violation stemming from an out-of-competition drug test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/10/lyman-good-receives-usada-notice-pulled-from-ufc-205|title=Lyman Good receives USADA notice, pulled from UFC 205|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Staff|date=2016-10-24|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> However on April 4, Good pulled out due to injury and the bout was scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/04/lyman-good-out-ufc-249-injury-belal-muhammad-opponent|title=Lyman Good out of UFC 249 bout with Belal Muhammad due to injury|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Danny Segura|date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nA women's strawweight bout between former [[UFC Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Champions]] [[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]] and [[Rose Namajunas]] was expected to co-headline the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/ufc-249-rose-namajunas-vs-jessica-andrade-rematch-booked|title=Rose Namajunas, Jessica Andrade agree to rematch at UFC 249 in Brooklyn|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Mike Bohn|date=2020-01-09|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The pairing met previously at [[UFC 237]] in May 2019, when Andrade won via second round TKO to capture the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaindia.com/ufc-237-results-jessica-andrade-kos-rose-namajunas-in-round-2-wins-strawweight-belt/|title=UFC 237 results \u2013 Jessica Andrade KO\u2019s Rose Namajunas in round 2, wins strawweight belt|publisher=mmaindia.com|author=Sohail Syed|date=2019-05-12|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In turn, Namajunas pulled out due to personal reasons on April 8 and at this time, there is no word on a potential replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/ufc/story/_/id/29013557/rose-namajunas-pulls-ufc-249-bout-vs-jessica-andrade|title=Rose Namajunas pulls out of UFC 249 bout vs. Jessica Andrade|publisher=espn.com|author=Marc Raimondi and Ariel Helwani|date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/9/21215451/manager-rose-namajunas-withdrew-from-ufc-249-after-covid-19-deaths-in-family|title=Manager: Rose Namajunas withdrew from UFC 249 after COVID-19 deaths in family|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Newswire|date=2020-04-09|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nOn March 12, [[New York (state)|New York]] governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] issued an order restricting mass gatherings and sporting events due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/482976-nyc-governor-shuts-broadway-coronavirus/|title=Broadway is canceled: New York governor orders closure of theaters, ban on gatherings of 500+ due to coronavirus|publisher=rt.com|author=Staff|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> On March 16, UFC president [[Dana White]] announced via a letter to employees shared to the public that this event \"is still scheduled as planned, but the location may change\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King and John Morgan|date=2020-03-15|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On March 18, the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] announced that the event would not be sanctioned to take place in [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thescore.com/mma/news/1965609|title=Commission stops UFC 249 from happening in New York|publisher=thescore.com|author=Nick Baldwin|date=2020-03-18|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On March 23, White revealed that he already had a new location for this event, but would only confirm that it will be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/dana-white-says-he-has-location-for-ufc-249-confirms-closed-door-event|title=Dana White says he has location for UFC 249; confirms closed-door event|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Mike Bohn|date=2020-03-23|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> He added two days later that the card could feature a different lineup depending on the logistics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/dana-white-ufc-249-could-add-francis-ngannou-vs-jairzinho-rozenstruik|title=Dana White: UFC 249 could add Francis Ngannou vs. Jairzinho Rozenstruik, other fights|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2020-03-25|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nKhabib Nurmagomedov stated on March 30 that he was in [[Dagestan]] and his participation in the event could be jeopardized by travel bans related to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28970604/khabib-nurmagomedov-vs-tony-ferguson-likely-again|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov stuck in Russia, hears new Tony Ferguson opponent sought|publisher=espn.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2020-03-30|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> He stated on April 1 that he would probably not be competing at the event due to those restrictions and reinforced that people should be in quarantine nowadays.<ref name=\"5th\">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/04/khabib-nurmagomedov-out-of-ufc-249-fight-vs-tony-ferguson|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov confirms he's out of UFC 249: 'I can\u2019t control it all'|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Danny Segura|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/2/21205923/khabib-nurmagomedov-fires-back-at-criticism-over-not-fighting-tony-ferguson-at-ufc-249|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov fires back at criticism over not fighting Tony Ferguson at UFC 249|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-04-02|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He later confirmed that he would compete if a location was given and they were able to move him there, but did not see it happening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/4/21206580/khabib-nurmagomedov-ready-to-fight-but-i-dont-know-the-location-this-is-not-professional|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov ready to fight, but \u2018I don\u2019t know the location \u2026 this is not professional\u2019|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe UFC announced on April 6 that Nurmagomedov will be replaced by former [[List of WSOF champions#Lightweight Championship|WSOF Lightweight Champion]] [[Justin Gaethje]] and an interim title will be disputed between him and Tony Ferguson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29002048/dana-white-says-tony-ferguson-justin-gaethje-headline-ufc-249|title=Dana White says Tony Ferguson-Justin Gaethje to headline UFC 249|publisher=espn.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The rest of the card suffered a few changes, with the following fights being added to the card:<ref name=\"NewCard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209211/ufc-announces-updated-lineup-for-ufc-249-andrade-vs-namajunas-2-still-co-headlines|title=UFC 249 fight card announced, Andrade vs. Namajunas 2 still co-headlines|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n*A heavyweight bout between former [[UFC Heavyweight Championship]] challenger [[Francis Ngannou]] and [[Jairzinho Rozenstruik]]. The bout was originally scheduled to headline [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]] on March 28, but the event was cancelled due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King and John Morgan|date=2020-03-15|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n*A heavyweight bout between [[Greg Hardy]] and Yorgan de Castro; the bout was scheduled for [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n*A welterweight bout between [[Vicente Luque]] and [[Niko Price]]; both fighters were expected to face different opponents at [[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]].\n*[[Islam Makhachev]] was expected to face [[Alexander Hernandez]] at a lightweight bout, but was removed from the event due to travel restrictions and replaced by Omar Morales.\n*A bantamweight bout between [[Marlon Vera]] and former [[UFC Flyweight Championship]] challenger [[Ray Borg]]; Vera was expected to compete against a different opponent at [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n*Ottman Azaitar was expected to face Khama Worthy at a lightweight bout, but was removed from the event due to travel restrictions and replaced by [[Michael Johnson (fighter)|Michael Johnson]].\n*A light heavyweight bout between [[Ryan Spann]] and [[Sam Alvey]]; Alvey was expected to compete against a different opponent at [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n\nThe following fights were removed from the event and are expected to be rescheduled for future cards: a light heavyweight bout between [[Magomed Ankalaev]] and [[Ion Cu\u021belaba]] (a rematch from their meeting at [[UFC Fight Night: Benavidez vs. Figueiredo]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/2/29/21159660/ufc-norfolk-results-magomed-ankalaev-earns-ko-over-ion-cutelaba-in-highly-controversial-stoppage|title=UFC Norfolk results: Magomed Ankalaev earns KO over Ion Cutelaba in highly controversial stoppage|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-02-29|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>; a heavyweight bout between [[Ben Rothwell]] and [[Gian Villante]]; a middleweight bout between [[Karl Roberson]] and Makhmud Muradov; a bantamweight bout between Hunter Azure and Umar Nurmagomedov.<ref name=\"NewCard\" />\n\nA location for the event was not revealed, but Dana White said the UFC's temporary home will host U.S.-based fighters who aren't barred from traveling domestically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/7/21211634/dana-white-covid-19-plans-weekly-fights-at-ufc-249-location-a-private-island-and-joe-rogan|title=Dana White\u2019s COVID-19 plan: Two months of weekly fights at UFC 249 location, a private island, and Joe Rogan|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Fight card==\n{{MMAevent}}\n{{MMAevent card|Main card}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Tony Ferguson]]\n|vs.\n|[[Justin Gaethje]]\n|\n|\n|\n|For the interim [[UFC Lightweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Women's Strawweight\n|[[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]]\n|vs.\n|TBA\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Heavyweight\n|[[Francis Ngannou]]\n|vs.\n|[[Jairzinho Rozenstruik]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Heavyweight\n|[[Greg Hardy]]\n|vs.\n|Yorgan de Castro\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Welterweight\n|[[Vicente Luque]]\n|vs.\n|[[Niko Price]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Featherweight  \n|[[Jeremy Stephens]]\n|vs.\n|[[Calvin Kattar]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent card|Preliminary Card (ESPN)|header=no}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Middleweight\n|[[Ronaldo Souza]]\n|vs.\n|[[Uriah Hall]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Alexander Hernandez]]\n|vs.\n|Omar Antonio Morales Ferrer\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Bantamweight\n|[[Marlon Vera]]\n|vs.\n|[[Ray Borg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Light Heavyweight\n|[[Ryan Spann]]\n|vs.\n|[[Sam Alvey]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent card|Preliminary Card (UFC Fight Pass)|header=no}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Michael Johnson (fighter)|Michael Johnson]]\n|vs.\n|Khama Worthy\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Women\u2019s Bantamweight\n|[[Sijara Eubanks]]\n|vs.\n|[[Sarah Moras]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent end|notes=yes|MMAevent bout=}}\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/event/ufc-249|title=UFC 249: Ferguson vs. Gaethje|publisher=Ultimate Fighting Championship|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|New York City|Martial Arts}}\n* [[List of UFC events]]\n* [[List of current UFC fighters]]\n* [[2020 in UFC]]\n* [[Mixed martial arts in New York]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}} \n{{UFC Events}}\n{{2020 in mixed martial arts}}\n\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship events]]\n[[Category:2020 in mixed martial arts]]\n[[Category:Sports in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scheduled mixed martial arts events]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports\u200e]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|UFC mixed martial arts event in 2020}}\n{{Infobox MMA event\n|name= UFC 249: Ferguson vs. Gaethje\n|image= UFC 249 poster.jpg\n|promotion=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n|date={{start date|2020|04|18}}\n|venue= [[TBA]]\n|city= [[TBA]]\n|attendance=\n|gate=\n|previousevent=[[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]]\n|followingevent=[[UFC Fight Night: Smith vs. Teixeira]]\n}}\n\n'''''UFC 249: Ferguson vs Gaethje''''' was an upcoming [[mixed martial arts]] event produced by the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], scheduled to take place on April 18, 2020.<ref name=\"UFC249\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/mixed-martial-arts/ufc-249-khabib-nurmagomedov-tony-ferguson-1.39502080|title=Khabib vs. Ferguson set for UFC 249 at Barclays|publisher=newsday.com|author=Mark La Monica|date=2019-12-14|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>. It was canceled on April 9.<ref>https://twitter.com/espnmma/status/1248371420226347008</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA [[UFC Lightweight Championship]] bout between the current champion [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]] and former interim champion [[Tony Ferguson]] (also [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Lesnar vs. Team dos Santos]] welterweight winner) was slated to headline this event.<ref name=\"UFC249\" /> The pairing has previously been scheduled and cancelled for various reasons on four separate occasions ([[The Ultimate Fighter: Team McGregor vs. Team Faber#The Ultimate Fighter 22 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter: Team McGregor vs. Team Faber Finale]], [[UFC on Fox: Teixeira vs. Evans]], [[UFC 209]] and [[UFC 223]]) over the last four years.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mmafighting.com/2015/10/30/9645620/edson-barboza-steps-in-for-khabib-nurmagomedov-to-face-tony-ace-tony-ferguson|title= Edson Barboza steps in for Khabib Nurmagomedov to face Tony Ferguson at TUF Finale|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2015-10-30|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-tony-ferguson-out-rashad-evans-vs-glover-teixeira-set-as-new-main-event-040516|title=Tony Ferguson out; Rashad Evans vs. Glover Teixeira set as new main event|publisher=foxsports.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2016-04-05|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/3/3/14805818/ufc-releases-statement-on-khabib-nurmagomedov|title=UFC releases statement on Khabib Nurmagomedov|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2017-03-03|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2018/4/1/17187016/how-did-tony-ferguson-injure-his-knee-ufc-223|title=You won't believe how Tony Ferguson injured his knee and ended up off UFC 223|author=Ryan Harkness|date=2018-04-01|publisher=mmamania.com|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> The bout was canceled for a fifth time due to issues related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] ''(see section below)''.\n\n[[File:\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0438\u0431 \u041d\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0433\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432-2. 12.9.2019.jpg|thumb|left|190px|[[Khabib Nurmagomedov]] was expected to make his third title defense at this event, but had to pull out due to [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\n\nA featherweight bout between [[Jeremy Stephens]] and [[Calvin Kattar]] was expected to take place at [[UFC 248]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2020/1/6/21051609/ufc-248-jeremy-stephens-vs-calvin-kattar-march-7-las-vegas|title=UFC 248: Jeremy Stephens vs Calvin Kattar on tap for March 7 in Las Vegas|author=Jesse Holland|date=2020-01-06|publisher=mmamania.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> However, Stephens was removed from the card in mid-January with an injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/jeremy-stephens-injured-out-ufc-248-fight-calvin-kattar|title=Jeremy Stephens injured, out of planned UFC 248 bout vs. Calvin Kattar; rescheduling expected|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|access-date=2020-01-16|date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The pairing was rescheduled for this event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/calvin-kattar-vs-jeremy-stephens-ufc-249|title=Calvin Kattar vs. Jeremy Stephens in the works for UFC 249|author=Nolan King|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|access-date=2020-01-23|date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nA heavyweight bout between [[Shamil Abdurakhimov]] and [[Ciryl Gane]] was scheduled for the event. However on March 5, it was announced that Gane was forced to pull out from the event after he was struck by a [[pneumothorax]] during one of his trainings. The bout was eventually scrapped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/3/5/21166938/ciryl-gane-out-ufc-249-fight-shamil-abdurakhimov|title=Ciryl Gane out of UFC 249 fight with Shamil Abdurakhimov|date=2020-03-05|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nA welterweight bout between former [[List of Bellator champions#Welterweight Championship|Bellator Welterweight Champion]] [[Lyman Good]] and [[Belal Muhammad (fighter)|Belal Muhammad]] was scheduled for this event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/02/ufc-249-belal-muhammad-vs-lyman-good-booked|title=Belal Muhammad vs. Lyman Good added to UFC 249 in Brooklyn|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Farah Hannoun and Mike Bohn|date=2020-02-11|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> The pairing was expected to meet at [[UFC 205]] in November 2016, but Good was pulled after being notified by [[USADA]] due to a potential anti-doping violation stemming from an out-of-competition drug test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/10/lyman-good-receives-usada-notice-pulled-from-ufc-205|title=Lyman Good receives USADA notice, pulled from UFC 205|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Staff|date=2016-10-24|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> However on April 4, Good pulled out due to injury and the bout was scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/04/lyman-good-out-ufc-249-injury-belal-muhammad-opponent|title=Lyman Good out of UFC 249 bout with Belal Muhammad due to injury|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Danny Segura|date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nA women's strawweight bout between former [[UFC Women's Strawweight Championship|UFC Women's Strawweight Champions]] [[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]] and [[Rose Namajunas]] was expected to co-headline the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/01/ufc-249-rose-namajunas-vs-jessica-andrade-rematch-booked|title=Rose Namajunas, Jessica Andrade agree to rematch at UFC 249 in Brooklyn|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Mike Bohn|date=2020-01-09|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The pairing met previously at [[UFC 237]] in May 2019, when Andrade won via second round TKO to capture the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaindia.com/ufc-237-results-jessica-andrade-kos-rose-namajunas-in-round-2-wins-strawweight-belt/|title=UFC 237 results \u2013 Jessica Andrade KO\u2019s Rose Namajunas in round 2, wins strawweight belt|publisher=mmaindia.com|author=Sohail Syed|date=2019-05-12|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In turn, Namajunas pulled out due to personal reasons on April 8 and at this time, there is no word on a potential replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/ufc/story/_/id/29013557/rose-namajunas-pulls-ufc-249-bout-vs-jessica-andrade|title=Rose Namajunas pulls out of UFC 249 bout vs. Jessica Andrade|publisher=espn.com|author=Marc Raimondi and Ariel Helwani|date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/9/21215451/manager-rose-namajunas-withdrew-from-ufc-249-after-covid-19-deaths-in-family|title=Manager: Rose Namajunas withdrew from UFC 249 after COVID-19 deaths in family|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Newswire|date=2020-04-09|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nOn March 12, [[New York (state)|New York]] governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] issued an order restricting mass gatherings and sporting events due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/482976-nyc-governor-shuts-broadway-coronavirus/|title=Broadway is canceled: New York governor orders closure of theaters, ban on gatherings of 500+ due to coronavirus|publisher=rt.com|author=Staff|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> On March 16, UFC president [[Dana White]] announced via a letter to employees shared to the public that this event \"is still scheduled as planned, but the location may change\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King and John Morgan|date=2020-03-15|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On March 18, the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] announced that the event would not be sanctioned to take place in [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thescore.com/mma/news/1965609|title=Commission stops UFC 249 from happening in New York|publisher=thescore.com|author=Nick Baldwin|date=2020-03-18|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On March 23, White revealed that he already had a new location for this event, but would only confirm that it will be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/dana-white-says-he-has-location-for-ufc-249-confirms-closed-door-event|title=Dana White says he has location for UFC 249; confirms closed-door event|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Mike Bohn|date=2020-03-23|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> He added two days later that the card could feature a different lineup depending on the logistics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/dana-white-ufc-249-could-add-francis-ngannou-vs-jairzinho-rozenstruik|title=Dana White: UFC 249 could add Francis Ngannou vs. Jairzinho Rozenstruik, other fights|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2020-03-25|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nKhabib Nurmagomedov stated on March 30 that he was in [[Dagestan]] and his participation in the event could be jeopardized by travel bans related to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28970604/khabib-nurmagomedov-vs-tony-ferguson-likely-again|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov stuck in Russia, hears new Tony Ferguson opponent sought|publisher=espn.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2020-03-30|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> He stated on April 1 that he would probably not be competing at the event due to those restrictions and reinforced that people should be in quarantine nowadays.<ref name=\"5th\">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/04/khabib-nurmagomedov-out-of-ufc-249-fight-vs-tony-ferguson|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov confirms he's out of UFC 249: 'I can\u2019t control it all'|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Danny Segura|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/2/21205923/khabib-nurmagomedov-fires-back-at-criticism-over-not-fighting-tony-ferguson-at-ufc-249|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov fires back at criticism over not fighting Tony Ferguson at UFC 249|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-04-02|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He later confirmed that he would compete if a location was given and they were able to move him there, but did not see it happening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/4/21206580/khabib-nurmagomedov-ready-to-fight-but-i-dont-know-the-location-this-is-not-professional|title=Khabib Nurmagomedov ready to fight, but \u2018I don\u2019t know the location \u2026 this is not professional\u2019|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe UFC announced on April 6 that Nurmagomedov will be replaced by former [[List of WSOF champions#Lightweight Championship|WSOF Lightweight Champion]] [[Justin Gaethje]] and an interim title will be disputed between him and Tony Ferguson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29002048/dana-white-says-tony-ferguson-justin-gaethje-headline-ufc-249|title=Dana White says Tony Ferguson-Justin Gaethje to headline UFC 249|publisher=espn.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The rest of the card suffered a few changes, with the following fights being added to the card:<ref name=\"NewCard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209211/ufc-announces-updated-lineup-for-ufc-249-andrade-vs-namajunas-2-still-co-headlines|title=UFC 249 fight card announced, Andrade vs. Namajunas 2 still co-headlines|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n*A heavyweight bout between former [[UFC Heavyweight Championship]] challenger [[Francis Ngannou]] and [[Jairzinho Rozenstruik]]. The bout was originally scheduled to headline [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]] on March 28, but the event was cancelled due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King and John Morgan|date=2020-03-15|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n*A heavyweight bout between [[Greg Hardy]] and Yorgan de Castro; the bout was scheduled for [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n*A welterweight bout between [[Vicente Luque]] and [[Niko Price]]; both fighters were expected to face different opponents at [[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]].\n*[[Islam Makhachev]] was expected to face [[Alexander Hernandez]] at a lightweight bout, but was removed from the event due to travel restrictions and replaced by Omar Morales.\n*A bantamweight bout between [[Marlon Vera]] and former [[UFC Flyweight Championship]] challenger [[Ray Borg]]; Vera was expected to compete against a different opponent at [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n*Ottman Azaitar was expected to face Khama Worthy at a lightweight bout, but was removed from the event due to travel restrictions and replaced by [[Michael Johnson (fighter)|Michael Johnson]].\n*A light heavyweight bout between [[Ryan Spann]] and [[Sam Alvey]]; Alvey was expected to compete against a different opponent at [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]].\n\nThe following fights were removed from the event and are expected to be rescheduled for future cards: a light heavyweight bout between [[Magomed Ankalaev]] and [[Ion Cu\u021belaba]] (a rematch from their meeting at [[UFC Fight Night: Benavidez vs. Figueiredo]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/2/29/21159660/ufc-norfolk-results-magomed-ankalaev-earns-ko-over-ion-cutelaba-in-highly-controversial-stoppage|title=UFC Norfolk results: Magomed Ankalaev earns KO over Ion Cutelaba in highly controversial stoppage|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2020-02-29|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>; a heavyweight bout between [[Ben Rothwell]] and [[Gian Villante]]; a middleweight bout between [[Karl Roberson]] and Makhmud Muradov; a bantamweight bout between Hunter Azure and Umar Nurmagomedov.<ref name=\"NewCard\" />\n\nA location for the event was not revealed, but Dana White said the UFC's temporary home will host U.S.-based fighters who aren't barred from traveling domestically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/7/21211634/dana-white-covid-19-plans-weekly-fights-at-ufc-249-location-a-private-island-and-joe-rogan|title=Dana White\u2019s COVID-19 plan: Two months of weekly fights at UFC 249 location, a private island, and Joe Rogan|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Fight card==\n{{MMAevent}}\n{{MMAevent card|Main card}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Tony Ferguson]]\n|vs.\n|[[Justin Gaethje]]\n|\n|\n|\n|For the interim [[UFC Lightweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Women's Strawweight\n|[[J\u00e9ssica Andrade]]\n|vs.\n|TBA\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Heavyweight\n|[[Francis Ngannou]]\n|vs.\n|[[Jairzinho Rozenstruik]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Heavyweight\n|[[Greg Hardy]]\n|vs.\n|Yorgan de Castro\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Welterweight\n|[[Vicente Luque]]\n|vs.\n|[[Niko Price]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Featherweight  \n|[[Jeremy Stephens]]\n|vs.\n|[[Calvin Kattar]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent card|Preliminary Card (ESPN)|header=no}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Middleweight\n|[[Ronaldo Souza]]\n|vs.\n|[[Uriah Hall]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Alexander Hernandez]]\n|vs.\n|Omar Antonio Morales Ferrer\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Bantamweight\n|[[Marlon Vera]]\n|vs.\n|[[Ray Borg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Light Heavyweight\n|[[Ryan Spann]]\n|vs.\n|[[Sam Alvey]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent card|Preliminary Card (UFC Fight Pass)|header=no}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Lightweight\n|[[Michael Johnson (fighter)|Michael Johnson]]\n|vs.\n|Khama Worthy\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent bout\n|Women\u2019s Bantamweight\n|[[Sijara Eubanks]]\n|vs.\n|[[Sarah Moras]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n}}\n{{MMAevent end|notes=yes|MMAevent bout=}}\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/event/ufc-249|title=UFC 249: Ferguson vs. Gaethje|publisher=Ultimate Fighting Championship|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|New York City|Martial Arts}}\n* [[List of UFC events]]\n* [[List of current UFC fighters]]\n* [[2020 in UFC]]\n* [[Mixed martial arts in New York]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}} \n{{UFC Events}}\n{{2020 in mixed martial arts}}\n\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship events]]\n[[Category:2020 in mixed martial arts]]\n[[Category:Sports in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial arts in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scheduled mixed martial arts events]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports\u200e]]\n", "name_user": "Longdongwong", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UFC_249"}
{"title_page": "Gough Island", "text_new": "{{short description|Island in the South Atlantic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox islands\n | name          = Gough Island <br> <small>Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares</small>\n | map           = South Atlantic\n| image_name    = [[File:Gough island top view.png|300px]]\n| image_caption = View of Gough Island\n| image_alt     = View of Gough Island\n| area_km2      = 91\n| length_km     = 13\n| width_km      = 7\n| elevation_m = 910\n| highest_mount = [[Edinburgh Peak]]\n| location      = [[South Atlantic Ocean]]\n| archipelago   = [[Tristan da Cunha]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|40|19|0|S|9|56|0|W|region:SH_type:isle_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| country_admin_divisions = [[St Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n| footnotes        = \n| module =\n  {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child = yes\n  |ID = 740\n  |Year = 1995\n  |Criteria = Natural: (vii), (x)\n  }}\n{{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_date = 20 November 2008\n| designation1_number = 1868<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gough Island|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/1868|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n[[file:Gough.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Map of Gough island]]\n[[File:Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Botany (1981) (20450043601).jpg|thumb|East coast of Gough Island with 115 m high Penguin Islet lying 0.8 km off the point]]\n'''Gough Island''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0261|\u0252|f}}), also known historically as '''Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares''' after the [[Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares|Portuguese explorer]], is a rugged [[volcanic island]] in the South Atlantic Ocean. It is a dependency of [[Tristan da Cunha]] and part of the [[British overseas territory]] of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]. It is about {{convert|400|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east of the Tristan da Cunha archipelago (which includes [[Nightingale Island]] and [[Inaccessible Island]]), {{convert|2400|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-east from [[South Georgia Island]], {{convert|2700|km|mi|abbr=on}} west from [[Cape Town]], and over {{convert|3200|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the nearest point of South America.\n\nGough Island is uninhabited except for the personnel of a [[weather station]] (usually six people) which the [[South African National Antarctic Programme]] has maintained, with British permission, continually on the island since 1956. It is one of the most remote places with a constant human presence. It is part of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] of [[Gough and Inaccessible Islands]]. \n\n==Name==\nThe island was first named ''Ilha de Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares'' on Portuguese maps. It was named Gough Island after the British mariner Captain [[Gough-Calthorpe family|Charles Gough]] of the ''Richmond'', who sighted the island in 1732. Confusion of the unusual Portuguese saint name [[Gon\u00e7alo de Amarante|Gon\u00e7alo]] with Spanish Diego led to the misnomer '''Diego Alvarez Island''' in English-language sources from the 1800s to 1930s.<ref>Report on the geological collections made during the voyage of the ... British Museum (Natural History), Walter Campbell Smith, British Museum (Natural History) \u2013 1930 \"DIEGO ALVAREZ OR GOUGH ISLAND. By W. Campbell Smith. Gough Island, as it seems to be more usually called, lies about 200 miles south of the Tristan da Cunha group in latitude 40\u00b0 S., longitude 10\u00b0 W.1 It is about 8 miles long by 3 ...\"</ref><ref>Plants of Gough Island: (Diego Alvarez) Erling Christophersen \u2013 1934</ref><ref>The Antarctic dictionary: a complete guide to Antarctic English \u2013 Page 150 Bernadette Hince \u2013 2000 -\"I went for adventure. to have fun, Gough Island Gough Island was named I. de Goncalo Alvarez on early maps. after its discoverer. Portuguese navigator Goncalo Alvarez. The name was later corrupted to I. Diego Alvarez. and there was confusion about the locality. It was renamed after Captain Charles Gough of the British barque Richmond. who sighted the island in 1713.\"</ref> However, the most likely explanation is that it was simply a misreading of 'Is de Go Alvarez', the name by which the island is represented on some of the early charts, the 'de Go' mutating into 'Diego'.<ref>Raymond John Howgego, ''Historical Encyclopedia of Atlantic Vigias'', London, 2015</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe details of the discovery of Gough Island are unclear, but the most likely occasion is July 1505 by the Portuguese explorer [[Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?pid=S0038-23532008000500005&script=sci_arttext |title=South African Journal of Science \u2013 Gough Island 500 years after its discovery: a bibliography of scientific and popular literature 1505 to 2005 |publisher=Scielo.org.za |date= |accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref> Maps during the next three centuries named the island after him. On some later maps, this was erroneously given as Diego Alvarez.\n\nAccording to some historians, the British merchant [[Anthony de la Roch\u00e9]] was the first to land on the island, in the austral autumn of 1675.<ref name=\"wacenm\">{{cite journal | author = Wace N.M. | year = 1969 | title = The discovery, exploitation and settlement of the Tristan da Cunha Islands | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society of Australasia (South Australian Branch) | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 11\u201340 }}</ref><ref name=\"multiple\">Capt. Francisco de Seixas y Lovera, [https://books.google.com/books?id=l7PWN7_1wAoC&dq=Descripcion%20geographica%2C%20y%20derrotero%20de%20la%20region%20austral%20Magallanica&pg=PT96#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''Descripcion geographica, y derrotero de la region austral Magallanica.  Que se dirige al Rey nuestro se\u00f1or, gran monarca de Espa\u00f1a, y sus dominios en Europa, Emperador del Nuevo Mundo Americano, y Rey de los reynos de la Filipinas y Malucas''], Madrid, Antonio de Zafra, 1690. ([[wikisource:Anthony de la Roch\u00e9 and Roch\u00e9 Island (South Georgia) in 1675|Relevant fragment]])</ref><ref name=\"Laperouse\">J.-F.G. de la P\u00e9rouse, F.A.M. de la R\u00faa. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VqdCAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false A Voyage Round the World, Performed in the Years 1785, 1786, 1787, and 1788, by the ''Boussole'' and ''Astrolabe'': Under the Command of J.-F.G. de la P\u00e9rouse, Volume 1.] London: Lackington, Allen, and Company, 1807. pp.71-81.</ref>\n\n[[Gough-Calthorpe family|Charles Gough]] rediscovered the island on 3 March 1732, thinking it was a new find.<ref>Gough's log is preserved in the East India Collection at the British Library. The entry for 3 March 1732 is printed in Gabriel Wright (pub.), \"A New Nautical Directory for the East-India and China Navigation\", 7th edn, London, 1804, p. 394.</ref>\nIt had been named Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares since 1505 after the captain of [[Vasco da Gama]]'s flagship on his epic voyage to the east, and under this name it was marked with reasonable accuracy on the charts of the South Atlantic during the following 230 or so years. Then, in 1732, Captain Gough of the British ship ''Richmond'' reported the discovery of a new island, which he placed 400 miles to the east of Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares. Fifty years later cartographers realised that the two islands were the same, and despite the priority of the Portuguese discovery, and the greater accuracy of the position given by them, \"Gough's Island\" was the name adopted.<ref>Heaney, J.B., Holdgate, M.W. (1957). The Gough Island Scientific Survey. The Geographical Journal, Vol. 123, No. 1, pp. 20\u201331</ref>\n\nIn the early 19th century, sealers sometimes briefly inhabited the island. The earliest known example is a sealing gang from the U.S. ship ''Rambler'' (Captain Joseph Bowditch) which remained on the island in the 1804\u20131805 season.<ref>R.K. Headland (Ed.) ''Historical Antarctic Sealing Industry'', Scott Polar Research Institute (University of Cambridge), 2018, p.176. {{ISBN|978-0-901021-26-7}}</ref> The sealing era lasted from 1804 to 1910 during which 34 sealing vessels are known to have visited the island, one of which was lost offshore.<ref>Headland, p.167.</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish National Antarctic Expedition]] on the ''[[Scotia (barque)|Scotia]]'' made the first visit to the island by a scientific party on 21 April 1904, when [[William Speirs Bruce]] and others collected specimens.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Rudmose Brown | first1 = R. N. | last2 = Pirie | first2 = J. H. | last3 = Mossman | first3 = R. C. | title = The Voyage of the Scotia | publisher = Mercat Press | location =  Edinburgh | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-1-84183-044-5 | pages =132\u201334}}</ref> The [[Shackleton\u2013Rowett Expedition]] also stopped at the island in 1922.<ref>{{cite book|author= Wild, Frank|title= Shackleton's last voyage: The Story of the ''Quest''|chapter-url= https://archive.org/stream/shackletonslastv00wilduoft/shackletonslastv00wilduoft_djvu.txt|chapter=Chapter XIII: Diego Alvarez or Gough Island |year=1923 |accessdate= 18 December 2016}}</ref> \n\nGough Island was formally claimed in 1938 for Britain, during a visit by HMS ''Milford'' of the Royal Navy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btinternet.com/~sa_sa/gough_island/gough_island.html |title=Gough Island, South Atlantic Ocean |publisher=Btinternet.com |accessdate=2012-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012070944/http://www.btinternet.com/~sa_sa/gough_island/gough_island.html |archivedate=12 October 2012 }}</ref> In 1995, the island was inscribed as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. In 2004, the site was extended to include [[Inaccessible Island]] and renamed [[Gough and Inaccessible Islands]].\n\nGough Island is the only place outside South America from which the [[solar eclipse of September 12, 2034]], will be visible; the centre of the path of totality crosses over the island.\n\n==Geography and geology==\n{{main article|Geography of Gough Island}}\nGough Island is roughly rectangular with a length of {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}} and a width of {{convert|7|km|mi}}. It has an area of {{convert|91|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and rises to heights of over {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |title=Gough Island |publisher=Sanap.ac.za |date= |accessdate=2012-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Topographic features include the highest peak, Edinburgh Peak, Hags Tooth, Mount Rowett, Sea Elephant Bay, Quest Bay, and Hawkins Bay.\n\nIt includes small satellite islands and rocks such as Southwest Island, Saddle Island (South), Tristiana Rock, Isolda Rock (West), Round Island, Cone Island, Lot's Wife, Church Rock (North), Penguin Island (Northeast), and The Admirals (East). \n\n===Climate===\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen system]], Gough Island features an [[oceanic climate]] (''Cfb''). Gough Island's temperatures are very solid between {{convert|11|C|F}} and {{convert|17|C|F}} during the day year-round, due to its isolated position far out in the Atlantic Ocean. The Atlantic is much cooler in the southern hemisphere than the northern, but frosts are still very rare. As a result, summers are not very hot. Precipitation is high for all of the year and sunshine hours are low. Snow falls in the interior, but is rare at sea level.<ref>{{cite book|url={{Google books|fRJtB2MNdJMC|page=471|plainurl=yes}}|title=Encyclopedia of the Antarctic|first=Beau|last=Riffenburgh|date=20 May 2018|publisher=Taylor & Francis|via=Google Books|isbn=978-0-415-97024-2}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gough Island (1961\u20131990, extremes 1956\u20131990)\n|single line = Y\n|metric first = Y\n|Jan record high C = 26.4\n|Feb record high C = 25.7\n|Mar record high C = 25.9\n|Apr record high C = 22.6\n|May record high C = 20.5\n|Jun record high C = 20.6\n|Jul record high C = 19.3\n|Aug record high C = 21.7\n|Sep record high C = 19.3\n|Oct record high C = 21.4\n|Nov record high C = 23.9\n|Dec record high C = 25.1\n|year record high C = 26.4\n|Jan high C = 17.2\n|Feb high C = 17.4\n|Mar high C = 16.9\n|Apr high C = 15.4\n|May high C = 13.7\n|Jun high C = 12.4\n|Jul high C = 11.5\n|Aug high C = 11.2\n|Sep high C = 11.5\n|Oct high C = 12.9\n|Nov high C = 14.9\n|Dec high C = 16.2\n|year high C = 14.3\n|Jan mean C = 13.9\n|Feb mean C = 14.4\n|Mar mean C = 13.9\n|Apr mean C = 12.8\n|May mean C = 11.3\n|Jun mean C = 10.0\n|Jul mean C = 9.1\n|Aug mean C = 8.9\n|Sep mean C = 8.9\n|Oct mean C = 10.1\n|Nov mean C = 11.9\n|Dec mean C = 13.2\n|year mean C = 11.5\n|Jan low C = 11.1\n|Feb low C = 11.6\n|Mar low C = 11.3\n|Apr low C = 10.4\n|May low C = 8.9\n|Jun low C = 7.6\n|Jul low C = 6.6\n|Aug low C = 6.5\n|Sep low C = 6.6\n|Oct low C = 7.8\n|Nov low C = 9.4\n|Dec low C = 10.3\n|year low C = 9.0\n|Jan record low C = 5.3\n|Feb record low C = 5.1\n|Mar record low C = 4.8\n|Apr record low C = 3.7\n|May record low C = 1.4\n|Jun record low C = 0.1\n|Jul record low C = -0.9\n|Aug record low C = -2.7\n|Sep record low C = 0.2\n|Oct record low C = 0.5\n|Nov record low C = 2.4\n|Dec record low C = 4.1\n|year record low C = -2.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 210\n|Feb precipitation mm = 183\n|Mar precipitation mm = 254\n|Apr precipitation mm = 276\n|May precipitation mm = 286\n|Jun precipitation mm = 310\n|Jul precipitation mm = 273\n|Aug precipitation mm = 304\n|Sep precipitation mm = 270\n|Oct precipitation mm = 249\n|Nov precipitation mm = 213\n|Dec precipitation mm = 241\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 16\n|Feb precipitation days = 13\n|Mar precipitation days = 18\n|Apr precipitation days = 19\n|May precipitation days = 21\n|Jun precipitation days = 22\n|Jul precipitation days = 23\n|Aug precipitation days = 21\n|Sep precipitation days = 20\n|Oct precipitation days = 18\n|Nov precipitation days = 16\n|Dec precipitation days = 18\n|year precipitation days = 225\n|Jan humidity = 81\n|Feb humidity = 82\n|Mar humidity = 82\n|Apr humidity = 82\n|May humidity = 82\n|Jun humidity = 83\n|Jul humidity = 83\n|Aug humidity = 83\n|Sep humidity = 81\n|Oct humidity = 81\n|Nov humidity = 81\n|Dec humidity = 81\n|year humidity = 82\n|Jan sun = 183.8\n|Feb sun = 148.8\n|Mar sun = 123.3\n|Apr sun = 95.6\n|May sun = 83.7\n|Jun sun = 60.4\n|Jul sun = 71.7\n|Aug sun = 87.5\n|Sep sun = 101.6\n|Oct sun = 128.5\n|Nov sun = 161.4\n|Dec sun = 182.9\n|year sun = 1429.2\n|source 1 = NOAA,<ref name=\"NOAA\">{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG__I/UA/68906.TXT\n| title = Gough Island Climate Normals 1961\u22121990\n| publisher = National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration\n| accessdate = November 21, 2013}}</ref> [[Deutscher Wetterdienst]] (extremes)<ref name = DWD>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dwd.de/DWD/klima/beratung/ak/ak_689060_kt.pdf\n| title = Klimatafel von Gough Island / S\u00fcdatlantik / Gro\u00dfbritannien\n| work = Baseline climate means (1961\u20131990) from stations all over the world\n| publisher = Deutscher Wetterdienst\n| language = German\n| accessdate = November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n|source 2 = climate-charts.com<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.climate-charts.com/Locations/u/UA68906.php\n|title = Climate Statistics for Gough Island, South Africa\n|date = 20 February 1998\n|access-date = 7 March 2012\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160820193201/http://www.climate-charts.com/Locations/u/UA68906.php\n|archive-date = 20 August 2016\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Fauna and flora==\n[[File:Blechnum and Phylica.png|thumb|upright|The fern ''[[Blechnum]]'' and tree ''[[Phylica]]'' on Gough Island]]\nGough and [[Inaccessible Island]] are a protected [[wildlife reserve]], which has been designated a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=Unesco>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/740|title=Gough and Inaccessible Islands|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=UNESCO Organization}}</ref> It has been described as one of the least disrupted [[ecosystem]]s of its kind and one of the best shelters for nesting [[seabird]]s in the Atlantic. In particular, it is host to almost the entire world population of the [[Tristan albatross]] (''Diomedea dabbenena'') and the [[Atlantic petrel]] (''Pterodroma incerta'').<ref>Cuthbert, J. & Sommer, E. ''[http://www.marineornithology.org/PDF/32_1/32_1_97-103.pdf Population size and trends of four globally threatened seabirds at Gough Island, South Atlantic Ocean]''. Marine Ornithology 32: 97\u2013103.</ref> The island is also home to the almost flightless [[Gough moorhen]],<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Sb1IJYzXZhUC&pg=RA1-PA60&lpg=RA1-PA60&dq=%22george+Comer%22+antartica |title=Flightless birds |author=Roots, Clive |location=Westport, Conn. |publisher=Greenwood Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-313-33545-7 |accessdate=2008-03-31 |page=60}}</ref> and the critically endangered [[Gough bunting]].\n\n===Birds===\n[[File:Gough Bunting Male.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A male Gough Bunting on the island]]\nThe island has been identified as an [[Important Bird Area]] (IBA) by [[BirdLife International]] for its endemic landbirds and as a breeding site for [[seabird]]s. Birds for which the IBA has conservation significance include [[northern rockhopper penguin]]s (30,000 breeding pairs), [[Tristan albatross]]es (1500\u20132000 pairs), [[sooty albatross]]es (5000 pairs), [[Atlantic yellow-nosed albatross]]es (5000 pairs), [[broad-billed prion]]s (1,750,000 pairs), [[Kerguelen petrel]]s (20,000 pairs), [[soft-plumaged petrel]]s (400,000 pairs), [[Atlantic petrel]]s (900,000 pairs), [[great-winged petrel]]s (5000 pairs), [[grey petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[great shearwater]]s (100,000 pairs), [[little shearwater]]s (10,000 pairs), [[grey-backed storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[white-faced storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[white-bellied storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[Antarctic tern]]s (500 pairs), [[southern skua]]s (500 pairs), [[Gough moorhen]]s (2500 pairs) and [[Gough bunting]]s (3000 individuals).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.birdlife.org |title= Gough Island |accessdate=2012-10-25 |work= Important Bird Areas factsheet |publisher= BirdLife International |year= 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Mammals===\n[[File:1954stampGoughTristan.jpg|thumb|Elephant seal at Gough Island depicted on a 1954 Tristan da Cunha stamp]]\nThe island has a large breeding population of [[subantarctic fur seal]]s and some [[southern right whale]]s still migrate around the island.\n\nHouse mice are currently present on the island. (see [[Gough Island#Invasive species|Invasive Species]])\n\n===Invasive species===\n\n====Pearlwort (''Sagina procumbens'')====\nIn 1998 a number of [[Sagina procumbens|procumbent pearlwort (''Sagina procumbens'')]] plants were found on the island which are capable of dramatically transforming the upland plant ecosystem (as it has on the [[Prince Edward Islands]]).\n<ref>Cooper, J. et al., [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/island_invasives/pdfhqprint/2cooper.pdf \"Earth, fire and water: applying novel techniques to eradicate the invasive plant, procumbent pearlwort ''Sagina procumbens'', on Gough Island, a World Heritage Site in the South Atlantic\"], [[Invasive Species Specialist Group]], 2010, Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref> Eradication efforts are ongoing but are expected to require years of 'concerted effort'.\n<ref>Bisser, P. et al., [http://www.conservationevidence.com/individual-study/2327 \"Strategies to eradicate the invasive plant procumbent pearlwort ''Sagina procumbens'' on Gough Island, 2010\"], Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref>\n\n====House mice====\nIn April 2007 researchers published evidence that predation by introduced [[house mouse|house mice]] on seabird chicks is occurring at levels that might drive the Tristan albatross and the Atlantic petrel to extinction.<ref>{{cite journal\n|author1=R M Wanless |author2=A Angel |author3=R J Cuthbert |author4=G M Hilton |author5=P G Ryan | title = Can predation by invasive mice drive seabird extinctions?\n| year = 2007\n| volume = 3\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 241\u2013244\n| doi = 10.1098/rsbl.2007.0120\n| pmid = 17412667\n| pmc = 2464706\n| journal = Biology Letters}}</ref>\nThe [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] awarded \u00a362,000 by the UK government's Overseas Territories Environment Programme to fund additional research on the Gough Island mice and a feasibility study of how best to deal with them. The grant also paid for the assessment of a [[rat]] problem on Tristan da Cunha island. Trials for a method of eradicating the mice through baiting were commenced,<ref>R. J. Cuthbert1\n, P. Visser et al., [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/Island_Invasives/pdfwebview/1Cuthbert.pdf \"Preparations for the eradication of mice from Gough Island: results of bait acceptance trials above ground and around cave systems\"], 2011,  Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref> and ultimately a \u00a39.2m eradication programme was planned, and set to begin in 2020, with the island expected to be mouse free by 2022. The inception of this programme in 2020 was confirmed in 2018. The programme will use helicopters to drop cereal pellets containing the rodenticide [[brodifacoum]]. As of October 2018, it is estimated that as many as 2,000,000 fewer eggs and chicks are being raised due to the impact of mice on the island, threatening the extinction of several species of seabirds that breed exclusively or nearly exclusively on Gough Island.<ref name=\"killer\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/ibi.12664|title=The impacts of introduced House Mice on the breeding success of nesting seabirds on Gough Island|last=Caravaggi|first=Anthony|date=22 October 2018|journal=Ibis|volume=161|issue=3|pages=648\u2013661|publisher=IBIS International Journal of Avian Science}}</ref> Gough has also been identified as the third most important island in the world (out of 107 islands) to be targeted for the removal of non-native invasive mammals to save threatened species from extinction and make major progress towards achieving global conservation targets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Butchart|first=Stuart H. M.|last2=Micol|first2=Thierry|last3=Cranwell|first3=Steve|last4=Pasachnik|first4=Stesha A.|last5=Wanless|first5=Ross|last6=Fisher|first6=Robert N.|last7=Griffiths|first7=Richard|last8=Pierce|first8=Ray|last9=Borroto-P\u00e1ez|first9=Rafael|date=2019-03-27|title=Globally important islands where eradicating invasive mammals will benefit highly threatened vertebrates|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=14|issue=3|pages=e0212128|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0212128|pmid=30917126|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2019PLoSO..1412128H}}</ref>\n\n==Weather station==\nA [[weather station]] has been operating on Gough Island since 1956. It is operated as part of the network of the [[South African Weather Service]]. Because [[cold front]]s approach South Africa from the south-west, the Gough station is particularly important in forecasting winter weather. Initially it was housed in the station at The Glen, but moved in 1963 to the South lowlands of the island, more precisely 40\u00b020'57.68\"S  9\u00b052'49.13\"W. The new location improved the validity and reliability of the data acquired for use in modeling.\n\n===Human presence===\nEach year a new overwintering team arrives by ship from [[Cape Town]] (beginning in 2012, the ''[[S. A. Agulhas II]]'') to staff the weather station and perform scientific research. The team for a particular year may be termed as \"Gough\" and an expedition number: for example, the 1956 team were \"Gough 01\", and the team for 2013 were \"Gough 58\". Each new team directly replaces the departing one, thereby maintaining a continual human presence on the island.<ref>[http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html \"South Africa National Antarctic Programme - Gough Island Teams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |date=12 September 2017 }}, Retrieved 12 February 2014</ref><ref>Chris Bell, [http://goughisland58.blogspot.co.uk/ \"Chris Bell's Blog from Gough 58\"], Retrieved 12 February 2014</ref>\n\nA team normally consists of:\n* A senior [[meteorologist]]\n* Two junior meteorologists\n* A [[radio technician]]\n* A [[medic]]\n* A [[diesel mechanic]]\n* A number of [[biologist]]s (depending on ongoing research projects)\n\nThe team is supplied with enough food to last the whole year. People and cargo are landed either by helicopter, from a helideck-equipped supply ship, or by a fixed crane atop a cliff near the station (a place aptly called \"Crane Point\").\n\nIn 2014 a member of the research team choked to death on the island and his body was taken back to South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa-technology/sa-man-dies-gough-island|title=SA man dies on Gough Island|author=|date=|website=www.enca.com}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n<gallery>\nFile:Gough Island Map.jpg|Relief map\nFile:Orthographic projection over Gough Island.png|Orthographic projection\nFile:Gough Island Landsat.jpg|Satellite map\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|South African National Antarctic Programme}}\n* {{annotated link|SANAE}}\n* {{annotated link|Marion Island}}\n* {{annotated link|S. A. Agulhas}}\n* {{annotated link|S. A. Agulhas II}}\n* {{annotated link|Nigel Morritt Wace}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.goughisland.com www.goughisland.com] - The Gough Island Restoration Project website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html The South African Weather Station on Gough Island] \u2013 Official website.\n*[https://www.facebook.com/groups/57386398567 Facebook Groups] - Gough Island team discussions\n*[https://whc.unesco.org/sites/740.htm Gough and Inaccessible Islands] - UNESCO wildlife reserve publication\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/chantal_steyn/sets/72157612980545317/ Photographs of Gough Island] - Flickr publication by Chantal van Staden.\n\n{{Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom}}\n{{SANAP navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Seabird colonies]]\n[[Category:South African National Antarctic Programme]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Saint Helena]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in British Overseas Territories]]\n[[Category:Seal hunting]]\n[[Category:Mid-Atlantic Ridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Island in the South Atlantic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox islands\n | name          = Gough Island <br> <small>Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares</small>\n | map           = South Atlantic\n| image_name    = [[File:Gough island top view.png|300px]]\n| image_caption = View of Gough Island\n| image_alt     = View of Gough Island\n| area_km2      = 91\n| length_km     = 13\n| width_km      = 7\n| elevation_m = 910\n| highest_mount = [[Edinburgh Peak]]\n| location      = [[South Atlantic Ocean]]\n| archipelago   = [[Tristan da Cunha]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|40|19|0|S|9|56|0|W|region:SH_type:isle_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| country_admin_divisions = [[St Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n| footnotes        = \n| module =\n  {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child = yes\n  |ID = 740\n  |Year = 1995\n  |Criteria = Natural: (vii), (x)\n  }}\n{{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_date = 20 November 2008\n| designation1_number = 1868<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gough Island|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/1868|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n[[file:Gough.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Map of Gough island]]\n[[File:Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Botany (1981) (20450043601).jpg|thumb|East coast of Gough Island with 115 m high Penguin Islet lying 0.8 km off the point]]\n'''Gough Island''' {{IPAc-en|\u0261|\u0252|f}}, also known historically as '''Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares''' after the [[Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares|Portuguese explorer]], is a rugged [[volcanic island]] in the South Atlantic Ocean. It is a dependency of [[Tristan da Cunha]] and part of the [[British overseas territory]] of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]. It is about {{convert|400|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east of the Tristan da Cunha archipelago (which includes [[Nightingale Island]] and [[Inaccessible Island]]), {{convert|2400|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-east from [[South Georgia Island]], {{convert|2700|km|mi|abbr=on}} west from [[Cape Town]], and over {{convert|3200|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the nearest point of South America.\n\nGough Island is uninhabited except for the personnel of a [[weather station]] (usually six people) which the [[South African National Antarctic Programme]] has maintained, with British permission, continually on the island since 1956. It is one of the most remote places with a constant human presence. It is part of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] of [[Gough and Inaccessible Islands]]. \n\n==Name==\nThe island was first named ''Ilha de Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares'' on Portuguese maps. It was named Gough Island after the British mariner Captain [[Gough-Calthorpe family|Charles Gough]] of the ''Richmond'', who sighted the island in 1732. Confusion of the unusual Portuguese saint name [[Gon\u00e7alo de Amarante|Gon\u00e7alo]] with Spanish Diego led to the misnomer '''Diego Alvarez Island''' in English-language sources from the 1800s to 1930s.<ref>Report on the geological collections made during the voyage of the ... British Museum (Natural History), Walter Campbell Smith, British Museum (Natural History) \u2013 1930 \"DIEGO ALVAREZ OR GOUGH ISLAND. By W. Campbell Smith. Gough Island, as it seems to be more usually called, lies about 200 miles south of the Tristan da Cunha group in latitude 40\u00b0 S., longitude 10\u00b0 W.1 It is about 8 miles long by 3 ...\"</ref><ref>Plants of Gough Island: (Diego Alvarez) Erling Christophersen \u2013 1934</ref><ref>The Antarctic dictionary: a complete guide to Antarctic English \u2013 Page 150 Bernadette Hince \u2013 2000 -\"I went for adventure. to have fun, Gough Island Gough Island was named I. de Goncalo Alvarez on early maps. after its discoverer. Portuguese navigator Goncalo Alvarez. The name was later corrupted to I. Diego Alvarez. and there was confusion about the locality. It was renamed after Captain Charles Gough of the British barque Richmond. who sighted the island in 1713.\"</ref> However, the most likely explanation is that it was simply a misreading of 'Is de Go Alvarez', the name by which the island is represented on some of the early charts, the 'de Go' mutating into 'Diego'.<ref>Raymond John Howgego, ''Historical Encyclopedia of Atlantic Vigias'', London, 2015</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe details of the discovery of Gough Island are unclear, but the most likely occasion is July 1505 by the Portuguese explorer [[Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?pid=S0038-23532008000500005&script=sci_arttext |title=South African Journal of Science \u2013 Gough Island 500 years after its discovery: a bibliography of scientific and popular literature 1505 to 2005 |publisher=Scielo.org.za |date= |accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref> Maps during the next three centuries named the island after him. On some later maps, this was erroneously given as Diego Alvarez.\n\nAccording to some historians, the British merchant [[Anthony de la Roch\u00e9]] was the first to land on the island, in the austral autumn of 1675.<ref name=\"wacenm\">{{cite journal | author = Wace N.M. | year = 1969 | title = The discovery, exploitation and settlement of the Tristan da Cunha Islands | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society of Australasia (South Australian Branch) | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 11\u201340 }}</ref><ref name=\"multiple\">Capt. Francisco de Seixas y Lovera, [https://books.google.com/books?id=l7PWN7_1wAoC&dq=Descripcion%20geographica%2C%20y%20derrotero%20de%20la%20region%20austral%20Magallanica&pg=PT96#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''Descripcion geographica, y derrotero de la region austral Magallanica.  Que se dirige al Rey nuestro se\u00f1or, gran monarca de Espa\u00f1a, y sus dominios en Europa, Emperador del Nuevo Mundo Americano, y Rey de los reynos de la Filipinas y Malucas''], Madrid, Antonio de Zafra, 1690. ([[wikisource:Anthony de la Roch\u00e9 and Roch\u00e9 Island (South Georgia) in 1675|Relevant fragment]])</ref><ref name=\"Laperouse\">J.-F.G. de la P\u00e9rouse, F.A.M. de la R\u00faa. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VqdCAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false A Voyage Round the World, Performed in the Years 1785, 1786, 1787, and 1788, by the ''Boussole'' and ''Astrolabe'': Under the Command of J.-F.G. de la P\u00e9rouse, Volume 1.] London: Lackington, Allen, and Company, 1807. pp.71-81.</ref>\n\n[[Gough-Calthorpe family|Charles Gough]] rediscovered the island on 3 March 1732, thinking it was a new find.<ref>Gough's log is preserved in the East India Collection at the British Library. The entry for 3 March 1732 is printed in Gabriel Wright (pub.), \"A New Nautical Directory for the East-India and China Navigation\", 7th edn, London, 1804, p. 394.</ref>\nIt had been named Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares since 1505 after the captain of [[Vasco da Gama]]'s flagship on his epic voyage to the east, and under this name it was marked with reasonable accuracy on the charts of the South Atlantic during the following 230 or so years. Then, in 1732, Captain Gough of the British ship ''Richmond'' reported the discovery of a new island, which he placed 400 miles to the east of Gon\u00e7alo \u00c1lvares. Fifty years later cartographers realised that the two islands were the same, and despite the priority of the Portuguese discovery, and the greater accuracy of the position given by them, \"Gough's Island\" was the name adopted.<ref>Heaney, J.B., Holdgate, M.W. (1957). The Gough Island Scientific Survey. The Geographical Journal, Vol. 123, No. 1, pp. 20\u201331</ref>\n\nIn the early 19th century, sealers sometimes briefly inhabited the island. The earliest known example is a sealing gang from the U.S. ship ''Rambler'' (Captain Joseph Bowditch) which remained on the island in the 1804\u20131805 season.<ref>R.K. Headland (Ed.) ''Historical Antarctic Sealing Industry'', Scott Polar Research Institute (University of Cambridge), 2018, p.176. {{ISBN|978-0-901021-26-7}}</ref> The sealing era lasted from 1804 to 1910 during which 34 sealing vessels are known to have visited the island, one of which was lost offshore.<ref>Headland, p.167.</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish National Antarctic Expedition]] on the ''[[Scotia (barque)|Scotia]]'' made the first visit to the island by a scientific party on 21 April 1904, when [[William Speirs Bruce]] and others collected specimens.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Rudmose Brown | first1 = R. N. | last2 = Pirie | first2 = J. H. | last3 = Mossman | first3 = R. C. | title = The Voyage of the Scotia | publisher = Mercat Press | location =  Edinburgh | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-1-84183-044-5 | pages =132\u201334}}</ref> The [[Shackleton\u2013Rowett Expedition]] also stopped at the island in 1922.<ref>{{cite book|author= Wild, Frank|title= Shackleton's last voyage: The Story of the ''Quest''|chapter-url= https://archive.org/stream/shackletonslastv00wilduoft/shackletonslastv00wilduoft_djvu.txt|chapter=Chapter XIII: Diego Alvarez or Gough Island |year=1923 |accessdate= 18 December 2016}}</ref> \n\nGough Island was formally claimed in 1938 for Britain, during a visit by HMS ''Milford'' of the Royal Navy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btinternet.com/~sa_sa/gough_island/gough_island.html |title=Gough Island, South Atlantic Ocean |publisher=Btinternet.com |accessdate=2012-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012070944/http://www.btinternet.com/~sa_sa/gough_island/gough_island.html |archivedate=12 October 2012 }}</ref> In 1995, the island was inscribed as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. In 2004, the site was extended to include [[Inaccessible Island]] and renamed [[Gough and Inaccessible Islands]].\n\nGough Island is the only place outside South America from which the [[solar eclipse of September 12, 2034]], will be visible; the centre of the path of totality crosses over the island.\n\n==Geography and geology==\n{{main article|Geography of Gough Island}}\nGough Island is roughly rectangular with a length of {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}} and a width of {{convert|7|km|mi}}. It has an area of {{convert|91|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and rises to heights of over {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |title=Gough Island |publisher=Sanap.ac.za |date= |accessdate=2012-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |archive-date=12 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Topographic features include the highest peak, Edinburgh Peak, Hags Tooth, Mount Rowett, Sea Elephant Bay, Quest Bay, and Hawkins Bay.\n\nIt includes small satellite islands and rocks such as Southwest Island, Saddle Island (South), Tristiana Rock, Isolda Rock (West), Round Island, Cone Island, Lot's Wife, Church Rock (North), Penguin Island (Northeast), and The Admirals (East). \n\n===Climate===\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen system]], Gough Island features an [[oceanic climate]] (''Cfb''). Gough Island's temperatures are very solid between {{convert|11|C|F}} and {{convert|17|C|F}} during the day year-round, due to its isolated position far out in the Atlantic Ocean. The Atlantic is much cooler in the southern hemisphere than the northern, but frosts are still very rare. As a result, summers are not very hot. Precipitation is high for all of the year and sunshine hours are low. Snow falls in the interior, but is rare at sea level.<ref>{{cite book|url={{Google books|fRJtB2MNdJMC|page=471|plainurl=yes}}|title=Encyclopedia of the Antarctic|first=Beau|last=Riffenburgh|date=20 May 2018|publisher=Taylor & Francis|via=Google Books|isbn=978-0-415-97024-2}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gough Island (1961\u20131990, extremes 1956\u20131990)\n|single line = Y\n|metric first = Y\n|Jan record high C = 26.4\n|Feb record high C = 25.7\n|Mar record high C = 25.9\n|Apr record high C = 22.6\n|May record high C = 20.5\n|Jun record high C = 20.6\n|Jul record high C = 19.3\n|Aug record high C = 21.7\n|Sep record high C = 19.3\n|Oct record high C = 21.4\n|Nov record high C = 23.9\n|Dec record high C = 25.1\n|year record high C = 26.4\n|Jan high C = 17.2\n|Feb high C = 17.4\n|Mar high C = 16.9\n|Apr high C = 15.4\n|May high C = 13.7\n|Jun high C = 12.4\n|Jul high C = 11.5\n|Aug high C = 11.2\n|Sep high C = 11.5\n|Oct high C = 12.9\n|Nov high C = 14.9\n|Dec high C = 16.2\n|year high C = 14.3\n|Jan mean C = 13.9\n|Feb mean C = 14.4\n|Mar mean C = 13.9\n|Apr mean C = 12.8\n|May mean C = 11.3\n|Jun mean C = 10.0\n|Jul mean C = 9.1\n|Aug mean C = 8.9\n|Sep mean C = 8.9\n|Oct mean C = 10.1\n|Nov mean C = 11.9\n|Dec mean C = 13.2\n|year mean C = 11.5\n|Jan low C = 11.1\n|Feb low C = 11.6\n|Mar low C = 11.3\n|Apr low C = 10.4\n|May low C = 8.9\n|Jun low C = 7.6\n|Jul low C = 6.6\n|Aug low C = 6.5\n|Sep low C = 6.6\n|Oct low C = 7.8\n|Nov low C = 9.4\n|Dec low C = 10.3\n|year low C = 9.0\n|Jan record low C = 5.3\n|Feb record low C = 5.1\n|Mar record low C = 4.8\n|Apr record low C = 3.7\n|May record low C = 1.4\n|Jun record low C = 0.1\n|Jul record low C = -0.9\n|Aug record low C = -2.7\n|Sep record low C = 0.2\n|Oct record low C = 0.5\n|Nov record low C = 2.4\n|Dec record low C = 4.1\n|year record low C = -2.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 210\n|Feb precipitation mm = 183\n|Mar precipitation mm = 254\n|Apr precipitation mm = 276\n|May precipitation mm = 286\n|Jun precipitation mm = 310\n|Jul precipitation mm = 273\n|Aug precipitation mm = 304\n|Sep precipitation mm = 270\n|Oct precipitation mm = 249\n|Nov precipitation mm = 213\n|Dec precipitation mm = 241\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 16\n|Feb precipitation days = 13\n|Mar precipitation days = 18\n|Apr precipitation days = 19\n|May precipitation days = 21\n|Jun precipitation days = 22\n|Jul precipitation days = 23\n|Aug precipitation days = 21\n|Sep precipitation days = 20\n|Oct precipitation days = 18\n|Nov precipitation days = 16\n|Dec precipitation days = 18\n|year precipitation days = 225\n|Jan humidity = 81\n|Feb humidity = 82\n|Mar humidity = 82\n|Apr humidity = 82\n|May humidity = 82\n|Jun humidity = 83\n|Jul humidity = 83\n|Aug humidity = 83\n|Sep humidity = 81\n|Oct humidity = 81\n|Nov humidity = 81\n|Dec humidity = 81\n|year humidity = 82\n|Jan sun = 183.8\n|Feb sun = 148.8\n|Mar sun = 123.3\n|Apr sun = 95.6\n|May sun = 83.7\n|Jun sun = 60.4\n|Jul sun = 71.7\n|Aug sun = 87.5\n|Sep sun = 101.6\n|Oct sun = 128.5\n|Nov sun = 161.4\n|Dec sun = 182.9\n|year sun = 1429.2\n|source 1 = NOAA,<ref name=\"NOAA\">{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG__I/UA/68906.TXT\n| title = Gough Island Climate Normals 1961\u22121990\n| publisher = National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration\n| accessdate = November 21, 2013}}</ref> [[Deutscher Wetterdienst]] (extremes)<ref name = DWD>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dwd.de/DWD/klima/beratung/ak/ak_689060_kt.pdf\n| title = Klimatafel von Gough Island / S\u00fcdatlantik / Gro\u00dfbritannien\n| work = Baseline climate means (1961\u20131990) from stations all over the world\n| publisher = Deutscher Wetterdienst\n| language = German\n| accessdate = November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n|source 2 = climate-charts.com<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.climate-charts.com/Locations/u/UA68906.php\n|title = Climate Statistics for Gough Island, South Africa\n|date = 20 February 1998\n|access-date = 7 March 2012\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160820193201/http://www.climate-charts.com/Locations/u/UA68906.php\n|archive-date = 20 August 2016\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Fauna and flora==\n[[File:Blechnum and Phylica.png|thumb|upright|The fern ''[[Blechnum]]'' and tree ''[[Phylica]]'' on Gough Island]]\nGough and [[Inaccessible Island]] are a protected [[wildlife reserve]], which has been designated a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref name=Unesco>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/740|title=Gough and Inaccessible Islands|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=UNESCO Organization}}</ref> It has been described as one of the least disrupted [[ecosystem]]s of its kind and one of the best shelters for nesting [[seabird]]s in the Atlantic. In particular, it is host to almost the entire world population of the [[Tristan albatross]] (''Diomedea dabbenena'') and the [[Atlantic petrel]] (''Pterodroma incerta'').<ref>Cuthbert, J. & Sommer, E. ''[http://www.marineornithology.org/PDF/32_1/32_1_97-103.pdf Population size and trends of four globally threatened seabirds at Gough Island, South Atlantic Ocean]''. Marine Ornithology 32: 97\u2013103.</ref> The island is also home to the almost flightless [[Gough moorhen]],<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Sb1IJYzXZhUC&pg=RA1-PA60&lpg=RA1-PA60&dq=%22george+Comer%22+antartica |title=Flightless birds |author=Roots, Clive |location=Westport, Conn. |publisher=Greenwood Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-313-33545-7 |accessdate=2008-03-31 |page=60}}</ref> and the critically endangered [[Gough bunting]].\n\n===Birds===\n[[File:Gough Bunting Male.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A male Gough Bunting on the island]]\nThe island has been identified as an [[Important Bird Area]] (IBA) by [[BirdLife International]] for its endemic landbirds and as a breeding site for [[seabird]]s. Birds for which the IBA has conservation significance include [[northern rockhopper penguin]]s (30,000 breeding pairs), [[Tristan albatross]]es (1500\u20132000 pairs), [[sooty albatross]]es (5000 pairs), [[Atlantic yellow-nosed albatross]]es (5000 pairs), [[broad-billed prion]]s (1,750,000 pairs), [[Kerguelen petrel]]s (20,000 pairs), [[soft-plumaged petrel]]s (400,000 pairs), [[Atlantic petrel]]s (900,000 pairs), [[great-winged petrel]]s (5000 pairs), [[grey petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[great shearwater]]s (100,000 pairs), [[little shearwater]]s (10,000 pairs), [[grey-backed storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[white-faced storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[white-bellied storm petrel]]s (10,000 pairs), [[Antarctic tern]]s (500 pairs), [[southern skua]]s (500 pairs), [[Gough moorhen]]s (2500 pairs) and [[Gough bunting]]s (3000 individuals).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.birdlife.org |title= Gough Island |accessdate=2012-10-25 |work= Important Bird Areas factsheet |publisher= BirdLife International |year= 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Mammals===\n[[File:1954stampGoughTristan.jpg|thumb|Elephant seal at Gough Island depicted on a 1954 Tristan da Cunha stamp]]\nThe island has a large breeding population of [[subantarctic fur seal]]s and some [[southern right whale]]s still migrate around the island.\n\nHouse mice are currently present on the island. (see [[Gough Island#Invasive species|Invasive Species]])\n\n===Invasive species===\n\n====Pearlwort (''Sagina procumbens'')====\nIn 1998 a number of [[Sagina procumbens|procumbent pearlwort (''Sagina procumbens'')]] plants were found on the island which are capable of dramatically transforming the upland plant ecosystem (as it has on the [[Prince Edward Islands]]).\n<ref>Cooper, J. et al., [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/island_invasives/pdfhqprint/2cooper.pdf \"Earth, fire and water: applying novel techniques to eradicate the invasive plant, procumbent pearlwort ''Sagina procumbens'', on Gough Island, a World Heritage Site in the South Atlantic\"], [[Invasive Species Specialist Group]], 2010, Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref> Eradication efforts are ongoing but are expected to require years of 'concerted effort'.\n<ref>Bisser, P. et al., [http://www.conservationevidence.com/individual-study/2327 \"Strategies to eradicate the invasive plant procumbent pearlwort ''Sagina procumbens'' on Gough Island, 2010\"], Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref>\n\n====House mice====\nIn April 2007 researchers published evidence that predation by introduced [[house mouse|house mice]] on seabird chicks is occurring at levels that might drive the Tristan albatross and the Atlantic petrel to extinction.<ref>{{cite journal\n|author1=R M Wanless |author2=A Angel |author3=R J Cuthbert |author4=G M Hilton |author5=P G Ryan | title = Can predation by invasive mice drive seabird extinctions?\n| year = 2007\n| volume = 3\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 241\u2013244\n| doi = 10.1098/rsbl.2007.0120\n| pmid = 17412667\n| pmc = 2464706\n| journal = Biology Letters}}</ref>\nThe [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] awarded \u00a362,000 by the UK government's Overseas Territories Environment Programme to fund additional research on the Gough Island mice and a feasibility study of how best to deal with them. The grant also paid for the assessment of a [[rat]] problem on Tristan da Cunha island. Trials for a method of eradicating the mice through baiting were commenced,<ref>R. J. Cuthbert1\n, P. Visser et al., [http://www.issg.org/pdf/publications/Island_Invasives/pdfwebview/1Cuthbert.pdf \"Preparations for the eradication of mice from Gough Island: results of bait acceptance trials above ground and around cave systems\"], 2011,  Retrieved on 12 February 2014.</ref> and ultimately a \u00a39.2m eradication programme was planned, and set to begin in 2020, with the island expected to be mouse free by 2022. The inception of this programme in 2020 was confirmed in 2018. The programme will use helicopters to drop cereal pellets containing the rodenticide [[brodifacoum]]. As of October 2018, it is estimated that as many as 2,000,000 fewer eggs and chicks are being raised due to the impact of mice on the island, threatening the extinction of several species of seabirds that breed exclusively or nearly exclusively on Gough Island.<ref name=\"killer\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/ibi.12664|title=The impacts of introduced House Mice on the breeding success of nesting seabirds on Gough Island|last=Caravaggi|first=Anthony|date=22 October 2018|journal=Ibis|volume=161|issue=3|pages=648\u2013661|publisher=IBIS International Journal of Avian Science}}</ref> Gough has also been identified as the third most important island in the world (out of 107 islands) to be targeted for the removal of non-native invasive mammals to save threatened species from extinction and make major progress towards achieving global conservation targets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Butchart|first=Stuart H. M.|last2=Micol|first2=Thierry|last3=Cranwell|first3=Steve|last4=Pasachnik|first4=Stesha A.|last5=Wanless|first5=Ross|last6=Fisher|first6=Robert N.|last7=Griffiths|first7=Richard|last8=Pierce|first8=Ray|last9=Borroto-P\u00e1ez|first9=Rafael|date=2019-03-27|title=Globally important islands where eradicating invasive mammals will benefit highly threatened vertebrates|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=14|issue=3|pages=e0212128|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0212128|pmid=30917126|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2019PLoSO..1412128H}}</ref>\n\n==Weather station==\nA [[weather station]] has been operating on Gough Island since 1956. It is operated as part of the network of the [[South African Weather Service]]. Because [[cold front]]s approach South Africa from the south-west, the Gough station is particularly important in forecasting winter weather. Initially it was housed in the station at The Glen, but moved in 1963 to the South lowlands of the island, more precisely 40\u00b020'57.68\"S  9\u00b052'49.13\"W. The new location improved the validity and reliability of the data acquired for use in modeling.\n\n===Human presence===\nEach year a new overwintering team arrives by ship from [[Cape Town]] (beginning in 2012, the ''[[S. A. Agulhas II]]'') to staff the weather station and perform scientific research. The team for a particular year may be termed as \"Gough\" and an expedition number: for example, the 1956 team were \"Gough 01\", and the team for 2013 were \"Gough 58\". Each new team directly replaces the departing one, thereby maintaining a continual human presence on the island.<ref>[http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html \"South Africa National Antarctic Programme - Gough Island Teams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html |date=12 September 2017 }}, Retrieved 12 February 2014</ref><ref>Chris Bell, [http://goughisland58.blogspot.co.uk/ \"Chris Bell's Blog from Gough 58\"], Retrieved 12 February 2014</ref>\n\nA team normally consists of:\n* A senior [[meteorologist]]\n* Two junior meteorologists\n* A [[radio technician]]\n* A [[medic]]\n* A [[diesel mechanic]]\n* A number of [[biologist]]s (depending on ongoing research projects)\n\nThe team is supplied with enough food to last the whole year. People and cargo are landed either by helicopter, from a helideck-equipped supply ship, or by a fixed crane atop a cliff near the station (a place aptly called \"Crane Point\").\n\nIn 2014 a member of the research team choked to death on the island and his body was taken back to South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa-technology/sa-man-dies-gough-island|title=SA man dies on Gough Island|author=|date=|website=www.enca.com}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n<gallery>\nFile:Gough Island Map.jpg|Relief map\nFile:Orthographic projection over Gough Island.png|Orthographic projection\nFile:Gough Island Landsat.jpg|Satellite map\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* {{annotated link|South African National Antarctic Programme}}\n* {{annotated link|SANAE}}\n* {{annotated link|Marion Island}}\n* {{annotated link|S. A. Agulhas}}\n* {{annotated link|S. A. Agulhas II}}\n* {{annotated link|Nigel Morritt Wace}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.goughisland.com www.goughisland.com] - The Gough Island Restoration Project website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193226/http://www.sanap.ac.za/sanap_gough/sanap_gough.html The South African Weather Station on Gough Island] \u2013 Official website.\n*[https://www.facebook.com/groups/57386398567 Facebook Groups] - Gough Island team discussions\n*[https://whc.unesco.org/sites/740.htm Gough and Inaccessible Islands] - UNESCO wildlife reserve publication\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/chantal_steyn/sets/72157612980545317/ Photographs of Gough Island] - Flickr publication by Chantal van Staden.\n\n{{Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom}}\n{{SANAP navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Seabird colonies]]\n[[Category:South African National Antarctic Programme]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Saint Helena]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in British Overseas Territories]]\n[[Category:Seal hunting]]\n[[Category:Mid-Atlantic Ridge]]\n", "name_user": "Getsnoopy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a formatting issue.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gough_Island"}
{"title_page": "MBTA Commuter Rail", "text_new": "{{short description|Greater Boston rail system}}\n{{Infobox rail\n| railroad_name      =MBTA Commuter Rail\n| system_map         =MBTA Commuter Rail and funding district map.svg \n| map_size           =300\n| map_caption        =MBTA Commuter Rail system map\n| image              =MBTA_F40PHM-2C.JPG\n| image_size         =300\n| image_caption      = MBTA train at [[Route 128 station]] on the [[Providence/Stoughton Line]].\n| marks              =MBTX\n| locale             =Eastern [[Massachusetts]] and [[Rhode Island]]\n| predecessor_line   = [[Boston and Maine Railroad]]<br>[[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]]<br>[[New York Central Railroad]]<br>[[Penn Central Transportation Company]]\n| start_year         =1964 (beginning of MBTA subsidies)<br />1973 and 1976 (MBTA asset purchases)<br />1981 (full consolidation)&nbsp;\n| end_year           = &nbsp;present\n| length             = {{convert|398|mi|km}}\n| gauge              ={{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| hq_city            =[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| website            =[http://mbta.com/ MBTA.com]\n}}\n\nThe '''MBTA Commuter Rail''' system serves as the [[commuter rail]] arm of the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]'s transportation coverage of [[Greater Boston]] in the [[United States]]. Trains run over 398 miles of track to 141 different stations, with 58 stations on the north side with the remaining 83 stations on the south. It is operated under contract by [[Keolis]], which took over operations on July 1, 2014 from the Massachusetts Bay Commuter Railroad Company (MBCR).\n\nAs of the third quarter of 2019, average weekday ridership of the system was 119,800,<ref name=apta>{{cite web |url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q3-Ridership-APTA.pdf |title=Transit Ridership Report: Third Quarter 2019 |date=January 30, 2020 |publisher=American Public Transportation Association}}</ref> making it the [[List of United States commuter rail systems by ridership|sixth-busiest commuter rail system in the U.S.]], behind the three New York-area systems, the [[Metra|Chicago-area system]], and the [[SEPTA Regional Rail|Philadelphia-area system]].<ref name=apta/> The line's characteristic purple-trimmed coaches operate as far south as [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island]], and as far north as [[Newburyport, Massachusetts|Newburyport]] and as far west as [[Fitchburg, Massachusetts|Fitchburg]], both in [[Massachusetts]].\n\nTrains originate at two major [[Terminal station|terminals]] in [[Boston]]\u2014[[South Station]] and [[North Station]]\u2014with both transportation hubs offering connections to [[Amtrak]], local bus, intercity bus via [[South Station Bus Terminal]], and subway lines. Currently [[North\u2013South Rail Link|no passenger rail infrastructure]] ''directly'' connects them, other than existing MBTA subway lines, however, MassDOT is studying the proposed [[North\u2013South Rail Link]], which would provide a solution to the problem.\n\n==Current lines==\n{{see also|List of MBTA Commuter Rail stations}}No lines feed into both the North and South Stations.[[Image:MBTA Commuter Rail Map.svg|thumb|MBTA Commuter Rail system]]\nThe following lines terminate at [[South Station]] (listed from southeast to west):<ref name=\"RailMap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/rail/|title=Commuter Rail Maps and Schedules|work=MBTA.com|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Greenbush Line]]\n*[[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]], consisting of:\n**[[Kingston/Plymouth Line]]\n**[[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] (the [[CapeFlyer|CapeFLYER]] operates over this line Memorial Day\u2013Labor Day using MBTA equipment)\n*[[Fairmount Line]]\n*[[Providence/Stoughton Line]]\n*[[Franklin Line]] (with pilot service to {{bts|Foxboro}} as the Foxboro Line)\n*[[Needham Line]]\n*[[Framingham/Worcester Line]]\n\nThe following lines terminate at [[North Station]] (listed from west to northeast):<ref name=\"RailMap\" />\n*[[Fitchburg Line]]\n*[[Lowell Line]]\n*[[Haverhill Line]]\n*[[Newburyport/Rockport Line]]\n\n==Operational history==\n\n===Consolidation under MBTA control===\n\n====Boston & Maine Railroad====\nThe Commonwealth of Massachusetts's involvement with the operating facets of commuter rail began in 1967 when the [[Boston & Maine Corporation|Boston & Maine Railroad]] (B&M) petitioned the [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] to discontinue all passenger services.<ref name=netransit /> Service north of the state line was discontinued, but most service in Massachusetts was preserved through a contract between the Commonwealth and the B&M, at this time still an independent railroad company. The Commonwealth and MBTA began to purchase several lines, like the [[Lowell Line]] between Somerville and Wilmington, from the B&M.\n\nIn 1969 the B&M transported 24,000 passengers every weekday on four separate routes. Its yearly deficit was {{USD|3.2 million}}. A pool of 86 [[Budd Rail Diesel Car]]s provided the service.<ref>{{Dorin-Commuter|p=13}}</ref> B&M filed for bankruptcy protection in 1970. All remaining B&M commuter assets, with the exception of yard tracks and freight-only branches, were sold to the Commonwealth on December 14, 1976, though B&M was contracted to operate the service using its existing fleet of diesel railcars.<ref name=netransit />\n\n====New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad====\nThe [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] (NYNH&H), the long-time operator of most South Station commuter trains, filed for bankruptcy for the last time in 1961.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brief History of the New Haven |url=https://www.nhrhta.org/history |website=New Haven Railroad Historical and Technical Association |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref> Two years earlier in 1959, the railroad had discontinued passenger service on the Old Colony division in southeastern Massachusetts. On July 28, 1965, the MBTA signed an agreement with the New Haven Railroad to purchase {{convert|11|miles}} of the former Old Colony mainline from [[Fort Point Channel]] to South Braintree in order to construct a new rapid transit line along the corridor. The line was expected to be completed within two years. The agreement also provided for the MBTA to subsidize commuter service on the railroad's remaining commuter rail lines for $1.2 million annually.<ref name=netransit /><ref>{{cite news |title=MBTA Buys Old Colony Line For a South Shore Express |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=July 29, 1965 |first=Robert |last=Carr |id = {{ProQuest|366125778}}}}</ref>\n\nThe NH was included in the [[Penn Central Transportation Company]] (PC) merger in 1968, which itself filed bankruptcy in 1970.<ref name=drury>{{cite book | last = Drury | first = George H. | authorlink = | title = The Historical Guide to North American Railroads: Histories, Figures, and Features of more than 160 Railroads Abandoned or Merged since 1930 | publisher = [[Kalmbach Publishing]] | year = 1994 | location = [[Waukesha, Wisconsin]] | pages = 222\u2013229, 248 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-89024-072-8}}</ref> MBTA purchased many PC southside commuter lines on January 27, 1973, including the [[Providence/Stoughton Line]] as far as the Rhode Island border plus the branch to Stoughton, the [[Franklin Line]] and [[Needham Line]] and the [[Framingham/Worcester Line]] from Riverside to Framingham, as well as a number of abandoned lines and lines without passenger service including the Old Colony mainline from Boston to Braintree and the [[Plymouth/Kingston Line]] (which were later restored).<ref name=netransit /> PC merged into [[Conrail]] on April 1, 1976; the MBTA bought the equipment but Conrail took over operations of the southside lines. The MBTA also purchased the [[Fairmount Line]] to restore it for passenger service as a bypass during [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] reconstruction.<ref name=netransit />\n\n====New York Central Railroad====\nThe [[Framingham/Worcester Line]], historically part of the [[Boston & Albany Railroad]] (B&A), was merged into the [[New York Central Railroad]] (NYC) and its ownership subsequently passed to PC in 1968. As part of the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] Boston Extension's construction in the 1960s, the Worcester Line's roadbed between Route 128 and Boston was sold to the [[Massachusetts Turnpike Authority]], with the provison that the control of the railroad remain with NYC. Conrail inherited the line which formed a vital freight artery between Boston's Beacon Yard and Conrail's [[Selkirk Yard]]. The Riverside-Framingham section was sold to the MBTA in 1976 as part of their larger acquisition of PC commuter assets, but the section past Framingham remained in Conrail control.<ref name=netransit /> In September 2009, Conrail successor [[CSX Transportation]] and the Commonwealth finalized a $100 million agreement to purchase CSX's Framingham to Worcester tracks, as well as the [[Grand Junction Railroad]] plus lines which will be part of the [[South Coast Rail]] project, to improve service on the Framingham/Worcester Line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transportation.blog.state.ma.us/blog/2009/09/lt-governor-historic-csx-rail-agreement.html |title=Lt. Governor: Historic CSX Rail Agreement |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |work=Commonwealth Conversations: Transportation |date=September 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref> After several years of construction and negotiations, ownership of the line was transferred to the commonwealth on October 4, 2012, with increased service on the outer section of the line beginning several weeks later.<ref name=netransit /><ref name=29oct>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20121004/NEWS/110049827/1116 |title=At CSX freight yard, Murray touts increased train service |newspaper=Worcester Telegram & Gazette |author=Monahan, John J. |date=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Combined operations===\nThe Northeast Rail Service Act of 1981 compelled Conrail to transfer operations of all passenger and commuter services to local transit authorities, resulting in Conrail ceasing all subsidized passenger rail services.<ref>Northeast Rail Service Act of 1981, Pub. L. 97-35, {{Usc-title-chap|45|20}}, August 13, 1981.</ref> B&M won the contract for the southside lines; for the first time, all Boston commuter service was operated by one entity. After bankruptcy, B&M continued to operate trains under the protection of the federal bankruptcy court, in the hopes that a reorganization could make it profitable again. It emerged from the court's protection when [[Timothy Mellon]]'s [[Pan Am Railways|Guilford Transportation Industries]] (GTI) bought it in 1983.<ref name=netransit /> GTI let the contract expire in 1987, after a bitter strike had shut down most of the northside lines in 1986.<ref name=netransit />\n\nFrom 1987 to 2003, [[Amtrak]] managed all of Boston's commuter rail.<ref name=netransit /> The relationship between MBTA and Amtrak was often rocky, and Amtrak did not submit a bid when the contract expired in 2003. MBTA observers saw Amtrak as having been a reliable manager and operator, but Amtrak sometimes experienced strained relations with the MBTA. Quibbles centered on equipment failures, crewing issues about the number of conductors per train, and responsibility for late trains. Because of these issues, and Amtrak's repeated statements that the MBTA contract was unreasonable, few were surprised at Amtrak's decision not to bid again.<ref name=\"MBCR contract\">{{cite web\n| title =MBTA Exercises Option With MBCR For Commuter Rail Service, Launches New Customer-Focused Improvements| publisher = MBTA| date = January 6, 2010| url = http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=18672&month=&year=| quote =MBTA extends MBCR contract another two years.}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|MBCR}}\nTwo tenders were submitted, one from GTI and another from the newly formed Massachusetts Bay Commuter Railroad Company (MBCR), a partnership between [[Veolia Transport|Connex]] (later Veolia), [[Bombardier Transportation]] and Alternate Concepts, Inc., the latter of which won the tender. MBCR took over the MBTA Commuter Rail operation from Amtrak in July 2003. The MBCR contract originally expired in July 2008 but had an additional five-year option; it was later extended three years to July 2011 and then another two to July 2013.<ref name=\"MBCR contract\" /><ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/07/commuter_rail_firm_gets_contract_extension/ Commuter Rail Firm Gets Contract Extension] Boston.com, accessed February 16, 2010.</ref> After concerns about on-time performance, the 2011 extension increased the fine for late trains from $100 to $300.<ref>Boston Metro, June 6, 2008, p. 2.</ref>\n[[File:Logo Keolis.png|thumb|Logo of Keolis Commuter Services, the current operator of MBTA Commuter Rail. This logo appears on employee uniforms and public timetables.]]\nIn August 2012, MBCR and [[Keolis]] were the two bidders for the contract. On January 8, 2014, the MBTA awarded Keolis the contract for $2.68 billion over eight years, with the possibility of two two-year extensions that could bring the total price to $4.3 billion.<ref>http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442451214&month=1&year=14 MBTA press release on Keolis Commuter Services award</ref> Keolis took over the operations on July 1, 2014. Keolis lost $29.3 million in its first year of operation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://trn.trains.com/news/news-wire/2016/02/22-mbta-keolis | title=Keolis loses millions of dollars on its MBTA contract | work=[[Trains Magazine]] | date=February 22, 2016 | accessdate=February 23, 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Service changes since MBTA takeover==\n\n===Expansions===\nSeveral significant improvements have been made during MBTA's period of stewardship which started circa 1973. However, the Commonwealth's support for rail operations began in the 1950s with contracted operations and subsidies to railroads providing commuter service, and more so in 1964 with the advent of MBTA.\n*The Commonwealth of Massachusetts pioneered the concept of \"Park and Ride\" by providing funds to construct the [[Route 128 Station]] on NH's Providence Line, at a location where the radial line intersected with [[Massachusetts Route 128]], the [[beltway]] encircling greater Boston. Route 128 Station was established 1953 by NH President [[Frederic C. Dumaine, Jr.]]. The initial station was simple in design, built as a parking lot located next to the tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhrhta.org/htdocs/images0200.htm |title=Route 128 Station |date=February 1, 2000 |publisher=New Haven Railroad Historical and Technical Association |accessdate=August 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719074252/http://www.nhrhta.org/htdocs/images0200.htm |archive-date=July 19, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*B&M's Eastern Route formerly operated across the bridge at Merrimack River and as far north as [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] on the former [[Eastern Railroad (Massachusetts)|Eastern Railroad]] alignment. Service past [[Ipswich (MBTA station)|Ipswich]] to [[Newburyport (MBTA station)|Newburyport]] was limited to a single daily round trip after 1967, and suspended in April 1976.<ref name=netransit /> Freight service to Newburyport lasted until 1984, and the line was formally abandoned in 1994 even as preparations began for restored service. After a brief period of abandonment, commuter rail service to Newburyport resumed on October 26, 1998, with an infill stop at [[Rowley (MBTA station)|Rowley]].<ref name=abandoned>{{cite book |title=Lost Railroads of New England |author=Karr, Ronald Dale |edition=Third |publisher=Branch Line Press |year=2010 |isbn=9780942147117 |page=54 }}</ref>\n*As part of the Northeast Corridor Improvement Program II (NECIP II) of the 1990s, MBTA's Providence Line was electrified using federal funds provided to Amtrak for its ''[[Acela Express]]'' project. However, MBTA does not operate electric equipment on the Providence Line, as such equipment would be unusable on other lines.\n*As [[Big Dig]] environmental mitigation, MBTA invested heavily in the Commuter Rail system by restoring large sections of the Old Colony division, which was abandoned in 1959. Service along the two main [[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]] was reestablished in 1997, and the [[Greenbush Line]] opened in 2007.<ref name=netransit />\n*After 1975, [[Framingham/Worcester Line]] service was cut back to [[Framingham (MBTA station)|Framingham]], though other lines reached exurbs more distant from Boston than Framingham. As compensation for delays in the Old Colony Lines restoration, rush-hour service to [[Worcester Union Station]] was restored in 1994, with infill stations at [[Ashland (MBTA station)|Ashland]], [[Southborough (MBTA station)|Southborough]], [[Westborough (MBTA station)|Westborough]], and [[Grafton (MBTA station)|Grafton]] stations were added in the MetroWest region between 2000 and 2002.<ref name=netransit /> The service was successful, resulting in relative de-emphasis of Amtrak and commuter bus services operating in the same corridor.\n*During the 1979-1987 reconstruction of the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]], Amtrak and MBTA trains were diverted over the Dorchester Branch, which had not seen passenger traffic since 1944. As part of this project, MBTA allowed [[Centralized Traffic Control]] to be installed on this branch, greatly increasing its signal capacity.<ref name=netransit /> Regular service was kept on the [[Fairmount Line]] after 1987 because the relocated service was popular with residents of Dorchester and Roxbury. As Big Dig mitigation, MBTA rebuilt existing stations and is adding 4 new stations along the line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/default.asp?id=14261 |title=Fairmount Line Improvements |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=December 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129100850/http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/default.asp?id=14261 |archive-date=January 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The first of these, [[Talbot Avenue station|Talbot Avenue]], opened on November 12, 2012, followed by [[Newmarket station (MBTA)|Newmarket]] and [[Four Corners/Geneva station|Four Corners/Geneva]] on July 1, 2013.<ref name=globetalbot>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/yourtown/news/dorchester/2012/11/mbta_opens_new_commuter_rail_s.html |title=MBTA opens new commuter rail station at Talbot Avenue in Dorchester on Fairmount Line |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Rocheleau, Matt |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=November 12, 2012}}</ref> [[Blue Hill Avenue station]] was opened on February 25, 2019, after many delays.\n*Agreement with the state of [[Rhode Island]] allowed MBTA's Attleboro Line to extend to [[Providence, Rhode Island]] during the late 1980s. At first, only weekday service was provided. In the mid-2000s, a new agreement with [[RIDOT]] provided funding to allow the service to operate on weekends also. Service was extended further south to  [[T. F. Green Airport (MBTA station)|T. F. Green Airport]] in [[Warwick, Rhode Island]] in December 2010 and to [[Wickford Junction (MBTA station)|Wickford Junction]] in [[North Kingston, Rhode Island|North Kingston]] in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.turnto10.com/news/2010/dec/06/7/boston-tf-green-rail-service-debuts-ar-316999 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205001015/http://www2.turnto10.com/news/2010/dec/06/7/boston-tf-green-rail-service-debuts-ar-316999 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 5, 2013 |title=Boston to T.F. Green rail service debuts |newspaper=NBC 10 News |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 1, 2011 }}</ref> This represents the first commuter service in Rhode Island south of Providence since 1981.<ref name=netransit />\n*In 2013, the [[CapeFLYER]] service began running from [[South Station (Boston)|South Station]] to [[Hyannis (MBTA station)|Hyannis]] on summer weekends - the first direct service from Boston to Cape Cod since 1959. Though officially a Cape Cod Regional Transit Authority service, the CapeFLYER uses MBTA equipment.<ref name=netransit /> Should this pilot service be successful, regular commuter service may be extended from [[Middleborough/Lakeville (MBTA station)|Middleborough/Lakeville]] to [[Buzzards Bay (MBTA station)|Buzzards Bay]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capenews.net/communities/sandwich/news/2650 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130819032715/http://www.capenews.net/communities/sandwich/news/2650 |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2013 |title=Cape Commuter Rail Is A Real Possibility |newspaper=Cape News |author=Kinsella, James |date=August 16, 2013 |accessdate=August 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n*A 4-mile extension of the [[Fitchburg Line]] to [[Wachusett (MBTA station)|Wachusett station]] opened on September 30, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Documents/Schedules_and_Maps/Upcoming_Schedules/Commuter_Rail/Fitchburg.pdf |title=FITCHBURG LINE Schedule effective September 30, 2016 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=September 30, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926143419/http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Documents/Schedules_and_Maps/Upcoming_Schedules/Commuter_Rail/Fitchburg.pdf |archivedate=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n*On November 14, 2013, MBTA began rehabilitating and rebuilding the tracks along 33 miles of right-of-way the agency acquired to restore service to [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]] and [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]] (See [[South Coast Rail]]).\n\n===Contractions===\n\nDuring the period of MBTA control, services have also been curtailed:\n\n*Commuter rail services along the [[Millis Branch]] and [[Dedham Branch]], by 1966 consisting of only a single daily rush-hour round trip, were discontinued by the NYNH&H on April 21, 1967 and have not been replaced.<ref name=netransit />\n*All former B&M services that extended north of the Massachusetts border were curtailed by 1967, except for a brief period of experimental service from January 28, 1980 to March 1, 1981.<ref name=\"netransit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/MBTARouteHistory.pdf |title=Changes to Transit Service in the MBTA district |accessdate=September 29, 2007 |last=Belcher |first=Jonathan |date=August 10, 2007 |publisher= }}</ref> Since then, restoration and extension of the Lowell Line to [[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua]], [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], and [[Concord, New Hampshire]], and the Haverhill Line to [[Portland, Maine]], have been repeatedly discussed. In 2001, Amtrak commenced operation of the ''[[Downeaster (train)|Downeaster]]'' between Boston's North Station and Portland under the auspices of the [[Northern New England Passenger Rail Authority]]. The Nashua service discussion is continuing in the context of the widening of [[Interstate 93]] in New Hampshire.\n*The B&M operated one daily round trip to South Sudbury (19.7 miles from Boston) over the former [[Central Massachusetts Railroad]] until its discontinuation on November 26, 1971.<ref name=netransit />\n*Passenger service on the [[Lexington and West Cambridge Railroad|Lexington Branch]] ended on January 10, 1977.<ref name=netransit /> The Northwest Extension of the [[MBTA Red Line]] replaced the service as far as Alewife in West Cambridge. No commuter rail service reaches the towns of Arlington, Lexington, and Bedford, Massachusetts. Today, the rail-banked line forms the [[Minuteman Bikeway]] and is a linear park in the vicinity of [[Davis Square, Somerville]].\n<!--Not supported by any evidence that these services lasted past 1960\n*The Lowell-Lawrence-Haverhill-Newburyport line had a [[Budd Rail Diesel Car|Budd RDC-1]] running on it well into the 1970s, but was discontinued when MBTA replaced the aging Budd equipment with more modern locomotive hauled trains. The route also saw one round-trip per day from Newburyport via Bradford, Andover, and Reading to Boston.-->\n*The southern half of the [[Woburn Branch Railroad|Woburn Loop]] still operated when the MBTA took over control, joining the Lowell Line at Winchester. Half the Lowell Line services terminated at Woburn Heights (10.0 miles from Boston), while the others stopped at North Woburn (today's Anderson RTC) and continued to Lowell. Weekend service ended on September 7, 1980, and all service on the branch stopped on January 30, 1981.<ref name=netransit/>\n*The Fitchburg Line under B&M operations terminated at [[Ayer, Massachusetts]], but was subsequently extended as far as [[Gardner, Massachusetts]] in January 1981. However, the service between Gardner and Fitchburg was ended at the end of 1986 after the parallel [[Massachusetts Route 2]] was upgraded to expressway standards, reducing travel time between these cities.<ref name=netransit />\n\n==Rolling stock==\n[[File:Outbound train stopped at Auburndale.JPG|thumb|A typical Commuter Rail train, consisting of one diesel locomotive and five coaches, at Auburndale station in 2012.]]\n\nAll MBTA commuter rail service is provided by [[push-pull train]]s powered by [[diesel locomotive]]s with a [[cab car]] on the opposite end. Trains typically have four to eight coaches (with six the most common) and seat between 400 and 1400 passengers. Approximately 65 trainsets are needed for weekday service.<ref name=\"roster\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ |title=The MBTA Vehicle Inventory Page |publisher=NETransit |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe primary heavy maintenance facility is the [[MBTA Commuter Rail Maintenance Facility]], located in [[Somerville, Massachusetts|East Somerville]] on the former site of the Boston and Maine's Boston Engine Terminal. It is also used for midday and overnight storage of trains on the northside lines. Southampton Street Yard and the Readville Interim Layover facility are used for light maintenance and layover service. [[List of Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority yards#Commuter rail|Various other layover facilities]] are used for midday and overnight storage; most are located near the outer ends of the lines.\n\n=== Locomotive fleet ===\n{{As of|2016|6}}, the MBTA owned 125 locomotives. Of these, 85 were in active passenger service, four used for work service, and 36 inactive for various reasons.<ref name=roster /> The current fleet of diesel locomotives comprises a mix of purpose-built passenger locomotives (such as the [[EMD F40PH]]) and freight locomotives rebuilt for passenger use (such as the GMD GP40MCs, which were originally GMD GP40-2LWs). All passenger locomotives are equipped with [[head end power]] (HEP), though some locomotives exclusively used for non-revenue work service are not.<ref name=roster />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Numbers<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Image\n|-\n|1973\u20131975\n|[[General Motors Diesel|GMD]]\n|[[GMD GP40MC]]\n|1115\u20131139\n|Rebuilt by AMF in 1997.<ref name=roster />  Some to be rebuilt in Keolis in-house overhaul, others to be rebuilt in Rochester.\n|[[File:MBTA GP40 1136.jpg|100px]]  \n|-\n|1987\u20131988\n|EMD\n|[[EMD F40PH-2C]]\n|1052\u20131053, 1055\u20131056, 1058-1059, 1062, 1067, 1070\u20131072\n|Rebuilt by [[MotivePower|MPI]] 2001\u20132003. 1073 retired and scrapped after the [[1990 Back Bay rail accident]]. All remaining units are being rebuilt by MPI as F40PH-3C class.<ref name=roster /> \n|[[File:MBTA 1055 at Littleton station, May 2019.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1987\u20131988\n|[[MotivePower|MPI]]\n|[[EMD F40PH|MPI F40PH-3C]]\n|1025\u20131026, 1028, 1031\u20131032, 1035, 1050\u20131051, 1054, 1057, 1060\u20131061, 1063\u20131066, 1068-1069, 1074, 1075\n|Rebuilt from F40PH-2C and F40PHM-2C class locomotives by MPI.\n|[[File:MBTA F40PH-3C 1054 Departing Hyde Park Station.png|100px]]\n|-\n|1991\u20131993\n|[[Morrison\u2013Knudsen|M-K]]\n|[[EMD F40PH|M-K F40PHM-2C]]\n|1027, 1029\u20131030, 1033\u20131034, 1036\n|Rebuilt by MPI 2003\u20132004. All units are being rebuilt by MPI as F40PH-3C class.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:Outbound train approaching Mansfield station, July 2019.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[MotivePower|MPI]]\n|[[MPI MPXpress#MP36PH-3C|MPI MP36PH-3C]]\n|010-011\n|Purchased from [[Utah Transit Authority]]'s [[FrontRunner]].<ref name=roster /><ref name=\"UTABUY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2011/02/mbta_unveils_fi.html|title=MBTA unveils first new locomotive in 23 years|last=Finucane|first=Martin|date=February 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n|[[File:MBTA locomotive 010 at Buzzards Bay on CapeFLYER trial run.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|MPI\n|[[MPI HSP46]]\n|2000\u20132039\n|Purchased new from [[MotivePower]]. Ordered in 2010.<ref name=rgi20100720>{{cite news | url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/boston-orders-motivepower-hsp46-diesels.html | title=Boston orders MotivePower HSP46 diesels | work=[[Railway Gazette International]] | date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n|[[File:MBTA 2001 at CRMF, October 2013.jpg|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Non-revenue===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Numbers<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes\n!Image\n|-\n|1957\u20131960\n|[[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]]\n|[[EMD GP9]]\n|904\n|Purchased from SEMTA. Ex-MBTA 902 is now at the [[Illinois Railway Museum]]. \n|[[File:MBTA 904 at South Station, March 2018.jpg |100px]]\n|-\n|1971\n|EMD\n|[[EMD GP40]]\n|3247\n|\n|[[File:MBTA 3247 at Porter station, September 2010.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[National Railway Equipment Company|NRE]]\n|[[NRE 3GS21B]]\n|3248\u20133249\n|\n|[[File:MBTA3gs21b at Boston.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n=== Coach fleet ===\n[[File:First revenue round trip of Rotem bilevels at Malden Center (2), April 2013.jpg|thumb|#1800 arrives at Malden Center on the first revenue round trip of the new BTC-4D and CTC-5 coaches]]\n\n{{As of|2016|6}}, the MBTA owned 481 coaches. Of these, 420 were in active service and 61 inactive for various reasons.<ref name=\"roster\" /> Coaches whose designations start with BTC (Blind Trailer Coach) are conventional coaches, while those starting with CTC (Control Trailer Coach) are [[cab car]]s. Cab cars will occasionally also appear in the middle of a consist. Coaches acquired before 1990 were single-level cars with 88 to 127 seats; those since are bilevel cars with 173 to 185 seats.<ref name=roster />\n\nVarious coaches are equipped with electronic doors for use on the [[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]] and [[Greenbush Line]], which have full-length high-level platforms at all stops. All BTC-3, CTC-3, BTC-4C, and BTC-4D coaches have restrooms.<ref name=\"roster\" /> Trains usually have one of these cars adjacent to the locomotive, as that car will be platformed at all high level platforms regardless of length, and thus handicapped riders will be able to access the restroom car.\n\nDuring winter months, a Ski Train serving [[Wachusett Mountain (ski area)|Wachusett Mountain]] runs on the [[Fitchburg Line]], using a coach car which is equipped for carrying bicycles or skis.<ref name=roster /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wachusett.com/default.aspx?tabid=66|publisher=Wachusett Mountain Ski Area|title=Ski Train To Wachusett|year=2012|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}</ref> During summer months, some [[Newburyport/Rockport Line]] trains to Rockport include one of two cars equipped to carry bicycles.<ref name=roster /><ref name=biketrain>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Riding_the_T/Bikes_on_the_T/Eastern%20Route%20Bike%20Train_11.pdf |title=MBTA Bike Train|author=MBTA |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> The [[CapeFLYER]] uses car 224, which has been modified as a cafe and baggage car.<ref name=roster />\n\nIn January 2019, the MBTA issued a Request for Qualifications to design additional bilevel coach cars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bc.mbta.com/business_center/bidding_solicitations/pdf/V61PS05_Public%20Announcement_SOQ_2019-01-22.pdf |title=SOLICITATION FOR ENGINEERING AND PROGRAM MANAGEMENT SERVICES IN SUPPORT OF THE BI-LEVEL COMMUTER RAIL COACH PROCUREMENT: REQUEST FOR QUALIFICATIONS |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=January 2019}}</ref> The agency approved a $279 million contract (total project cost of $345 million) for 80 additional Rotem bilevel coaches in September 2019, with delivery expected from September 2022 to June 2024. The MBTA plans an additional procurement of 100 bilevel cars, delivered from 2024 to 2027.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://mbta.com/news/2019-09-23/fmcb-approves-the-procurement-80-new-commuter-rail-bi-level-coaches |title=FMCB Approves the Procurement of 80 New Commuter Rail Bi-Level Coaches |date=September 23, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"50\" |Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"70\" |Fleet ID<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Seats<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Image\n|-\n|1978&ndash;79\n|[[Pullman Company|Pullman]]\n|BTC-1C\n|200&ndash;258\n|114\n|The BTC-1C cars were rebuilt from BTC-1 and CTC-1 cars in 1995 and 1996, at which point they were renumbered; coaches 203 and 215 were not rebuilt and are no longer used. Coach 219 is a bike/ski car, 221 a bike car, 224 a cafe car, and 225 planned to be a bike car.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:MBTA 240 at West Natick station, May 2017.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987\n|[[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]\n|BTC-1A\n|350&ndash;389\n|127\n|\n|[[File:Commuter train at Porter 2.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987&ndash;88\n|[[Messerschmitt-B\u00f6lkow-Blohm|MBB]]\n|BTC-3\n|500\u2013510, 512, 514\u2013532\n|86\n|511 and 513 are retired. 501, 503, 505, 508, 509, 516, 517, 522, 526, 527, 528 and 532 are leased to [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] for service on the [[Hartford Line]].<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:MBTA 507 in dead line, April 2014.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987&ndash;88\n|MBB\n|CTC-3\n|1500\u20131515, 1517\u20131524, 1526\u20131533\n|96\n|1516 and 1525 are retired. 1505, 1509, 1518 and 1520 are leased to [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] for service on the [[Hartford Line]].\n|[[File:MBTA 1529 at South Station, May 2016.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1989&ndash;90\n|Bombardier\n|BTC-1B\n|600\u2013611, 613\u2013653\n|122\n|612 is retired.\n|[[File:MBTA 616 shop.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1989&ndash;90\n|Bombardier\n|CTC-1B\n|1600\u20131647, 1649\u20131652\n|122\n|1648 is retired. Cab controllers have been deactivated in coaches 1600&ndash;1624; they are used exclusively as blind coaches.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:Lynn station with train 172.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1990&ndash;91\n|[[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]]\n|BTC-4\n|700&ndash;749\n|185\n|700\u2013749 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]] in Hornell, New York. They will have some features identical to the 800 series cars, including destination displays and LED lighting.\n|[[File:Bilevel MBTA coaches at South Station, April 2002.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1990&ndash;91\n|Kawasaki\n|CTC-4\n|1700\u20131709, 1711\u20131724\n|175\n|1710 is retired. 1700\u20131709 and 1711\u20131724 have all been overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:Needham Line train 614.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1997\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4A\n|750&ndash;766\n|182\n|750\u2013766 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:BTC-4A coaches on the CapeFLYER.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2001\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4B\n|767&ndash;781\n|182\n|767\u2013781 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:Outbound train at East Braintree Weymouth Landing station, January 2017.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2005\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4C\n|900&ndash;932\n|178\n|\n|[[File:BTC-4C coach on CapeFLYER at Buzzards Bay.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|[[Hyundai Rotem]]\n|BTC-4D\n|800&ndash;846\n|179\n|\n|[[File:Rotem car 801 at North Station.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|Hyundai Rotem\n|CTC-5\n|1800&ndash;1827\n|173\n|\n|[[File:Cab car 1800 at North Station.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Retired equipment===\n[[File:MBTA 1101 with GO coaches at South Station, March 1979.jpg|thumb|An EMD FP10 locomotive with rented GO Transit coaches at South Station in 1978]]\n\nAs the Commonwealth assumed the control of the Commuter Rail during the 1970s, it inherited various non-standard equipment from predecessor railroads. These included:\n\n* Numerous [[Budd Company|Budd]] [[Rail Diesel Car]]s,<ref name=railwayage>{{cite magazine |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1215/is_n11_v192/ai_11544541/ |title=How MBTA rebuilt ridership |magazine=Railway Age |date=November 1991 |accessdate=August 3, 2008 |author=Middleton, William D.}}</ref> including a total of 86 from the B&M, New Haven Railroad and [[SEPTA]]. The RDC fleet was de-powered in the 1970s and turned into locomotive-hauled coaches by Morrison Knudsen.<ref name=railwayage /> These became known as \"Boise Budds\", after the location of the MK shop where the work was done. The RDC fleet was phased out during the 1980s and completely replaced with conventional coaches by 1989.<ref name=roster /> Remaining examples of these units now serve on the [[Grand Canyon Railway]] and [[Hobo Railroad]]; a derelict pair sit on a disused track near North Station, and a single unit has been restored and is displayed at [[Bedford Depot]].\n* In 1978\u20131980 MBTA acquired 19 rebuilt EMD FP10 units which were later transferred to [[Metro North Railroad]] in 1991\u20131993.<ref name=railwayage /> [[EMD GP-9]]s were also operated in Boston suburban service. MBTA #904, one of six GP-9s received from [[SEMTA]] in 1987, is retained as a work engine.<ref name=roster />\n* Ex\u2013[[GO Transit]] stainless steel coaches were operated as an interim solution pending delivery of the CTC-1/BTC-1 order.\n* From 2002 to 2004, MBTA leased some retired Amtrak F40PHs while the F40PHM-2Cs were getting rebuilt.\n* Until 2015, MBTA operated standard F40PHs, numbered 1000-1017.\n\n==Wi-Fi==\n[[File:Outbound Needham Line train at Forest Hills.JPG|thumb|left|Two coaches in 2012 with wraps indicating that they are Wi-Fi enabled. This 2008-built system will be replaced with a new system.]]\nFree [[Wi-Fi]] internet service with limited bandwidth is provided on all trains. A two-tiered model where riders can pay extra for faster service is in planning.<ref name=mbtawifi />\n\nThe program started with a $262,000 pilot in January 2008 on the [[Worcester Line]], where 45 coaches were fitted with routers which connected to cellular data networks. This was the first Wi-Fi available on a commuter rail service in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/141940/article.html |title=Wi-Fi trial Connects Massachusetts Train Passengers |newspaper=PC World |last=Cox |first=John |date=January 28, 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> The Worcester Line was chosen for the pilot phase in part to compensate for low on-time performance, as well as to test the service across the line's varied terrain.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327210717/http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=March 27, 2008 |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |quote=First, it provides one of the best opportunities from a geographical perspective to test Wi-Fi capabilities as it runs from Boston to central Massachusetts (Worcester) through various terrains (hills, wooded areas, etc.) Secondly, we are aware that the Framingham/Worcester trains have experienced significant performance issues due mainly to the owner and operator of the line (CSX). For that, we want to offer Framingham/Worcester customers the first opportunity. |title=Framingham/Worcester Commuter Rail customers: Try our free MBTA Wi-Fi Commuter Rail Connect Test Program! |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=January 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> The program was considered successful; in December 2008, the MBTA announced that Wi-Fi would be available on all trains by mid-2009. Of the 410 coaches then owned by the MBTA, 258 would receive Wi-Fi equipment at a rate of about 30 per month.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=16235&month=&year |title=Free Wi-Fi Service Expanded |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=December 19, 2008 |accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, the MBTA announced that a private company would be building a new $5.6 million network to replace the 2008-built network. The MBTA is not paying for the new network; instead, the company expects to recoup its investment by providing a two-tiered offering. Free limited-bandwidth Wi-Fi will continue to be provided, along with local television broadcasts; a monthly fee will be charged by the company for access to higher bandwidth and other broadcasts, with 7.5% of the fee returned to the MBTA.<ref name=newwifi /> The new system was to be completed in 2016, with the revenue agreement lasting until 2037.<ref name=newwifi >{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/07/24/mbta-revamp-commuter-rail-wifi-system/U2onDF0uABUiOhUPj0SkqO/story.html |title=MBTA to boost Web service on commuter rail |newspaper=The Boston Globe |last=Thadani |first=Trisha |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442452651&month=&year= |title=New WiFi System for Commuter Rail |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=May 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=mbtawifi>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |title=WiFi Commuter Rail Connect |date=October 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101073850/http://mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=January 1, 2016 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2016, the new system was still in permitting and design, except for enhanced Wi-Fi at Back Bay, South Station, and North Station expected to be complete by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226025756/http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=December 26, 2016 |title=WiFi Commuter Rail Connect |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> In August 2017, the MBTA canceled the $140 million plan due to local opposition to the erection of 320 [[monopole antenna|monopoles]], each {{convert|70|feet|adj=on}} tall, as well as the need to focus on more critical projects like the [[Green Line Extension]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2017/08/10/mbta-nixes-140m-plan-to-upgrade-wifi-on-commuter.html |title=MBTA nixes $140M plan to upgrade Wi-Fi on commuter rail |newspaper=Boston Business Journal |date=August 10, 2017 |first=Don |last=Seiffert}}</ref>\n\n==Fare policy==\n[[Image:MBCR tickets.jpg|right|thumb|Commuter Rail tickets in the form of CharlieTickets purchased at fare vending machines and ticket booths (left) and paper tickets purchased on-board (right).]]\n\nThe MBTA Commuter Rail uses a fare zone policy whereby origin and destination stations are not individually priced, but assigned a zone based on distance from Boston.<ref name=\"FareInfo\">{{cite web|url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/rail/|title=Commuter Rail Fares & Passes |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> There are a total of eleven zones (1A, then 1 through 10) with an increasing fare to or from Boston the higher the zone number. Most stations in inner Boston, as well as stations in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] and [[Medford, Massachusetts|Medford]], are located in zone 1A; trips from this zone are the least expensive and cost the same as rapid transit ($2.40), while the highest priced Zone 10 fares are $12.50 per ride.<ref name=\"FareInfo\" /> Travel between suburban zones without going to Boston is charged an \"interzone\" fare based on the number of zones traveled.<ref name=\"FareInfo\" /> Seniors, those with a disability, and middle and high school students with proper identification receive a 50% discounted rate; children under eleven travel free with a paying adult.<ref name=\"ReducedFares\">{{cite web |url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/reduced_fare_programs/ |title=Reduced Fares |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref> Fares are collected by train conductors; while [[fare evasion]] is explicitly illegal, it is not criminal.<ref name=\"8-2010 Scorecard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Score_Card/Scorecard-2010-08.pdf|title=MBTA Scorecard|date=August 2010|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|page=14|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mass.gov/legis/laws/mgl/159-101.htm|title=Section 101 Evasion of payment of toll or fare |work=Massachusetts General Laws |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTickets may be purchased at automatic vending machines located in principal stations and at suburban stations from nearby businesses and vendors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/sales_locations/ |title=Sales Locations |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/fares_and_passes/purchase_programs/|title=Purchase Programs|work=MBTA.com|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref> Passengers joining at stations without ticketing machines or vendors can purchase tickets on board.<ref name=\"8-2010 Scorecard\" /> Alternatively, riders can use the MBTA mTicket app to purchase tickets on iPhone and Android devices, which allows them to display their tickets on their mobile phone screens rather than presenting paper tickets or passes.<ref name=\"mTicketing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/fares_and_passes/mticketing/|title=Mobile Ticketing}}</ref> Travelers can purchase tickets as a one-way, round trip, ten ride (no discount), or monthly pass (discounted over daily round-trip purchase).<ref name=\"FareInfo\" />\n\n==Ridership==\nRidership levels on the Commuter Rail have grown since the MBTA's involvement began in the late 1960s, with overall average weekday ridership growing from 29,500 in 1969 to 76,000 in 1990 and 143,700 in 2008. This was accomplished by a series of rationalizations, such as closing lightly used lines, concentrating service on heavily utilized lines, and re-opening formerly abandoned branches with high traffic potential, such as the Old Colony Lines. A general growth of transit usage in the [[Northeastern United States]] also contributed. Growing ridership in this way required substantial capital investment, which was provided by a mixture of Federal mass transit funds and Commonwealth transportation bond issues.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==Train operations==\n[[File:Inbound Campello.JPG|thumb|An MBTA train at [[Campello (MBTA station)|Campello]] station inbound to South Station.]]\nLike most commuter railroads in the Northeastern United States, MBTA is a member of the [[Northeast Operating Rules Advisory Committee]] (NORAC) and uses the rulebook promulgated by that organization.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public/58000-58499/58167/585157.pdf |title=NORAC Operating Rules |publisher=Northeast Operating Rules Advisory Committee |date=November 6, 2011 |edition=10 |via=National Transportation Safety Board |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203171210/http://dms.ntsb.gov/public/58000-58499/58167/585157.pdf |archivedate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Much of the MBTA Commuter Rail system is governed by NORAC rule 251, as the tracks are signalled for movement in one direction of travel only. During the 1990s, parts of the system, such as the Framingham/Worcester Line, were re-signalled to allow a more advanced mode of operations known as NORAC rule 261, which allows trains to operate in either direction on both tracks where double track is available. During the morning rush hour, both tracks can be simultaneously used for inbound traffic, allowing one train to make local stops while an express train overtakes the local train.<ref>{{cite web |author=Trahan, Tyler |title=The First T-Alert |url=http://iridethet.blogspot.com/2011/12/first-t-alert.html |date=December 9, 2011 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn each train, the cab car is attached at the end closest to the downtown Boston terminal station for the particular line (either North or South Station), and the locomotive is attached at the end farthest from the terminal station. On each train serving the North Station lines, the \"ADA\" coach used to carry mobility-limited persons is attached next to the locomotive, allowing level boarding at all suburban stations featuring mini-high platforms. On the other hand, on each train serving the South Station lines, the cab car also serves as the \"ADA\" coach. (The \"ADA\" coaches support compliance with the [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990]].)\n\nTrainlined doors that open automatically via central control are available on some equipment, but at low level platforms the conductor in each car must manually open a trap to allow passengers to descend via stairs onto the platform.\n\n[[Positive Train Control]] is scheduled to be implemented on the entire system per a federal mandate, which requires installation by the end of 2018 with the possibility of a two-year extension. {{As of|November 2015}}, the MBTA expects to complete PTC on the southside lines by December 2018, on the northside lines by March 2020, and an overlay for freight on the sections of [[Pan Am Railways]]' Freight Main Line which overlap MBTA territory by August 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Board_Meetings/FMCBPTCAward110215.pdf |title=Commuter Rail Positive Train Control (PTC) Project: Financial Management Control Board Presentation |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=November 2, 2015 |first=Gerard J. |last=Polcari |accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Future operations===\nIn November 2019, the MBTA Fiscal and Management Control Board voted to back plans to further electrify the Commuter Rail system and increase service along key corridors. The resolution in which the board passed instructs the MBTA to prepare to launch a pilot service along the Fairmount line and a portion of the Newburyport/Rockport line where Commuter Rail service would be increased and fares reduced to that of a rapid transit ticket. Both of those lines, as well as the Providence/Stoughton line, are also to be electrified under the plan. The projected cost of such plans were not immediately clear at the time of the board's vote, but projections range from $10.6 billion to $28.9 billion, depending upon the results of the pilot program and future possible expansion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/bostonomix/2019/11/04/mbta-regional-rail-electric-trains |title=MBTA Board Commits To Reimagined Commuter Rail System |publisher=WBUR |date=November 4, 2019 |first=Chris |last=Lisinski |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Planned expansions==\n<!-- EDITORIAL NOTE: When major updates are made to this section, be sure to also update the brief summary section in the main [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] article, which points to here. -->\n\n===South Station lines===\n{{Outdated|section|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:Foxboro MBTA station, Foxborough MA.jpg|thumb|right|Foxboro station is proposed as the terminus of a Franklin Line branch]]\nThe [[South Coast Rail]] project is proposed to extend commuter rail service to the South Coast cities of [[Taunton, Massachusetts|Taunton]], [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], and [[New Bedford]]. After previous service was discontinued in 1958, the project surfaced in the 1980s. A full planning process was held from 1990 until its suspension in 2002. Planning restarted from the beginning in 2007; the Final Environmental Impact Statement was issued in August 2013. Several separately-funded projects, such as bridge reconstructions, have been undertaken, including major tie replacement (beginning in November 2013), and $2.3 billion was appropriated to the project in an April 2014 state bill.<ref name=bill>{{cite web |url=https://malegislature.gov/Laws/SessionLaws/Acts/2014/Chapter79 |title=Session Laws: Chapter 79 of the Acts of 2014 |date=April 18, 2014 |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> However, full construction has been repeatedly delayed. Plans were changed in 2017 to have limited Phase 1 diesel service via the [[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] in 2022, with full electric service via Stoughton in 2030. The modified plan, which is expected to cost $3.42 billion, proved immediately controversial.<ref name=sharp>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/regionals/south/2017/06/16/sharp-differences-over-latest-plan-for-south-coast-rail/Vlmt4rC3DXy8Wo5gIJWLYI/story.html |title=Sharp differences over latest plan for South Coast Rail |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=June 16, 2017 |first=John |last=Laidler |accessdate=June 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA Providence Line extension to [[Wickford Junction (MBTA station)|Wickford Junction]], in [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island]] opened on April 23, 2012. The [[Rhode Island Department of Transportation]] is also studying the feasibility of serving existing Amtrak stations in [[Kingston (Amtrak station)|Kingston]] and [[Westerly (Amtrak station)|Westerly]] as well as constructing new stations in [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]], [[East Greenwich, Rhode Island|East Greenwich]], and [[Davisville, Rhode Island|West Davisville]]. Federal funding has also been provided for preliminary planning of a new station in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ri.gov/engineering/intermod/index.asp#ComRail |title=Intermodal Planning |publisher=Rhode Island Department of Transportation |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726192250/http://www.dot.ri.gov/engineering/intermod/index.asp#ComRail |archivedate=July 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThere is also a proposal to extend the [[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] to [[Wareham, Massachusetts|Wareham]] and eventually to [[Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts|Buzzards Bay]]. The [[CapeFLYER]] started service along this section to [[Hyannis (CCRTA station)|Hyannis]] on summer weekends in 2013.\n\nIn September 2013, the state announced plans to run [[diesel multiple unit]] (DMU) service between [[Back Bay (MBTA station)|Back Bay]] and the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] on [[Track 61 (Boston)|Track 61]] beginning in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/09/05/state-begin-innovative-rail-service-between-seaport-district-and-back-bay/oHUinYj30lzOV6KNCQUMEJ/story.html |title=State to begin innovative rail service between Seaport District and Back Bay |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Leung, Shirley |date=September 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, the MBTA announce it would purchase DMU self-propelled rail cars for the Fairmount Line with eventual expansion to five other lines, including Track 61, to be known as the [[Indigo Line]]. The planned DMU procurement was canceled in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727155548/http://www.bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2015/06/charlie_baker_derails_t_trains |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2015/06/charlie_baker_derails_t_trains |title=Charlie Baker derails T trains |archivedate=July 27, 2015 |newspaper=Boston Herald |last=Stout |first=Matt |date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> A new [[West Station (MBTA station)|West Station]], is planned to be built on the Framingham-Worcester line in the [[Beacon Park Yard]] site, where it may also connect to North Station via the [[Grand Junction Railroad]].<ref name=Annear>{{cite news|last=Annear|first=Steve|title=Take A Ride On The MBTA's 'New Indigo Line' In 2024|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2014/01/09/massdot-capital-plan-proposal/|accessdate=March 11, 2014|newspaper=[[Boston Magazine]]|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===North Station lines===\nThere is a proposal to build a South Salem station in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], to improve access to [[Salem State University]], as well as to extend Commuter Rail to [[Peabody, Massachusetts]] and [[Danvers, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Documents/North_Shore_Transit_Improvements/ExecSum.pdf |title=Draft North Shore Transit Improvements Project-MIS: Executive Summary |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=August 13, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113145925/http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Documents/North_Shore_Transit_Improvements/ExecSum.pdf |archivedate=November 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe former state Secretary of Transportation [[James Aloisi]] indicated in 2009 support for commuter service from Worcester to North Station via Clinton and Ayer, presumably along the [[Worcester, Nashua and Rochester Railroad]] right of way, owned by [[Pan Am Railways]] {{as of|2009|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20090428/NEWS/904280486/1052 |title=MBTA warns of cuts / Transportation future hot topic |author=Priyanka Dayal |newspaper=Worcester Telegram |date=April 28, 2009 |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the state of [[New Hampshire]] created the [[New Hampshire Rail Transit Authority]] and allocated money to build platforms at Nashua and Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.nh.gov/media/news/2007/072607rail.html |title=Governor Lynch Ceremonially Signs Law Supporting Development Of Commuter Rail in New Hampshire |date=July 27, 2007 |publisher=State of New Hampshire Governor's Office |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327002340/http://www.governor.nh.gov/media/news/2007/072607rail.html |archivedate=March 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA 2008 article in the ''[[Eagle Tribune]]'' claimed that Massachusetts is negotiating to buy property which has the potential to extend the Haverhill Line to [[Plaistow, New Hampshire]]. Funding is available, and Plaistow is potentially interested, but wants to better understand the potential drawbacks of being the location of the layover station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/punewshh/local_story_072061531.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731144451/http://www.eagletribune.com/punewshh/local_story_072061531.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2012 |title=Haverhill chamber chief supports train stop in Plaistow |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |author=Carey, Meghan |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/punewsnh/local_story_069070842.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729224256/http://www.eagletribune.com/punewsnh/local_story_069070842.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |title=Plaistow officials hopeful MBTA considers rail extension |author=Carey, Meghan |date=March 9, 2008 |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |accessdate=August 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===North\u2013South Rail Link===\n{{main|North\u2013South Rail Link}}\nNo direct connection exists between the two downtown commuter rail terminals; to travel from one station to the other, passengers must use the [[MBTA subway]] or [[MBTA Bus|bus]] lines to make the connection. A [[North\u2013South Rail Link]] has been proposed to unite the two halves of the commuter rail system. For non-revenue transfers of equipment, the MBTA and Amtrak use the [[Grand Junction Railroad and Depot Company|Grand Junction Branch]].\n\n==Freight service==\n[[File:BostonSandandGravel.agr.jpg|thumb|left|Boston Sand and Gravel and tracks as seen from an MBTA train]]\nOn the North Side lines, as part of the original sale agreement, B&M and its successor [[Pan Am Railways]] (formerly Guilford Transportation Industries) retains \"perpetual and exclusive\" trackage rights for freight service. Pan Am provides freight service on those lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctps.org/bostonmpo/3_programs/1_transportation_plan/2030Tranplan_ch2c.pdf |title=2030 Transportation Plan Chapter 2: The Boston Region MPO and its Existing Transportation System (Part 3) |date=April 2007 |publisher=Boston Region Metropolitan Planning Organization |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717113751/http://www.ctps.org/bostonmpo/3_programs/1_transportation_plan/2030Tranplan_ch2c.pdf |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Boston Sand and Gravel]] has an agreement with Pan Am to operate its shortline [[New Hampshire Northcoast]] Railroad trains from [[Ossipee, New Hampshire]] to just north of Boston's North Station to supply aggregates to its plant on the Boston/Cambridge border.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonsand.com/nhnorthcoast.aspx |title=NH NORTHCOAST |publisher=Boston Sand & Gravel |year=2011 |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107073628/http://www.bostonsand.com/nhnorthcoast.aspx |archivedate=November 7, 2011 }}</ref> An occasional move occurs with run-through power from [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] to supply coal the Merrimack Station power plant in [[Bow, New Hampshire]], over the Fitchburg Line. The Haverhill and Fitchburg lines also host four to six Pan Am manifest freight trains per day.\n\nOn the South Side lines, [[CSX Transportation]] retains trackage rights over much of the former New Haven territory. Limited service is also provided by the [[Providence & Worcester Railroad]] on the Providence Line, principally from Central Falls (the intersection with its main line to Worcester) through Providence towards New Haven (although some freights go as far east as Attleboro before leaving the corridor).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwrr.com/PWmap3.html |title=P&W Map |publisher=Providence & Worcester Railroad |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425081000/http://www.pwrr.com/PWmap3.html |archivedate=April 25, 2012 }}</ref> The [[Bay Colony Railroad]] provides a limited amount of service on some lines.\n\nCSXT used to provide intermodal, autorack, and general merchandise over the Worcester Line, a part of CSXT's Boston Line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://csx.com/index.cfm/customers/maps/csx-system-map/ |title=CSX System Map |publisher=CSX Transportation |accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> This part of the Commuter Rail network could host over 12 mainline freight trains per day, including descendants of Conrail's expedited intermodal Trail Van trains. Currently most freight service terminates in Framingham, and a trainload facility in Westboro, with limited freight service east through [[Beacon Park Yard]] in Allston to a few local customers. In 2013 CSX moved its intermodal service from Beacon Park to an expanded yard in Worcester.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transportation.blog.state.ma.us/blog/2009/11/csx-rail-agreement-south-coast-rail-plans-move-forward.html |title=CSX Rail Agreement, South Coast Rail Plans Move Forward |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |date=November 25, 2009 |accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tg20130617\">{{cite news | url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20130617/NEWS/306179788/1237 | title=CSX project wrap-up means money for city | work=[[Telegram & Gazette]] | date=June 17, 2013 | accessdate=September 1, 2014 | author=Kotsopoulos, Nick}}</ref>\n\nOn its former Old Colony division, the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] (NYNH&H) essentially vacated its right of freight operations by abandoning the tracks in 1959. As MBTA rebuilt the tracks, it gained freight service rights, and those rights were franchised to [[Conrail]] (predecessor to CSX), which provided freight service on the former Old Colony division.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Art and architecture==\n{{see also|Arts on the Line}}\nAs parts of their Arts on the Line program, the MBTA has public art at certain commuter rail stations. Large sculptures and murals are present at South Station, Back Bay, and Lynn, while a number of other stations include historic information panels on station signs.<ref name=MBTAPubArt>{{cite web|title=Public Art in Transit: Over the Years|url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/art_collection/|website=mbta.com|publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|accessdate=June 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625094038/http://mbta.com/about_the_mbta/art_collection/|archive-date=June 25, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Railways}}\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Commuter rail in North America]]\n*[[List of Massachusetts railroads]]\n*[[Commuter rail in North America#List of North American commuter rail operators|List of North American commuter rail operators]]\n*[[List of suburban and commuter rail systems]]\n*[[List of United States commuter rail systems by ridership]]\n{{col-break|gap=10em}}\n*Other commuter rail operations in Massachusetts:\n**[[Cape Cod and Hyannis Railroad]] (defunct)\n**[[Connecticut River Line]] (proposed)\n**[[Hartford Line]]\n{{col-end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n*[http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/rail/ MBTA - Commuter Rail Schedules and Maps]\n*[http://www.keoliscs.com/ Keolis Commuter Services]\n*[http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ NETransit - MBTA Fleet Roster]\n\n{{MBTA}}\n{{Keolis}}\n{{Northeast Corridor navbox}}\n{{USCommRail}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mbta Commuter Rail}}\n[[Category:Keolis]]\n[[Category:MBTA Commuter Rail| ]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts railroads]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island railroads]]\n[[Category:Transportation in New England]]\n[[Category:Commuter rail in the United States]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greater Boston rail system}}\n{{Infobox rail\n| railroad_name      =MBTA Commuter Rail\n| system_map         =MBTA Commuter Rail and funding district map.svg \n| map_size           =300\n| map_caption        =MBTA Commuter Rail system map\n| image              =MBTA_F40PHM-2C.JPG\n| image_size         =300\n| image_caption      = MBTA train at [[Route 128 station]] on the [[Providence/Stoughton Line]].\n| marks              =MBTX\n| locale             =Eastern [[Massachusetts]] and [[Rhode Island]]\n| predecessor_line   = [[Boston and Maine Railroad]]<br>[[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]]<br>[[New York Central Railroad]]<br>[[Penn Central Transportation Company]]\n| start_year         =1964 (beginning of MBTA subsidies)<br />1973 and 1976 (MBTA asset purchases)<br />1981 (full consolidation)&nbsp;\n| end_year           = &nbsp;present\n| length             = {{convert|398|mi|km}}\n| gauge              ={{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| hq_city            =[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| website            =[http://mbta.com/ MBTA.com]\n}}\n\nThe '''MBTA Commuter Rail''' system serves as the [[commuter rail]] arm of the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]'s transportation coverage of [[Greater Boston]] in the [[United States]]. Trains run over 398 miles of track to 141 different stations, with 58 stations on the north side with the remaining 83 stations on the south. It is operated under contract by [[Keolis]], which took over operations on July 1, 2014 from the Massachusetts Bay Commuter Railroad Company (MBCR).\n\nAs of the third quarter of 2019, average weekday ridership of the system was 119,800,<ref name=apta>{{cite web |url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q3-Ridership-APTA.pdf |title=Transit Ridership Report: Third Quarter 2019 |date=January 30, 2020 |publisher=American Public Transportation Association}}</ref> making it the [[List of United States commuter rail systems by ridership|sixth-busiest commuter rail system in the U.S.]], behind the three New York-area systems, the [[Metra|Chicago-area system]], and the [[SEPTA Regional Rail|Philadelphia-area system]].<ref name=apta/> The line's characteristic purple-trimmed coaches operate as far south as [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island]], and as far north as [[Newburyport, Massachusetts|Newburyport]] and as far west as [[Fitchburg, Massachusetts|Fitchburg]], both in [[Massachusetts]].\n\nTrains originate at two major [[Terminal station|terminals]] in [[Boston]]\u2014[[South Station]] and [[North Station]]\u2014with both transportation hubs offering connections to [[Amtrak]], local bus, intercity bus via [[South Station Bus Terminal]], and subway lines. Currently [[North\u2013South Rail Link|no passenger rail infrastructure]] ''directly'' connects them, other than existing MBTA subway lines, however, MassDOT is studying the proposed [[North\u2013South Rail Link]], which would provide a solution to the problem.\n\n==Current lines==\n{{see also|List of MBTA Commuter Rail stations}}No lines feed into both the North and South Stations.[[Image:MBTA Commuter Rail Map.svg|thumb|MBTA Commuter Rail system]]\nThe following lines terminate at [[South Station]] (listed from southeast to west):<ref name=\"RailMap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/rail/|title=Commuter Rail Maps and Schedules|work=MBTA.com|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Greenbush Line]]\n*[[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]], consisting of:\n**[[Kingston/Plymouth Line]]\n**[[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] (the [[CapeFlyer|CapeFLYER]] operates over this line Memorial Day\u2013Labor Day using MBTA equipment)\n*[[Fairmount Line]]\n*[[Providence/Stoughton Line]]\n*[[Franklin Line]] (with pilot service to {{bts|Foxboro}} as the Foxboro Line)\n*[[Needham Line]]\n*[[Framingham/Worcester Line]]\n\nThe following lines terminate at [[North Station]] (listed from west to northeast):<ref name=\"RailMap\" />\n*[[Fitchburg Line]]\n*[[Lowell Line]]\n*[[Haverhill Line]]\n*[[Newburyport/Rockport Line]]\n\n==Operational history==\n\n===Consolidation under MBTA control===\n\n====Boston & Maine Railroad====\nThe Commonwealth of Massachusetts's involvement with the operating facets of commuter rail began in 1967 when the [[Boston & Maine Corporation|Boston & Maine Railroad]] (B&M) petitioned the [[Interstate Commerce Commission]] to discontinue all passenger services.<ref name=netransit /> Service north of the state line was discontinued, but most service in Massachusetts was preserved through a contract between the Commonwealth and the B&M, at this time still an independent railroad company. The Commonwealth and MBTA began to purchase several lines, like the [[Lowell Line]] between Somerville and Wilmington, from the B&M.\n\nIn 1969 the B&M transported 24,000 passengers every weekday on four separate routes. Its yearly deficit was {{USD|3.2 million}}. A pool of 86 [[Budd Rail Diesel Car]]s provided the service.<ref>{{Dorin-Commuter|p=13}}</ref> B&M filed for bankruptcy protection in 1970. All remaining B&M commuter assets, with the exception of yard tracks and freight-only branches, were sold to the Commonwealth on December 14, 1976, though B&M was contracted to operate the service using its existing fleet of diesel railcars.<ref name=netransit />\n\n====New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad====\nThe [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] (NYNH&H), the long-time operator of most South Station commuter trains, filed for bankruptcy for the last time in 1961.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brief History of the New Haven |url=https://www.nhrhta.org/history |website=New Haven Railroad Historical and Technical Association |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref> Two years earlier in 1959, the railroad had discontinued passenger service on the Old Colony division in southeastern Massachusetts. On July 28, 1965, the MBTA signed an agreement with the New Haven Railroad to purchase {{convert|11|miles}} of the former Old Colony mainline from [[Fort Point Channel]] to South Braintree in order to construct a new rapid transit line along the corridor. The line was expected to be completed within two years. The agreement also provided for the MBTA to subsidize commuter service on the railroad's remaining commuter rail lines for $1.2 million annually.<ref name=netransit /><ref>{{cite news |title=MBTA Buys Old Colony Line For a South Shore Express |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=July 29, 1965 |first=Robert |last=Carr |id = {{ProQuest|366125778}}}}</ref>\n\nThe NH was included in the [[Penn Central Transportation Company]] (PC) merger in 1968, which itself filed bankruptcy in 1970.<ref name=drury>{{cite book | last = Drury | first = George H. | authorlink = | title = The Historical Guide to North American Railroads: Histories, Figures, and Features of more than 160 Railroads Abandoned or Merged since 1930 | publisher = [[Kalmbach Publishing]] | year = 1994 | location = [[Waukesha, Wisconsin]] | pages = 222\u2013229, 248 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-89024-072-8}}</ref> MBTA purchased many PC southside commuter lines on January 27, 1973, including the [[Providence/Stoughton Line]] as far as the Rhode Island border plus the branch to Stoughton, the [[Franklin Line]] and [[Needham Line]] and the [[Framingham/Worcester Line]] from Riverside to Framingham, as well as a number of abandoned lines and lines without passenger service including the Old Colony mainline from Boston to Braintree and the [[Plymouth/Kingston Line]] (which were later restored).<ref name=netransit /> PC merged into [[Conrail]] on April 1, 1976; the MBTA bought the equipment but Conrail took over operations of the southside lines. The MBTA also purchased the [[Fairmount Line]] to restore it for passenger service as a bypass during [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] reconstruction.<ref name=netransit />\n\n====New York Central Railroad====\nThe [[Framingham/Worcester Line]], historically part of the [[Boston & Albany Railroad]] (B&A), was merged into the [[New York Central Railroad]] (NYC) and its ownership subsequently passed to PC in 1968. As part of the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] Boston Extension's construction in the 1960s, the Worcester Line's roadbed between Route 128 and Boston was sold to the [[Massachusetts Turnpike Authority]], with the provison that the control of the railroad remain with NYC. Conrail inherited the line which formed a vital freight artery between Boston's Beacon Yard and Conrail's [[Selkirk Yard]]. The Riverside-Framingham section was sold to the MBTA in 1976 as part of their larger acquisition of PC commuter assets, but the section past Framingham remained in Conrail control.<ref name=netransit /> In September 2009, Conrail successor [[CSX Transportation]] and the Commonwealth finalized a $100 million agreement to purchase CSX's Framingham to Worcester tracks, as well as the [[Grand Junction Railroad]] plus lines which will be part of the [[South Coast Rail]] project, to improve service on the Framingham/Worcester Line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transportation.blog.state.ma.us/blog/2009/09/lt-governor-historic-csx-rail-agreement.html |title=Lt. Governor: Historic CSX Rail Agreement |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |work=Commonwealth Conversations: Transportation |date=September 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref> After several years of construction and negotiations, ownership of the line was transferred to the commonwealth on October 4, 2012, with increased service on the outer section of the line beginning several weeks later.<ref name=netransit /><ref name=29oct>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20121004/NEWS/110049827/1116 |title=At CSX freight yard, Murray touts increased train service |newspaper=Worcester Telegram & Gazette |author=Monahan, John J. |date=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Combined operations===\nThe Northeast Rail Service Act of 1981 compelled Conrail to transfer operations of all passenger and commuter services to local transit authorities, resulting in Conrail ceasing all subsidized passenger rail services.<ref>Northeast Rail Service Act of 1981, Pub. L. 97-35, {{Usc-title-chap|45|20}}, August 13, 1981.</ref> B&M won the contract for the southside lines; for the first time, all Boston commuter service was operated by one entity. After bankruptcy, B&M continued to operate trains under the protection of the federal bankruptcy court, in the hopes that a reorganization could make it profitable again. It emerged from the court's protection when [[Timothy Mellon]]'s [[Pan Am Railways|Guilford Transportation Industries]] (GTI) bought it in 1983.<ref name=netransit /> GTI let the contract expire in 1987, after a bitter strike had shut down most of the northside lines in 1986.<ref name=netransit />\n\nFrom 1987 to 2003, [[Amtrak]] managed all of Boston's commuter rail.<ref name=netransit /> The relationship between MBTA and Amtrak was often rocky, and Amtrak did not submit a bid when the contract expired in 2003. MBTA observers saw Amtrak as having been a reliable manager and operator, but Amtrak sometimes experienced strained relations with the MBTA. Quibbles centered on equipment failures, crewing issues about the number of conductors per train, and responsibility for late trains. Because of these issues, and Amtrak's repeated statements that the MBTA contract was unreasonable, few were surprised at Amtrak's decision not to bid again.<ref name=\"MBCR contract\">{{cite web\n| title =MBTA Exercises Option With MBCR For Commuter Rail Service, Launches New Customer-Focused Improvements| publisher = MBTA| date = January 6, 2010| url = http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=18672&month=&year=| quote =MBTA extends MBCR contract another two years.}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|MBCR}}\nTwo tenders were submitted, one from GTI and another from the newly formed Massachusetts Bay Commuter Railroad Company (MBCR), a partnership between [[Veolia Transport|Connex]] (later Veolia), [[Bombardier Transportation]] and Alternate Concepts, Inc., the latter of which won the tender. MBCR took over the MBTA Commuter Rail operation from Amtrak in July 2003. The MBCR contract originally expired in July 2008 but had an additional five-year option; it was later extended three years to July 2011 and then another two to July 2013.<ref name=\"MBCR contract\" /><ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2010/01/07/commuter_rail_firm_gets_contract_extension/ Commuter Rail Firm Gets Contract Extension] Boston.com, accessed February 16, 2010.</ref> After concerns about on-time performance, the 2011 extension increased the fine for late trains from $100 to $300.<ref>Boston Metro, June 6, 2008, p. 2.</ref>\n[[File:Logo Keolis.png|thumb|Logo of Keolis Commuter Services, the current operator of MBTA Commuter Rail. This logo appears on employee uniforms and public timetables.]]\nIn August 2012, MBCR and [[Keolis]] were the two bidders for the contract. On January 8, 2014, the MBTA awarded Keolis the contract for $2.68 billion over eight years, with the possibility of two two-year extensions that could bring the total price to $4.3 billion.<ref>http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442451214&month=1&year=14 MBTA press release on Keolis Commuter Services award</ref> Keolis took over the operations on July 1, 2014. Keolis lost $29.3 million in its first year of operation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://trn.trains.com/news/news-wire/2016/02/22-mbta-keolis | title=Keolis loses millions of dollars on its MBTA contract | work=[[Trains Magazine]] | date=February 22, 2016 | accessdate=February 23, 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Service changes since MBTA takeover==\n\n===Expansions===\nSeveral significant improvements have been made during MBTA's period of stewardship which started circa 1973. However, the Commonwealth's support for rail operations began in the 1950s with contracted operations and subsidies to railroads providing commuter service, and more so in 1964 with the advent of MBTA.\n*The Commonwealth of Massachusetts pioneered the concept of \"Park and Ride\" by providing funds to construct the [[Route 128 Station]] on NH's Providence Line, at a location where the radial line intersected with [[Massachusetts Route 128]], the [[beltway]] encircling greater Boston. Route 128 Station was established 1953 by NH President [[Frederic C. Dumaine, Jr.]]. The initial station was simple in design, built as a parking lot located next to the tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhrhta.org/htdocs/images0200.htm |title=Route 128 Station |date=February 1, 2000 |publisher=New Haven Railroad Historical and Technical Association |accessdate=August 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719074252/http://www.nhrhta.org/htdocs/images0200.htm |archive-date=July 19, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*B&M's Eastern Route formerly operated across the bridge at Merrimack River and as far north as [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] on the former [[Eastern Railroad (Massachusetts)|Eastern Railroad]] alignment. Service past [[Ipswich (MBTA station)|Ipswich]] to [[Newburyport (MBTA station)|Newburyport]] was limited to a single daily round trip after 1967, and suspended in April 1976.<ref name=netransit /> Freight service to Newburyport lasted until 1984, and the line was formally abandoned in 1994 even as preparations began for restored service. After a brief period of abandonment, commuter rail service to Newburyport resumed on October 26, 1998, with an infill stop at [[Rowley (MBTA station)|Rowley]].<ref name=abandoned>{{cite book |title=Lost Railroads of New England |author=Karr, Ronald Dale |edition=Third |publisher=Branch Line Press |year=2010 |isbn=9780942147117 |page=54 }}</ref>\n*As part of the Northeast Corridor Improvement Program II (NECIP II) of the 1990s, MBTA's Providence Line was electrified using federal funds provided to Amtrak for its ''[[Acela Express]]'' project. However, MBTA does not operate electric equipment on the Providence Line, as such equipment would be unusable on other lines.\n*As [[Big Dig]] environmental mitigation, MBTA invested heavily in the Commuter Rail system by restoring large sections of the Old Colony division, which was abandoned in 1959. Service along the two main [[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]] was reestablished in 1997, and the [[Greenbush Line]] opened in 2007.<ref name=netransit />\n*After 1975, [[Framingham/Worcester Line]] service was cut back to [[Framingham (MBTA station)|Framingham]], though other lines reached exurbs more distant from Boston than Framingham. As compensation for delays in the Old Colony Lines restoration, rush-hour service to [[Worcester Union Station]] was restored in 1994, with infill stations at [[Ashland (MBTA station)|Ashland]], [[Southborough (MBTA station)|Southborough]], [[Westborough (MBTA station)|Westborough]], and [[Grafton (MBTA station)|Grafton]] stations were added in the MetroWest region between 2000 and 2002.<ref name=netransit /> The service was successful, resulting in relative de-emphasis of Amtrak and commuter bus services operating in the same corridor.\n*During the 1979-1987 reconstruction of the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]], Amtrak and MBTA trains were diverted over the Dorchester Branch, which had not seen passenger traffic since 1944. As part of this project, MBTA allowed [[Centralized Traffic Control]] to be installed on this branch, greatly increasing its signal capacity.<ref name=netransit /> Regular service was kept on the [[Fairmount Line]] after 1987 because the relocated service was popular with residents of Dorchester and Roxbury. As Big Dig mitigation, MBTA rebuilt existing stations and is adding 4 new stations along the line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/default.asp?id=14261 |title=Fairmount Line Improvements |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=December 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129100850/http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/default.asp?id=14261 |archive-date=January 29, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The first of these, [[Talbot Avenue station|Talbot Avenue]], opened on November 12, 2012, followed by [[Newmarket station (MBTA)|Newmarket]] and [[Four Corners/Geneva station|Four Corners/Geneva]] on July 1, 2013.<ref name=globetalbot>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/yourtown/news/dorchester/2012/11/mbta_opens_new_commuter_rail_s.html |title=MBTA opens new commuter rail station at Talbot Avenue in Dorchester on Fairmount Line |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Rocheleau, Matt |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=November 12, 2012}}</ref> [[Blue Hill Avenue station]] was opened on February 25, 2019, after many delays.\n*Agreement with the state of [[Rhode Island]] allowed MBTA's Attleboro Line to extend to [[Providence, Rhode Island]] during the late 1980s. At first, only weekday service was provided. In the mid-2000s, a new agreement with [[RIDOT]] provided funding to allow the service to operate on weekends also. Service was extended further south to  [[T. F. Green Airport (MBTA station)|T. F. Green Airport]] in [[Warwick, Rhode Island]] in December 2010 and to [[Wickford Junction (MBTA station)|Wickford Junction]] in [[North Kingston, Rhode Island|North Kingston]] in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.turnto10.com/news/2010/dec/06/7/boston-tf-green-rail-service-debuts-ar-316999 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205001015/http://www2.turnto10.com/news/2010/dec/06/7/boston-tf-green-rail-service-debuts-ar-316999 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 5, 2013 |title=Boston to T.F. Green rail service debuts |newspaper=NBC 10 News |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 1, 2011 }}</ref> This represents the first commuter service in Rhode Island south of Providence since 1981.<ref name=netransit />\n*In 2013, the [[CapeFLYER]] service began running from [[South Station (Boston)|South Station]] to [[Hyannis (MBTA station)|Hyannis]] on summer weekends - the first direct service from Boston to Cape Cod since 1959. Though officially a Cape Cod Regional Transit Authority service, the CapeFLYER uses MBTA equipment.<ref name=netransit /> Should this pilot service be successful, regular commuter service may be extended from [[Middleborough/Lakeville (MBTA station)|Middleborough/Lakeville]] to [[Buzzards Bay (MBTA station)|Buzzards Bay]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capenews.net/communities/sandwich/news/2650 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130819032715/http://www.capenews.net/communities/sandwich/news/2650 |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2013 |title=Cape Commuter Rail Is A Real Possibility |newspaper=Cape News |author=Kinsella, James |date=August 16, 2013 |accessdate=August 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n*A 4-mile extension of the [[Fitchburg Line]] to [[Wachusett (MBTA station)|Wachusett station]] opened on September 30, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Documents/Schedules_and_Maps/Upcoming_Schedules/Commuter_Rail/Fitchburg.pdf |title=FITCHBURG LINE Schedule effective September 30, 2016 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=September 30, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926143419/http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Documents/Schedules_and_Maps/Upcoming_Schedules/Commuter_Rail/Fitchburg.pdf |archivedate=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n*On November 14, 2013, MBTA began rehabilitating and rebuilding the tracks along 33 miles of right-of-way the agency acquired to restore service to [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]] and [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]] (See [[South Coast Rail]]).\n\n===Contractions===\n\nDuring the period of MBTA control, services have also been curtailed:\n\n*Commuter rail services along the [[Millis Branch]] and [[Dedham Branch]], by 1966 consisting of only a single daily rush-hour round trip, were discontinued by the NYNH&H on April 21, 1967 and have not been replaced.<ref name=netransit />\n*All former B&M services that extended north of the Massachusetts border were curtailed by 1967, except for a brief period of experimental service from January 28, 1980 to March 1, 1981.<ref name=\"netransit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/MBTARouteHistory.pdf |title=Changes to Transit Service in the MBTA district |accessdate=September 29, 2007 |last=Belcher |first=Jonathan |date=August 10, 2007 |publisher= }}</ref> Since then, restoration and extension of the Lowell Line to [[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua]], [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], and [[Concord, New Hampshire]], and the Haverhill Line to [[Portland, Maine]], have been repeatedly discussed. In 2001, Amtrak commenced operation of the ''[[Downeaster (train)|Downeaster]]'' between Boston's North Station and Portland under the auspices of the [[Northern New England Passenger Rail Authority]]. The Nashua service discussion is continuing in the context of the widening of [[Interstate 93]] in New Hampshire.\n*The B&M operated one daily round trip to South Sudbury (19.7 miles from Boston) over the former [[Central Massachusetts Railroad]] until its discontinuation on November 26, 1971.<ref name=netransit />\n*Passenger service on the [[Lexington and West Cambridge Railroad|Lexington Branch]] ended on January 10, 1977.<ref name=netransit /> The Northwest Extension of the [[MBTA Red Line]] replaced the service as far as Alewife in West Cambridge. No commuter rail service reaches the towns of Arlington, Lexington, and Bedford, Massachusetts. Today, the rail-banked line forms the [[Minuteman Bikeway]] and is a linear park in the vicinity of [[Davis Square, Somerville]].\n<!--Not supported by any evidence that these services lasted past 1960\n*The Lowell-Lawrence-Haverhill-Newburyport line had a [[Budd Rail Diesel Car|Budd RDC-1]] running on it well into the 1970s, but was discontinued when MBTA replaced the aging Budd equipment with more modern locomotive hauled trains. The route also saw one round-trip per day from Newburyport via Bradford, Andover, and Reading to Boston.-->\n*The southern half of the [[Woburn Branch Railroad|Woburn Loop]] still operated when the MBTA took over control, joining the Lowell Line at Winchester. Half the Lowell Line services terminated at Woburn Heights (10.0 miles from Boston), while the others stopped at North Woburn (today's Anderson RTC) and continued to Lowell. Weekend service ended on September 7, 1980, and all service on the branch stopped on January 30, 1981.<ref name=netransit/>\n*The Fitchburg Line under B&M operations terminated at [[Ayer, Massachusetts]], but was subsequently extended as far as [[Gardner, Massachusetts]] in January 1981. However, the service between Gardner and Fitchburg was ended at the end of 1986 after the parallel [[Massachusetts Route 2]] was upgraded to expressway standards, reducing travel time between these cities.<ref name=netransit />\n\n==Rolling stock==\n[[File:Outbound train stopped at Auburndale.JPG|thumb|A typical Commuter Rail train, consisting of one diesel locomotive and five coaches, at Auburndale station in 2012.]]\n\nAll MBTA commuter rail service is provided by [[push-pull train]]s powered by [[diesel locomotive]]s with a [[cab car]] on the opposite end. Trains typically have four to eight coaches (with six the most common) and seat between 400 and 1400 passengers. Approximately 65 trainsets are needed for weekday service.<ref name=\"roster\">{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ |title=The MBTA Vehicle Inventory Page |publisher=NETransit |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe primary heavy maintenance facility is the [[MBTA Commuter Rail Maintenance Facility]], located in [[Somerville, Massachusetts|East Somerville]] on the former site of the Boston and Maine's Boston Engine Terminal. It is also used for midday and overnight storage of trains on the northside lines. Southampton Street Yard and the Readville Interim Layover facility are used for light maintenance and layover service. [[List of Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority yards#Commuter rail|Various other layover facilities]] are used for midday and overnight storage; most are located near the outer ends of the lines.\n\n=== Locomotive fleet ===\n{{As of|2016|6}}, the MBTA owned 125 locomotives. Of these, 85 were in active passenger service, four used for work service, and 36 inactive for various reasons.<ref name=roster /> The current fleet of diesel locomotives comprises a mix of purpose-built passenger locomotives (such as the [[EMD F40PH]]) and freight locomotives rebuilt for passenger use (such as the GMD GP40MCs, which were originally GMD GP40-2LWs). All passenger locomotives are equipped with [[head end power]] (HEP), though some locomotives exclusively used for non-revenue work service are not.<ref name=roster />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Numbers<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Image\n|-\n|1973\u20131975\n|[[General Motors Diesel|GMD]]\n|[[GMD GP40MC]]\n|1115\u20131139\n|Rebuilt by AMF in 1997.<ref name=roster />  Some to be rebuilt in Keolis in-house overhaul, others to be rebuilt in Rochester.\n|[[File:MBTA GP40 1136.jpg|100px]]  \n|-\n|1987\u20131988\n|EMD\n|[[EMD F40PH-2C]]\n|1052\u20131053, 1055\u20131056, 1058-1059, 1062, 1067, 1070\u20131072\n|Rebuilt by [[MotivePower|MPI]] 2001\u20132003. 1073 retired and scrapped after the [[1990 Back Bay rail accident]]. All remaining units are being rebuilt by MPI as F40PH-3C class.<ref name=roster /> \n|[[File:MBTA 1055 at Littleton station, May 2019.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1987\u20131988\n|[[MotivePower|MPI]]\n|[[EMD F40PH|MPI F40PH-3C]]\n|1025\u20131026, 1028, 1031\u20131032, 1035, 1050\u20131051, 1054, 1057, 1060\u20131061, 1063\u20131066, 1068-1069, 1074, 1075\n|Rebuilt from F40PH-2C and F40PHM-2C class locomotives by MPI.\n|[[File:MBTA F40PH-3C 1054 Departing Hyde Park Station.png|100px]]\n|-\n|1991\u20131993\n|[[Morrison\u2013Knudsen|M-K]]\n|[[EMD F40PH|M-K F40PHM-2C]]\n|1027, 1029\u20131030, 1033\u20131034, 1036\n|Rebuilt by MPI 2003\u20132004. All units are being rebuilt by MPI as F40PH-3C class.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:MBTA Train 2813.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[MotivePower|MPI]]\n|[[MPI MPXpress#MP36PH-3C|MPI MP36PH-3C]]\n|010-011\n|Purchased from [[Utah Transit Authority]]'s [[FrontRunner]].<ref name=roster /><ref name=\"UTABUY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2011/02/mbta_unveils_fi.html|title=MBTA unveils first new locomotive in 23 years|last=Finucane|first=Martin|date=February 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref>\n|[[File:MBTA locomotive 010 at Buzzards Bay on CapeFLYER trial run.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|MPI\n|[[MPI HSP46]]\n|2000\u20132039\n|Purchased new from [[MotivePower]]. Ordered in 2010.<ref name=rgi20100720>{{cite news | url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/boston-orders-motivepower-hsp46-diesels.html | title=Boston orders MotivePower HSP46 diesels | work=[[Railway Gazette International]] | date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n|[[File:MBTA 2001 at CRMF, October 2013.jpg|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Non-revenue===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Numbers<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes\n!Image\n|-\n|1957\u20131960\n|[[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]]\n|[[EMD GP9]]\n|904\n|Purchased from SEMTA. Ex-MBTA 902 is now at the [[Illinois Railway Museum]]. \n|[[File:MBTA 904 at South Station, March 2018.jpg |100px]]\n|-\n|1971\n|EMD\n|[[EMD GP40]]\n|3247\n|\n|[[File:MBTA 3247 at Porter station, September 2010.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[National Railway Equipment Company|NRE]]\n|[[NRE 3GS21B]]\n|3248\u20133249\n|\n|[[File:MBTA3gs21b at Boston.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n=== Coach fleet ===\n[[File:First revenue round trip of Rotem bilevels at Malden Center (2), April 2013.jpg|thumb|#1800 arrives at Malden Center on the first revenue round trip of the new BTC-4D and CTC-5 coaches]]\n\n{{As of|2016|6}}, the MBTA owned 481 coaches. Of these, 420 were in active service and 61 inactive for various reasons.<ref name=\"roster\" /> Coaches whose designations start with BTC (Blind Trailer Coach) are conventional coaches, while those starting with CTC (Control Trailer Coach) are [[cab car]]s. Cab cars will occasionally also appear in the middle of a consist. Coaches acquired before 1990 were single-level cars with 88 to 127 seats; those since are bilevel cars with 173 to 185 seats.<ref name=roster />\n\nVarious coaches are equipped with electronic doors for use on the [[Old Colony Lines (MBTA)|Old Colony Lines]] and [[Greenbush Line]], which have full-length high-level platforms at all stops. All BTC-3, CTC-3, BTC-4C, and BTC-4D coaches have restrooms.<ref name=\"roster\" /> Trains usually have one of these cars adjacent to the locomotive, as that car will be platformed at all high level platforms regardless of length, and thus handicapped riders will be able to access the restroom car.\n\nDuring winter months, a Ski Train serving [[Wachusett Mountain (ski area)|Wachusett Mountain]] runs on the [[Fitchburg Line]], using a coach car which is equipped for carrying bicycles or skis.<ref name=roster /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wachusett.com/default.aspx?tabid=66|publisher=Wachusett Mountain Ski Area|title=Ski Train To Wachusett|year=2012|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}</ref> During summer months, some [[Newburyport/Rockport Line]] trains to Rockport include one of two cars equipped to carry bicycles.<ref name=roster /><ref name=biketrain>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Riding_the_T/Bikes_on_the_T/Eastern%20Route%20Bike%20Train_11.pdf |title=MBTA Bike Train|author=MBTA |accessdate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> The [[CapeFLYER]] uses car 224, which has been modified as a cafe and baggage car.<ref name=roster />\n\nIn January 2019, the MBTA issued a Request for Qualifications to design additional bilevel coach cars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bc.mbta.com/business_center/bidding_solicitations/pdf/V61PS05_Public%20Announcement_SOQ_2019-01-22.pdf |title=SOLICITATION FOR ENGINEERING AND PROGRAM MANAGEMENT SERVICES IN SUPPORT OF THE BI-LEVEL COMMUTER RAIL COACH PROCUREMENT: REQUEST FOR QUALIFICATIONS |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=January 2019}}</ref> The agency approved a $279 million contract (total project cost of $345 million) for 80 additional Rotem bilevel coaches in September 2019, with delivery expected from September 2022 to June 2024. The MBTA plans an additional procurement of 100 bilevel cars, delivered from 2024 to 2027.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://mbta.com/news/2019-09-23/fmcb-approves-the-procurement-80-new-commuter-rail-bi-level-coaches |title=FMCB Approves the Procurement of 80 New Commuter Rail Bi-Level Coaches |date=September 23, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year built<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Builder<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"50\" |Model<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"70\" |Fleet ID<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Seats<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Notes<ref name=\"roster\" />\n!Image\n|-\n|1978&ndash;79\n|[[Pullman Company|Pullman]]\n|BTC-1C\n|200&ndash;258\n|114\n|The BTC-1C cars were rebuilt from BTC-1 and CTC-1 cars in 1995 and 1996, at which point they were renumbered; coaches 203 and 215 were not rebuilt and are no longer used. Coach 219 is a bike/ski car, 221 a bike car, 224 a cafe car, and 225 planned to be a bike car.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:MBTA 240 at West Natick station, May 2017.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987\n|[[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]\n|BTC-1A\n|350&ndash;389\n|127\n|\n|[[File:Commuter train at Porter 2.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987&ndash;88\n|[[Messerschmitt-B\u00f6lkow-Blohm|MBB]]\n|BTC-3\n|500\u2013510, 512, 514\u2013532\n|86\n|511 and 513 are retired. 501, 503, 505, 508, 509, 516, 517, 522, 526, 527, 528 and 532 are leased to [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] for service on the [[Hartford Line]].<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:MBTA 507 in dead line, April 2014.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|1987&ndash;88\n|MBB\n|CTC-3\n|1500\u20131515, 1517\u20131524, 1526\u20131533\n|96\n|1516 and 1525 are retired. 1505, 1509, 1518 and 1520 are leased to [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]] for service on the [[Hartford Line]].\n|[[File:MBTA 1529 at South Station, May 2016.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1989&ndash;90\n|Bombardier\n|BTC-1B\n|600\u2013611, 613\u2013653\n|122\n|612 is retired.\n|[[File:MBTA 616 shop.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1989&ndash;90\n|Bombardier\n|CTC-1B\n|1600\u20131647, 1649\u20131652\n|122\n|1648 is retired. Cab controllers have been deactivated in coaches 1600&ndash;1624; they are used exclusively as blind coaches.<ref name=roster />\n|[[File:Lynn station with train 172.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1990&ndash;91\n|[[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]]\n|BTC-4\n|700&ndash;749\n|185\n|700\u2013749 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]] in Hornell, New York. They will have some features identical to the 800 series cars, including destination displays and LED lighting.\n|[[File:Bilevel MBTA coaches at South Station, April 2002.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1990&ndash;91\n|Kawasaki\n|CTC-4\n|1700\u20131709, 1711\u20131724\n|175\n|1710 is retired. 1700\u20131709 and 1711\u20131724 have all been overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:Needham Line train 614.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|1997\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4A\n|750&ndash;766\n|182\n|750\u2013766 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:BTC-4A coaches on the CapeFLYER.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2001\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4B\n|767&ndash;781\n|182\n|767\u2013781 are being overhauled by [[Alstom]]\n|[[File:Outbound train at East Braintree Weymouth Landing station, January 2017.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2005\n|Kawasaki\n|BTC-4C\n|900&ndash;932\n|178\n|\n|[[File:BTC-4C coach on CapeFLYER at Buzzards Bay.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|[[Hyundai Rotem]]\n|BTC-4D\n|800&ndash;846\n|179\n|\n|[[File:Rotem car 801 at North Station.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n|Hyundai Rotem\n|CTC-5\n|1800&ndash;1827\n|173\n|\n|[[File:Cab car 1800 at North Station.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Retired equipment===\n[[File:MBTA 1101 with GO coaches at South Station, March 1979.jpg|thumb|An EMD FP10 locomotive with rented GO Transit coaches at South Station in 1978]]\n\nAs the Commonwealth assumed the control of the Commuter Rail during the 1970s, it inherited various non-standard equipment from predecessor railroads. These included:\n\n* Numerous [[Budd Company|Budd]] [[Rail Diesel Car]]s,<ref name=railwayage>{{cite magazine |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1215/is_n11_v192/ai_11544541/ |title=How MBTA rebuilt ridership |magazine=Railway Age |date=November 1991 |accessdate=August 3, 2008 |author=Middleton, William D.}}</ref> including a total of 86 from the B&M, New Haven Railroad and [[SEPTA]]. The RDC fleet was de-powered in the 1970s and turned into locomotive-hauled coaches by Morrison Knudsen.<ref name=railwayage /> These became known as \"Boise Budds\", after the location of the MK shop where the work was done. The RDC fleet was phased out during the 1980s and completely replaced with conventional coaches by 1989.<ref name=roster /> Remaining examples of these units now serve on the [[Grand Canyon Railway]] and [[Hobo Railroad]]; a derelict pair sit on a disused track near North Station, and a single unit has been restored and is displayed at [[Bedford Depot]].\n* In 1978\u20131980 MBTA acquired 19 rebuilt EMD FP10 units which were later transferred to [[Metro North Railroad]] in 1991\u20131993.<ref name=railwayage /> [[EMD GP-9]]s were also operated in Boston suburban service. MBTA #904, one of six GP-9s received from [[SEMTA]] in 1987, is retained as a work engine.<ref name=roster />\n* Ex\u2013[[GO Transit]] stainless steel coaches were operated as an interim solution pending delivery of the CTC-1/BTC-1 order.\n* From 2002 to 2004, MBTA leased some retired Amtrak F40PHs while the F40PHM-2Cs were getting rebuilt.\n* Until 2015, MBTA operated standard F40PHs, numbered 1000-1017.\n\n==Wi-Fi==\n[[File:Outbound Needham Line train at Forest Hills.JPG|thumb|left|Two coaches in 2012 with wraps indicating that they are Wi-Fi enabled. This 2008-built system will be replaced with a new system.]]\nFree [[Wi-Fi]] internet service with limited bandwidth is provided on all trains. A two-tiered model where riders can pay extra for faster service is in planning.<ref name=mbtawifi />\n\nThe program started with a $262,000 pilot in January 2008 on the [[Worcester Line]], where 45 coaches were fitted with routers which connected to cellular data networks. This was the first Wi-Fi available on a commuter rail service in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/141940/article.html |title=Wi-Fi trial Connects Massachusetts Train Passengers |newspaper=PC World |last=Cox |first=John |date=January 28, 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> The Worcester Line was chosen for the pilot phase in part to compensate for low on-time performance, as well as to test the service across the line's varied terrain.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327210717/http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=March 27, 2008 |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |quote=First, it provides one of the best opportunities from a geographical perspective to test Wi-Fi capabilities as it runs from Boston to central Massachusetts (Worcester) through various terrains (hills, wooded areas, etc.) Secondly, we are aware that the Framingham/Worcester trains have experienced significant performance issues due mainly to the owner and operator of the line (CSX). For that, we want to offer Framingham/Worcester customers the first opportunity. |title=Framingham/Worcester Commuter Rail customers: Try our free MBTA Wi-Fi Commuter Rail Connect Test Program! |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=January 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> The program was considered successful; in December 2008, the MBTA announced that Wi-Fi would be available on all trains by mid-2009. Of the 410 coaches then owned by the MBTA, 258 would receive Wi-Fi equipment at a rate of about 30 per month.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=16235&month=&year |title=Free Wi-Fi Service Expanded |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=December 19, 2008 |accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, the MBTA announced that a private company would be building a new $5.6 million network to replace the 2008-built network. The MBTA is not paying for the new network; instead, the company expects to recoup its investment by providing a two-tiered offering. Free limited-bandwidth Wi-Fi will continue to be provided, along with local television broadcasts; a monthly fee will be charged by the company for access to higher bandwidth and other broadcasts, with 7.5% of the fee returned to the MBTA.<ref name=newwifi /> The new system was to be completed in 2016, with the revenue agreement lasting until 2037.<ref name=newwifi >{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/07/24/mbta-revamp-commuter-rail-wifi-system/U2onDF0uABUiOhUPj0SkqO/story.html |title=MBTA to boost Web service on commuter rail |newspaper=The Boston Globe |last=Thadani |first=Trisha |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442452651&month=&year= |title=New WiFi System for Commuter Rail |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=May 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=mbtawifi>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |title=WiFi Commuter Rail Connect |date=October 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101073850/http://mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=January 1, 2016 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2016, the new system was still in permitting and design, except for enhanced Wi-Fi at Back Bay, South Station, and North Station expected to be complete by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226025756/http://www.mbta.com/riding_the_t/wifi/ |archivedate=December 26, 2016 |title=WiFi Commuter Rail Connect |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> In August 2017, the MBTA canceled the $140 million plan due to local opposition to the erection of 320 [[monopole antenna|monopoles]], each {{convert|70|feet|adj=on}} tall, as well as the need to focus on more critical projects like the [[Green Line Extension]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2017/08/10/mbta-nixes-140m-plan-to-upgrade-wifi-on-commuter.html |title=MBTA nixes $140M plan to upgrade Wi-Fi on commuter rail |newspaper=Boston Business Journal |date=August 10, 2017 |first=Don |last=Seiffert}}</ref>\n\n==Fare policy==\n[[Image:MBCR tickets.jpg|right|thumb|Commuter Rail tickets in the form of CharlieTickets purchased at fare vending machines and ticket booths (left) and paper tickets purchased on-board (right).]]\n\nThe MBTA Commuter Rail uses a fare zone policy whereby origin and destination stations are not individually priced, but assigned a zone based on distance from Boston.<ref name=\"FareInfo\">{{cite web|url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/rail/|title=Commuter Rail Fares & Passes |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> There are a total of eleven zones (1A, then 1 through 10) with an increasing fare to or from Boston the higher the zone number. Most stations in inner Boston, as well as stations in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] and [[Medford, Massachusetts|Medford]], are located in zone 1A; trips from this zone are the least expensive and cost the same as rapid transit ($2.40), while the highest priced Zone 10 fares are $12.50 per ride.<ref name=\"FareInfo\" /> Travel between suburban zones without going to Boston is charged an \"interzone\" fare based on the number of zones traveled.<ref name=\"FareInfo\" /> Seniors, those with a disability, and middle and high school students with proper identification receive a 50% discounted rate; children under eleven travel free with a paying adult.<ref name=\"ReducedFares\">{{cite web |url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/reduced_fare_programs/ |title=Reduced Fares |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref> Fares are collected by train conductors; while [[fare evasion]] is explicitly illegal, it is not criminal.<ref name=\"8-2010 Scorecard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Score_Card/Scorecard-2010-08.pdf|title=MBTA Scorecard|date=August 2010|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|page=14|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mass.gov/legis/laws/mgl/159-101.htm|title=Section 101 Evasion of payment of toll or fare |work=Massachusetts General Laws |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTickets may be purchased at automatic vending machines located in principal stations and at suburban stations from nearby businesses and vendors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/sales_locations/ |title=Sales Locations |publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/fares_and_passes/purchase_programs/|title=Purchase Programs|work=MBTA.com|publisher=[[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010}}</ref> Passengers joining at stations without ticketing machines or vendors can purchase tickets on board.<ref name=\"8-2010 Scorecard\" /> Alternatively, riders can use the MBTA mTicket app to purchase tickets on iPhone and Android devices, which allows them to display their tickets on their mobile phone screens rather than presenting paper tickets or passes.<ref name=\"mTicketing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbta.com/fares_and_passes/mticketing/|title=Mobile Ticketing}}</ref> Travelers can purchase tickets as a one-way, round trip, ten ride (no discount), or monthly pass (discounted over daily round-trip purchase).<ref name=\"FareInfo\" />\n\n==Ridership==\nRidership levels on the Commuter Rail have grown since the MBTA's involvement began in the late 1960s, with overall average weekday ridership growing from 29,500 in 1969 to 76,000 in 1990 and 143,700 in 2008. This was accomplished by a series of rationalizations, such as closing lightly used lines, concentrating service on heavily utilized lines, and re-opening formerly abandoned branches with high traffic potential, such as the Old Colony Lines. A general growth of transit usage in the [[Northeastern United States]] also contributed. Growing ridership in this way required substantial capital investment, which was provided by a mixture of Federal mass transit funds and Commonwealth transportation bond issues.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==Train operations==\n[[File:Inbound Campello.JPG|thumb|An MBTA train at [[Campello (MBTA station)|Campello]] station inbound to South Station.]]\nLike most commuter railroads in the Northeastern United States, MBTA is a member of the [[Northeast Operating Rules Advisory Committee]] (NORAC) and uses the rulebook promulgated by that organization.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dms.ntsb.gov/public/58000-58499/58167/585157.pdf |title=NORAC Operating Rules |publisher=Northeast Operating Rules Advisory Committee |date=November 6, 2011 |edition=10 |via=National Transportation Safety Board |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203171210/http://dms.ntsb.gov/public/58000-58499/58167/585157.pdf |archivedate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Much of the MBTA Commuter Rail system is governed by NORAC rule 251, as the tracks are signalled for movement in one direction of travel only. During the 1990s, parts of the system, such as the Framingham/Worcester Line, were re-signalled to allow a more advanced mode of operations known as NORAC rule 261, which allows trains to operate in either direction on both tracks where double track is available. During the morning rush hour, both tracks can be simultaneously used for inbound traffic, allowing one train to make local stops while an express train overtakes the local train.<ref>{{cite web |author=Trahan, Tyler |title=The First T-Alert |url=http://iridethet.blogspot.com/2011/12/first-t-alert.html |date=December 9, 2011 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn each train, the cab car is attached at the end closest to the downtown Boston terminal station for the particular line (either North or South Station), and the locomotive is attached at the end farthest from the terminal station. On each train serving the North Station lines, the \"ADA\" coach used to carry mobility-limited persons is attached next to the locomotive, allowing level boarding at all suburban stations featuring mini-high platforms. On the other hand, on each train serving the South Station lines, the cab car also serves as the \"ADA\" coach. (The \"ADA\" coaches support compliance with the [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990]].)\n\nTrainlined doors that open automatically via central control are available on some equipment, but at low level platforms the conductor in each car must manually open a trap to allow passengers to descend via stairs onto the platform.\n\n[[Positive Train Control]] is scheduled to be implemented on the entire system per a federal mandate, which requires installation by the end of 2018 with the possibility of a two-year extension. {{As of|November 2015}}, the MBTA expects to complete PTC on the southside lines by December 2018, on the northside lines by March 2020, and an overlay for freight on the sections of [[Pan Am Railways]]' Freight Main Line which overlap MBTA territory by August 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Board_Meetings/FMCBPTCAward110215.pdf |title=Commuter Rail Positive Train Control (PTC) Project: Financial Management Control Board Presentation |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=November 2, 2015 |first=Gerard J. |last=Polcari |accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Future operations===\nIn November 2019, the MBTA Fiscal and Management Control Board voted to back plans to further electrify the Commuter Rail system and increase service along key corridors. The resolution in which the board passed instructs the MBTA to prepare to launch a pilot service along the Fairmount line and a portion of the Newburyport/Rockport line where Commuter Rail service would be increased and fares reduced to that of a rapid transit ticket. Both of those lines, as well as the Providence/Stoughton line, are also to be electrified under the plan. The projected cost of such plans were not immediately clear at the time of the board's vote, but projections range from $10.6 billion to $28.9 billion, depending upon the results of the pilot program and future possible expansion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/bostonomix/2019/11/04/mbta-regional-rail-electric-trains |title=MBTA Board Commits To Reimagined Commuter Rail System |publisher=WBUR |date=November 4, 2019 |first=Chris |last=Lisinski |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Planned expansions==\n<!-- EDITORIAL NOTE: When major updates are made to this section, be sure to also update the brief summary section in the main [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] article, which points to here. -->\n\n===South Station lines===\n{{Outdated|section|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:Foxboro MBTA station, Foxborough MA.jpg|thumb|right|Foxboro station is proposed as the terminus of a Franklin Line branch]]\nThe [[South Coast Rail]] project is proposed to extend commuter rail service to the South Coast cities of [[Taunton, Massachusetts|Taunton]], [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], and [[New Bedford]]. After previous service was discontinued in 1958, the project surfaced in the 1980s. A full planning process was held from 1990 until its suspension in 2002. Planning restarted from the beginning in 2007; the Final Environmental Impact Statement was issued in August 2013. Several separately-funded projects, such as bridge reconstructions, have been undertaken, including major tie replacement (beginning in November 2013), and $2.3 billion was appropriated to the project in an April 2014 state bill.<ref name=bill>{{cite web |url=https://malegislature.gov/Laws/SessionLaws/Acts/2014/Chapter79 |title=Session Laws: Chapter 79 of the Acts of 2014 |date=April 18, 2014 |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> However, full construction has been repeatedly delayed. Plans were changed in 2017 to have limited Phase 1 diesel service via the [[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] in 2022, with full electric service via Stoughton in 2030. The modified plan, which is expected to cost $3.42 billion, proved immediately controversial.<ref name=sharp>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/regionals/south/2017/06/16/sharp-differences-over-latest-plan-for-south-coast-rail/Vlmt4rC3DXy8Wo5gIJWLYI/story.html |title=Sharp differences over latest plan for South Coast Rail |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=June 16, 2017 |first=John |last=Laidler |accessdate=June 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA Providence Line extension to [[Wickford Junction (MBTA station)|Wickford Junction]], in [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island]] opened on April 23, 2012. The [[Rhode Island Department of Transportation]] is also studying the feasibility of serving existing Amtrak stations in [[Kingston (Amtrak station)|Kingston]] and [[Westerly (Amtrak station)|Westerly]] as well as constructing new stations in [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]], [[East Greenwich, Rhode Island|East Greenwich]], and [[Davisville, Rhode Island|West Davisville]]. Federal funding has also been provided for preliminary planning of a new station in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dot.ri.gov/engineering/intermod/index.asp#ComRail |title=Intermodal Planning |publisher=Rhode Island Department of Transportation |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726192250/http://www.dot.ri.gov/engineering/intermod/index.asp#ComRail |archivedate=July 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThere is also a proposal to extend the [[Middleborough/Lakeville Line]] to [[Wareham, Massachusetts|Wareham]] and eventually to [[Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts|Buzzards Bay]]. The [[CapeFLYER]] started service along this section to [[Hyannis (CCRTA station)|Hyannis]] on summer weekends in 2013.\n\nIn September 2013, the state announced plans to run [[diesel multiple unit]] (DMU) service between [[Back Bay (MBTA station)|Back Bay]] and the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] on [[Track 61 (Boston)|Track 61]] beginning in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/09/05/state-begin-innovative-rail-service-between-seaport-district-and-back-bay/oHUinYj30lzOV6KNCQUMEJ/story.html |title=State to begin innovative rail service between Seaport District and Back Bay |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Leung, Shirley |date=September 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, the MBTA announce it would purchase DMU self-propelled rail cars for the Fairmount Line with eventual expansion to five other lines, including Track 61, to be known as the [[Indigo Line]]. The planned DMU procurement was canceled in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727155548/http://www.bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2015/06/charlie_baker_derails_t_trains |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2015/06/charlie_baker_derails_t_trains |title=Charlie Baker derails T trains |archivedate=July 27, 2015 |newspaper=Boston Herald |last=Stout |first=Matt |date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> A new [[West Station (MBTA station)|West Station]], is planned to be built on the Framingham-Worcester line in the [[Beacon Park Yard]] site, where it may also connect to North Station via the [[Grand Junction Railroad]].<ref name=Annear>{{cite news|last=Annear|first=Steve|title=Take A Ride On The MBTA's 'New Indigo Line' In 2024|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2014/01/09/massdot-capital-plan-proposal/|accessdate=March 11, 2014|newspaper=[[Boston Magazine]]|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===North Station lines===\nThere is a proposal to build a South Salem station in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], to improve access to [[Salem State University]], as well as to extend Commuter Rail to [[Peabody, Massachusetts]] and [[Danvers, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Documents/North_Shore_Transit_Improvements/ExecSum.pdf |title=Draft North Shore Transit Improvements Project-MIS: Executive Summary |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=August 13, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113145925/http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Documents/North_Shore_Transit_Improvements/ExecSum.pdf |archivedate=November 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe former state Secretary of Transportation [[James Aloisi]] indicated in 2009 support for commuter service from Worcester to North Station via Clinton and Ayer, presumably along the [[Worcester, Nashua and Rochester Railroad]] right of way, owned by [[Pan Am Railways]] {{as of|2009|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20090428/NEWS/904280486/1052 |title=MBTA warns of cuts / Transportation future hot topic |author=Priyanka Dayal |newspaper=Worcester Telegram |date=April 28, 2009 |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the state of [[New Hampshire]] created the [[New Hampshire Rail Transit Authority]] and allocated money to build platforms at Nashua and Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.nh.gov/media/news/2007/072607rail.html |title=Governor Lynch Ceremonially Signs Law Supporting Development Of Commuter Rail in New Hampshire |date=July 27, 2007 |publisher=State of New Hampshire Governor's Office |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327002340/http://www.governor.nh.gov/media/news/2007/072607rail.html |archivedate=March 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA 2008 article in the ''[[Eagle Tribune]]'' claimed that Massachusetts is negotiating to buy property which has the potential to extend the Haverhill Line to [[Plaistow, New Hampshire]]. Funding is available, and Plaistow is potentially interested, but wants to better understand the potential drawbacks of being the location of the layover station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/punewshh/local_story_072061531.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731144451/http://www.eagletribune.com/punewshh/local_story_072061531.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2012 |title=Haverhill chamber chief supports train stop in Plaistow |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |author=Carey, Meghan |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/punewsnh/local_story_069070842.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729224256/http://www.eagletribune.com/punewsnh/local_story_069070842.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |title=Plaistow officials hopeful MBTA considers rail extension |author=Carey, Meghan |date=March 9, 2008 |newspaper=Eagle-Tribune |accessdate=August 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===North\u2013South Rail Link===\n{{main|North\u2013South Rail Link}}\nNo direct connection exists between the two downtown commuter rail terminals; to travel from one station to the other, passengers must use the [[MBTA subway]] or [[MBTA Bus|bus]] lines to make the connection. A [[North\u2013South Rail Link]] has been proposed to unite the two halves of the commuter rail system. For non-revenue transfers of equipment, the MBTA and Amtrak use the [[Grand Junction Railroad and Depot Company|Grand Junction Branch]].\n\n==Freight service==\n[[File:BostonSandandGravel.agr.jpg|thumb|left|Boston Sand and Gravel and tracks as seen from an MBTA train]]\nOn the North Side lines, as part of the original sale agreement, B&M and its successor [[Pan Am Railways]] (formerly Guilford Transportation Industries) retains \"perpetual and exclusive\" trackage rights for freight service. Pan Am provides freight service on those lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctps.org/bostonmpo/3_programs/1_transportation_plan/2030Tranplan_ch2c.pdf |title=2030 Transportation Plan Chapter 2: The Boston Region MPO and its Existing Transportation System (Part 3) |date=April 2007 |publisher=Boston Region Metropolitan Planning Organization |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717113751/http://www.ctps.org/bostonmpo/3_programs/1_transportation_plan/2030Tranplan_ch2c.pdf |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Boston Sand and Gravel]] has an agreement with Pan Am to operate its shortline [[New Hampshire Northcoast]] Railroad trains from [[Ossipee, New Hampshire]] to just north of Boston's North Station to supply aggregates to its plant on the Boston/Cambridge border.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonsand.com/nhnorthcoast.aspx |title=NH NORTHCOAST |publisher=Boston Sand & Gravel |year=2011 |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107073628/http://www.bostonsand.com/nhnorthcoast.aspx |archivedate=November 7, 2011 }}</ref> An occasional move occurs with run-through power from [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] to supply coal the Merrimack Station power plant in [[Bow, New Hampshire]], over the Fitchburg Line. The Haverhill and Fitchburg lines also host four to six Pan Am manifest freight trains per day.\n\nOn the South Side lines, [[CSX Transportation]] retains trackage rights over much of the former New Haven territory. Limited service is also provided by the [[Providence & Worcester Railroad]] on the Providence Line, principally from Central Falls (the intersection with its main line to Worcester) through Providence towards New Haven (although some freights go as far east as Attleboro before leaving the corridor).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwrr.com/PWmap3.html |title=P&W Map |publisher=Providence & Worcester Railroad |accessdate=October 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425081000/http://www.pwrr.com/PWmap3.html |archivedate=April 25, 2012 }}</ref> The [[Bay Colony Railroad]] provides a limited amount of service on some lines.\n\nCSXT used to provide intermodal, autorack, and general merchandise over the Worcester Line, a part of CSXT's Boston Line.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://csx.com/index.cfm/customers/maps/csx-system-map/ |title=CSX System Map |publisher=CSX Transportation |accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> This part of the Commuter Rail network could host over 12 mainline freight trains per day, including descendants of Conrail's expedited intermodal Trail Van trains. Currently most freight service terminates in Framingham, and a trainload facility in Westboro, with limited freight service east through [[Beacon Park Yard]] in Allston to a few local customers. In 2013 CSX moved its intermodal service from Beacon Park to an expanded yard in Worcester.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transportation.blog.state.ma.us/blog/2009/11/csx-rail-agreement-south-coast-rail-plans-move-forward.html |title=CSX Rail Agreement, South Coast Rail Plans Move Forward |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |date=November 25, 2009 |accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tg20130617\">{{cite news | url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20130617/NEWS/306179788/1237 | title=CSX project wrap-up means money for city | work=[[Telegram & Gazette]] | date=June 17, 2013 | accessdate=September 1, 2014 | author=Kotsopoulos, Nick}}</ref>\n\nOn its former Old Colony division, the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] (NYNH&H) essentially vacated its right of freight operations by abandoning the tracks in 1959. As MBTA rebuilt the tracks, it gained freight service rights, and those rights were franchised to [[Conrail]] (predecessor to CSX), which provided freight service on the former Old Colony division.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Art and architecture==\n{{see also|Arts on the Line}}\nAs parts of their Arts on the Line program, the MBTA has public art at certain commuter rail stations. Large sculptures and murals are present at South Station, Back Bay, and Lynn, while a number of other stations include historic information panels on station signs.<ref name=MBTAPubArt>{{cite web|title=Public Art in Transit: Over the Years|url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/art_collection/|website=mbta.com|publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|accessdate=June 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625094038/http://mbta.com/about_the_mbta/art_collection/|archive-date=June 25, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Railways}}\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Commuter rail in North America]]\n*[[List of Massachusetts railroads]]\n*[[Commuter rail in North America#List of North American commuter rail operators|List of North American commuter rail operators]]\n*[[List of suburban and commuter rail systems]]\n*[[List of United States commuter rail systems by ridership]]\n{{col-break|gap=10em}}\n*Other commuter rail operations in Massachusetts:\n**[[Cape Cod and Hyannis Railroad]] (defunct)\n**[[Connecticut River Line]] (proposed)\n**[[Hartford Line]]\n{{col-end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n*[http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/rail/ MBTA - Commuter Rail Schedules and Maps]\n*[http://www.keoliscs.com/ Keolis Commuter Services]\n*[http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ NETransit - MBTA Fleet Roster]\n\n{{MBTA}}\n{{Keolis}}\n{{Northeast Corridor navbox}}\n{{USCommRail}}\n