fraim Elimelech |last=Urbach\n|publisher=Arno |year= 1979\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=The Curse of Ham in the Early Modern Era: The Bible and the Justifications for Slavery\n|first=David M.\n|last=Whitford\n|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd\n|year=2009\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Assaf, S., 'Slavery and the Slave-Trade among the Jews during the Middle Ages', Zion 4 (1939), pp.&nbsp;91\u2013125 [slavery and the slave trade among the jews during the middle ages]\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/20/opinion/black-demagogues-and-pseudo-scholars.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=Black Demagogues and Pseudo-Scholars|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=December 23, 2012|author=Henry Louis Gates Jr.|date=1992-07-20}}\n* [http://www.nizkor.org/ftp.cgi/people/ftp.py?people//f/faber.eli/Slavery_and_the_Jews.001 Excerpts from ''Slavery and the Jews. A Historical Inquiry'' By Eli Faber]\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=15&letter=O#54 Jewish occupations] [[Jewish Encyclopedia]], 1906 ed.\n\n{{Jewish Encyclopedia}}\n{{Religion and slavery}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jewish Views On Slavery}}\n[[Category:Antisemitic canards]]\n[[Category:Criticism of Judaism|Slavery]]\n[[Category:Judaism and society|Slavery]]\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies|Slavery]]\n[[Category:Judaism and slavery]]\n[[Category:Slave trade]]\n[[Category:Point of view]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:2100:8d00:7948:ba7d:73cb:3561", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jewish_views_on_slavery"}
{"title_page": "Syed Iraq Raza Zaidi", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Syed Iraq Raza Zaidi|timestamp=20200409122606|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Syed Iraq Raza Zaidi|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\nProfessor Iraq Raza Zaidi born on August 6, 1955 in [[Sainthal, Uttar Pradesh]]; is an Indian [[Academician]], Researcher, [[Laureate]], [[Poet]], and Linguist currently serving as the Head of the Department, in [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].\nAlong with his regular position in Jamia Millia Islamia, Professor Zaidi also heads many other institutions across the globe including (but not limited to) All India Persian Teacher's Association, \nOn 15th August 2019, his name was nominated for the [[Maharshi Badrayan Vyas Samman]] president's award and certificate of honour for his substantial contribution in the field of Persian language.\n\n==<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jmi.ac.in/persian/faculty-members/Dr_Iraq_Raza_Zaidi-1463|title=Dr.Iraq Raza Zaidi, HOD Persian Dept. JMI|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> References==\n\n==<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192658|title=Dr.Iraq Raza Zaidi for president award certificate of honour|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> References==\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Syed Iraq Raza Zaidi|timestamp=20200409122606|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Syed Iraq Raza Zaidi|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\nProfessor Iraq Raza Zaidi born on August 6, 1955 in [[Sainthal, Uttar Pradesh]]; is an Indian [[Academician]], Researcher, [[Laureate]], [[Poet]], and Linguist currently serving as the Head of the Department, in [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].\nAlong with his regular position in Jamia Millia Islamia, Professor Zaidi also heads many other institutions across the globe including (but not limited to) All India Persian Teacher's Association, \nOn 15th August 2019, his name was nominated for the [[Maharshi Badrayan Vyas Samman]] president's award and certificate of honour for his substantial contribution in the field of Persian language.\n\n==<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jmi.ac.in/persian/faculty-members/Dr_Iraq_Raza_Zaidi-1463|title=Dr.Iraq Raza Zaidi, HOD Persian Dept. JMI|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> References==\n\n==<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192658|title=Dr.Iraq Raza Zaidifor president certificate of honour|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> References==\n", "name_user": "ShiaTheologists", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e{{Cite web|url=http://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192658|title=Dr.Iraq Raza Zaidifor president certificate of honour|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}} References", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syed_Iraq_Raza_Zaidi"}
{"title_page": "Maj. John Gilman House", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Maj. John Gilman House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Maj. John Gilman House, Exeter NH.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 25 Cass St., [[Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|42|59|3|N|70|57|16|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New Hampshire#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1738}}\n  | architecture = Georgian\n  | added = June 14, 1988\n  | area = {{convert|1.2|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 88000659<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Maj. John Gilman House''' is a historic house at 25 Cass Street in [[Exeter, New Hampshire]].  Built in 1738, it is a well-preserved example of a Georgian gambrel-roof house, further notable for its association with the locally prominent Gilman family.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=88000659}}|title=NRHP nomination for Maj. John Gilman House|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref>  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1988.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==Description and history==\nThe John Gilman House is located north of Exeter's commercial and civic downtown area, at the southest corner of Cass and Park Streets.  It is a 2-1/2 story wood frame structure, with a gambrel roof and clapboarded exterior.  Its main facade is five bays wide, with a central entrance flanked by pilasters and topped by a transom and gabled pediment.  Windows are topped by shallow projecting cornices on the ground floor, and butt against the eave on the second floor.  The windows themselves appear to be c. 1830 Greek Revival replacements, and are narrower and taller than typical Georgian windows.  The interior was subjected to a careful restoration of its 18th-century character in the 1960s.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\nThe house was built in 1738 by Colonel John Gilman for his son, also named John.  The elder Gilman lived in the nearby [[Gilman Garrison House]], in which his son was born.  It is one of only three gambrel-roofed houses to survive in the town from the Georgian period, and it is the least-altered of those.  The Gilmans, both father and son, were prominent in the local militia and town affairs.  Later residents included Thomas Odiorne, son-in-law of the younger Gilman, who was a successful merchant and manufacturer of equipment and parts for sailing ships.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\nMajor John Gilman held an enslaved African boy of fourteen years old, Caesar Nero Paul, who later accompanied him to the French and Indian Wars, then became a free man in 1771. Caesar married Lovey Rollins and was the father of noted Baptist minister Rev. [[Thomas Paul]]. His daughter Rhoda married noted black Revolutionary soldier [[Jude Hall]], and another was the mother of black Abolitionist poet [[James Monroe Whitfield]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New Hampshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilman, John, Maj., House}}\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1738]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Maj. John Gilman House\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Maj. John Gilman House, Exeter NH.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 25 Cass St., [[Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|42|59|3|N|70|57|16|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New Hampshire#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1738}}\n  | architecture = Georgian\n  | added = June 14, 1988\n  | area = {{convert|1.2|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 88000659<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Maj. John Gilman House''' is a historic house at 25 Cass Street in [[Exeter, New Hampshire]].  Built in 1738, it is a well-preserved example of a Georgian gambrel-roof house, further notable for its association with the locally prominent Gilman family.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=88000659}}|title=NRHP nomination for Maj. John Gilman House|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref>  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1988.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==Description and history==\nThe John Gilman House is located north of Exeter's commercial and civic downtown area, at the southest corner of Cass and Park Streets.  It is a 2-1/2 story wood frame structure, with a gambrel roof and clapboarded exterior.  Its main facade is five bays wide, with a central entrance flanked by pilasters and topped by a transom and gabled pediment.  Windows are topped by shallow projecting cornices on the ground floor, and butt against the eave on the second floor.  The windows themselves appear to be c. 1830 Greek Revival replacements, and are narrower and taller than typical Georgian windows.  The interior was subjected to a careful restoration of its 18th-century character in the 1960s.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\nThe house was built in 1738 by Colonel John Gilman for his son, also named John.  The elder Gilman lived in the nearby [[Gilman Garrison House]], in which his son was born.  It is one of only three gambrel-roofed houses to survive in the town from the Georgian period, and it is the least-altered of those.  The Gilmans, both father and son, were prominent in the local militia and town affairs.  Later residents included Thomas Odiorne, son-in-law of the younger Gilman, who was a successful merchant and manufacturer of equipment and parts for sailing ships.<ref name=NRHP/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New Hampshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilman, John, Maj., House}}\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1738]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n", "name_user": "Exchange33", "label": "safe", "comment": "added Caesar Paul history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maj._John_Gilman_House"}
